{"title_page": "Scott Pruitt", "text_new": "{{For|the race car driver|Scott Pruett}}\n{{short description|14th Administrator of the EPA}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Scott Pruitt\n| image = File:Scott_Pruitt,_EPA_official_portrait_(cropped).jpg\n| office = 14th [[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency]]\n| deputy = Andrew Wheeler\n| term_start = February 17, 2017\n| term_end = July 6, 2018\n| predecessor = [[Gina McCarthy]]\n| successor = [[Andrew R. Wheeler|Andrew Wheeler]]\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| office1 = 17th [[Attorney General of Oklahoma]]\n| governor1 = [[Mary Fallin]]\n| term_start1 = January 10, 2011\n| term_end1 = February 17, 2017\n| predecessor1 = [[Drew Edmondson]]\n| successor1 = [[Michael J. Hunter|Mike Hunter]]\n| office2    = Member of the<br>[[Oklahoma Senate]]\n| constituency2 = 54th district (1999\u20132003)<br>36th district (2003\u201307)\n| term_start2 = January 5, 1999\n| term_end2 = January 2, 2007\n| predecessor2 = [[Gerald Wright (politician)|Gerald Wright]]\n| successor2 = [[Bill Brown (American politician)|Bill Brown]]\n| birth_name = Edward Scott Pruitt<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbts.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2010/11/Catalog_directory_Aug2013.pdf|title=Southern Seminary Catalog \u2013 Directory, 2013\u20132014|publisher=|accessdate=June 6, 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|5|9}}\n| birth_place = [[Danville, Kentucky|Danville]], [[Kentucky]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = Marlyn Pruitt (1992\u2013present)\n| children = 2\n| education = [[University of Kentucky]]\n[[Georgetown College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of Tulsa]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n}}\n\n'''Edward Scott Pruitt''' (born May 9, 1968) is an American lawyer, lobbyist and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician from the state of [[Oklahoma]]. He served as the fourteenth [[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) from February 17, 2017, to July 6, 2018. He was nominated for the EPA position by President [[Donald Trump]] and was confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] to lead the EPA in a 52\u201346 vote. Pruitt [[Climate change denial|rejects]] the [[scientific consensus on climate change]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-ten-worst-things-scott-pruitts-epa-has-already-done|title=The Ten Worst Things Scott Pruitt's EPA Has Already Done|author=Jay Michaelson|date=December 29, 2017|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|access-date=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPruitt represented [[Tulsa County, Oklahoma|Tulsa]] and [[Wagoner County, Oklahoma|Wagoner]] counties in the [[Oklahoma Senate]] from 1998 until 2006.  In 2010, Pruitt was elected [[Attorney General of Oklahoma]]. In that role, he was pro-life, opposed [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|same-sex marriage]], the [[Affordable Care Act]], and [[environmental regulations]] as a self-described \"leading advocate against the EPA's activist agenda.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Brief biography of Attorney General Scott Pruitt|url=https://www.ok.gov/oag/Media/About_the_AG/|publisher=Oklahoma Office of the Attorney General E. Scott Pruitt|accessdate=February 4, 2017|archivedate=January 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108114336/https://www.ok.gov/oag/Media/About_the_AG/}}</ref> In his campaigns for [[Oklahoma Attorney General]], Pruitt received major corporate and employee [[campaign finance in the United States|campaign contributions]] from the [[fossil fuel industry]], taking in at least $215,574 between 2010 and 2014 even though he ran unopposed in the latter year. As Oklahoma's Attorney General, Pruitt sued the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] at least 14 times regarding the agency's actions. In 2012, Pruitt was elected as chairman of the Republican Attorneys General Association and re-elected for a second term in February 2013.\n\nBy July 2018, Pruitt was under at least 14 separate federal investigations by the [[Government Accountability Office]], the EPA inspector general, the [[Office of Management and Budget|White House Office of Management and Budget]], the [[United States Office of Special Counsel|U.S. Office of Special Counsel]], and two House committees over his spending habits, conflicts of interest, extreme secrecy, and management practices. Pruitt made frequent use of first-class travel as well as frequent charter and military flights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-environment/2019/05/16/epa-watchdog-suggests-agency-recover-p |title=EPA watchdog suggests agency recover $124,000 in Pruitt's 'excessive' travel expenses; Agency rejects the idea, calling 'cost recovery inappropriate' because officials had approved Pruitt's trips at the time |authors=Juliet Eilperin and Brady Dennis |date=May 16, 2019 |website=washingtonpost.com |publisher= |access-date=16 May 2019 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/ex-epa-chief-scott-pruitt-spent-nearly-124-000-excessive-n1006491 |title=Ex-EPA chief Scott Pruitt spent nearly $124,000 on 'excessive airfare,' agency says; The inspector general's report found there was not \"sufficient justification to support security concerns requiring the use of first- and business-class travel.\" |authors=Laura Strickler and Adiel Kaplan |date=16 May 2019 |website=nbcnews.com |publisher= |access-date=16 May 2019 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/16/politics/pruitt-airfare-inspector-general/index.html |title=Scott Pruitt wasted nearly $124,000 on first- and business-class travel, EPA IG says |author=Gregory Wallace |date=16 May 2019 |website=CNN |publisher= |access-date=16 May 2019 |quote=}}</ref>  As EPA administrator, Pruitt leased a condo in Washington, D.C., at a deeply discounted rate from a lobbyist whose clients were regulated by the EPA. Pruitt further caused ethics concerns by circumventing the White House and using a narrow provision of the Safe Drinking Water Act to autonomously give raises to his two closest aides of approximately $28,000 and $57,000 each, which were substantially higher than salaries paid to those in similar positions in the Obama administration, and which allowed both to avoid signing conflicts of interest pledges. By June 2018, amid a steady succession of revelations of misconduct, a growing chorus of conservatives had begun suggesting that Pruitt should resign. On July 5, 2018, Pruitt announced he would resign from office on July 6, leaving [[Andrew R. Wheeler]] as the acting head of the agency.<ref name=globe2018/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/05/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-resigns/index.html|title=EPA chief Scott Pruitt resigns amid ethics scandals|author1-link=Jeremy Diamond (journalist)|author1=Jeremy Diamond |author2=Eli Watkins |author3=Juana Summers|work=CNN|access-date=July 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/07/05/scott-pruitts-full-resignation-letter-to-president-trump.html|title=Scott Pruitt's full resignation letter to President Trump|date=July 5, 2018|work=Fox News|access-date=July 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPruitt was born in 1968 in [[Danville, Kentucky]], the eldest of three siblings,<ref name=\"EE\"/> and moved to Lexington as a boy. There, his father, Edward, owned steak houses and his mother, Linda Pruitt Warner,<ref name=\"LHL\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kentucky.com/news/local/counties/fayette-county/article119508878.html|title=Trump's pick to lead EPA grew up in Lexington, played baseball at Lafayette, UK|publisher=Lexington Herald Leader|author=Blackford, Linda|date=December 8, 2016}}</ref> was a homemaker.<ref name=\"EE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060047801|title=From 'The Possum' to EPA boss|publisher=E&E News|date=January 4, 2017|author=Bravender, Robin}}</ref><ref name=newyorker2april18>{{cite news|last1=Talbot|first1=Margaret|authorlink=Margaret Talbot|title=Scott Pruitt's Dirty Politics|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/04/02/scott-pruitts-dirty-politics|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=[[The New Yorker]]|issue=April 2, 2018}}</ref> He was a football and baseball player at [[Lafayette High School (Lexington, Kentucky)|Lafayette High School]], earning a baseball scholarship to the [[University of Kentucky]], where he played second base. After a year, he transferred to [[Georgetown College (Kentucky)|Georgetown College]] in Kentucky and graduated in 1990 with bachelor's degrees in political science and communications.<ref name=baseball>{{cite news|last1=Blackford|first1=Linda|title=Trump's pick to lead EPA grew up in Lexington, played baseball at Lafayette, UK|url=http://www.kentucky.com/news/local/counties/fayette-county/article119508878.html|accessdate=July 26, 2017|newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader|date=December 7, 2016}}</ref> He then moved to [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], where he attended the [[University of Tulsa College of Law]] and earned a [[Juris Doctor]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Alec|title=The Trump Cabinet: Who is Scott Pruitt?|url=https://lawstreetmedia.com/blogs/politics-blog/the-trump-cabinet-scott-pruitt/|accessdate=February 7, 2017|publisher=Law Street|date=December 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Legal experience==\n\nAfter law school Pruitt started a solo legal practice in Tulsa that he named \"Christian Legal Services,\" which focused on defending Christians in religious liberty cases.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Michaelson|first1=Jay|title=Trump's EPA Pick Blends Conservative Christianity with Anti-Environmental Activism|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trumps-epa-pick-blends-conservative-christianity-with-anti-environmental-activism|accessdate=April 6, 2018|website=Daily Beast|date=January 23, 2017}}</ref>  Pruitt worked as a lawyer for five years before running for state senate.\n\n==Early career==\n\nPruitt was elected to the [[Oklahoma Senate]] in 1998, representing [[Tulsa County, Oklahoma|Tulsa]] and [[Wagoner County, Oklahoma|Wagoner]] counties.<ref name=\"HistoricMembers\">{{cite web | title=Historic Members | url=http://www.oksenate.gov/Senators/# | publisher=Oklahoma State Senate | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> In 1999 and again in 2005, Pruitt introduced legislation to establish fathers' \"property rights\" over unborn fetuses, which meant that a pregnant woman would be required to get the consent of the father prior to an abortion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/scott-pruitt-abortion_us_5b06ce55e4b05f0fc845a4aa|title=Scott Pruitt Twice Introduced Anti-Abortion Bills Giving Men 'Property Rights' Over Fetuses|last=Kaufman|first=Alexander C.|date=May 24, 2018|work=Huffington Post|access-date=May 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/environment/2018/05/scott-pruitt-tried-to-give-men-property-rights-over-fetuses/|title=Scott Pruitt tried to give men \"property rights\" over fetuses|work=Mother Jones|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> After two years in the Senate, Pruitt was selected to serve as the Republican whip from 2001 to 2003. He was then selected to serve as the Republican Assistant Floor Leader, a position he held until he left the Senate in 2006.<ref name=ballotpedia>{{cite web | url=https://ballotpedia.org/Scott_Pruitt | title=Scott Pruitt \u2013 Ballotpedia | publisher=}}</ref> During that time he also sat as the chair of a task force for the [[American Legislative Exchange Council]].<ref name=governing2003>{{cite news|url=http://www.governing.com/topics/politics/What-Makes-Alec-Smart.html|title=What Makes Alec Smart?|date=October 2003|work=[[Governing (magazine)|Governing]]|first=Alan|last=Greenblatt}}</ref>  There, he worked to put limits on workers' compensation and sponsored a reform bill that sought to impose drug tests on workers who were involved in job injuries or accidents.<ref name=newyorker2april18/>\n\nIn 2001, while a freshman state legislator, Pruitt sought his party's nomination to succeed [[Steve Largent]] as the representative for [[Oklahoma's 1st congressional district]] but was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite web|title=District 1: Previous Election Results|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/elections/OK/districts/OK01/profile/|website=Oklahoma: 2016 Election Center|publisher=The Washington Times|accessdate=February 7, 2017}}</ref>  In 2003, after his unsuccessful congressional campaign, Pruitt bought a share in a Triple-A baseball team, the Oklahoma City RedHawks, partnering with major Republican donor [[Robert A. Funk]] (reportedly for $11.5 million).<ref name=newyorker2april18/>  Pruitt, whose annual salary as a state senator was $38,400, financed his part of the purchase with a loan from SpiritBank.<ref name=newyorker2april18/>  In 2010, they sold the team for an undisclosed profit.<ref name=newyorker2april18/>\n\nIn October 2003, while a state senator, Pruitt purchased a home in Oklahoma City through a [[shell company]], Capitol House L.L.C., in which six partners held equal shares. The buyers included lobbyist Justin Whitefield, healthcare executive Jon Jiles, Robert Funk (who was Pruitt's PAC chairman), and attorney Ken Wagner. The home was purchased at about a $100,000 discount from its purchase price of a year earlier and included its furnishings. The seller was Marsha Lindsey, a lobbyist who advocated on behalf of a telecommunications company. Lindsey's loss was partly offset by her employer's retirement package. Pruitt and Whitefield both lived at the home while on business in the state capital. At the time, Whitefield was a registered lobbyist for industry-aligned groups that sought legislative changes to Oklahoma's [[workers' compensation]] laws; Pruitt was the major legislative supporter of these efforts. The home was sold by the L.L.C. in 2005, for $470,000. Pruitt failed to publicly disclose his financial relationships with Whitefield and the others, which were revealed by the press in 2018.<ref>Steve Eder & Hiroko Tabuchi [https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/03/us/scott-pruitt-lobbyist-house.html Pruitt's Coziness With Lobbyists Includes Secretly Buying a House With One], ''New York Times'' (May 3, 2018).</ref> In 2017, Wagner was hired by Pruitt as the EPA's state and regional affairs adviser.<ref>[https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060053058 Pruitt's friend joins agency as senior adviser], ''[[E&E News]]'', Kevin Bogardus and Mike Soraghan, April 13, 2017. Retrieved May 5, 2018.</ref>\n\n==Oklahoma Attorney General==\n{{See also|Oklahoma state elections, 2006#Lieutenant governor|Oklahoma state elections, 2010#Attorney General|Oklahoma elections, 2014#Attorney General}}\nIn 2006 Pruitt sought the Republican nomination to replace outgoing Republican [[Mary Fallin]] as [[Lieutenant Governor of Oklahoma]].  He was unsuccessful; Fallin later won the gubernatorial election and is the incumbent [[Governor of Oklahoma|Governor]].\nIn 2010, Pruitt again ran for the position of Attorney General of Oklahoma. He won the Republican primary on July 27, 2010, with 56.05% of the vote, defeating Ryan Leonard.<ref>{{cite web | title=Summary Results \u2013 Primary Election \u2013 July 27, 2010 | url=https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/10pri.html | publisher=Oklahoma State Election Board | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Pruitt went on to defeat the Democratic nominee, [[Oklahoma City]] defense attorney Jim Priest, in the November 2, 2010, general election with 65.11% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web | title=Summary Results \u2013 General Election \u2013 November 2, 2010 | url=https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/10gen.html | publisher=Oklahoma State Election Board | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref>  In 2014 Pruitt ran unopposed in both the primary and general elections.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Krehbiel | first1=Randy | title=Pruitt Re-Election Campaign Raised $300,000 After it Learned He Would Have No Opponent | url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/government/pruitt-re-election-campaign-raised-after-it-learned-he-would/article_74bdafd2-8020-5fc5-aaa9-5e6694c01589.html | date=December 16, 2014 | website=tulsaworld.com | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nAfter winning election in 2010, Pruitt dissolved the Environmental Protection Unit in the Attorney General's office.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pooley|first1=Eric|title=Donald Trump's EPA Pick Imperils Science\u2014And Earth|url=http://time.com/4635162/scott-pruitt-science-denial/|accessdate=February 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Dennis|first1=Brady|last2=Weigel|first2=David|title=EPA nominee Scott Pruitt won't say if he would recuse himself from his own lawsuits against the agency|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/can-the-epas-main-antagonist-become-its-next-leader/2017/01/17/d24308ca-dcf7-11e6-ad42-f3375f271c9c_story.html|website=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=February 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Washington|first1=Wayne|title=Florida congressman gets little traction on legislation to abolish EPA|url=http://www.mypalmbeachpost.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/florida-congressman-gets-little-traction-legislation-abolish-epa/eRqNfdiat9JEoo1E4O0xHM/|work=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|accessdate=February 15, 2017}}</ref> He stated a desire to increase operational efficiency and shifted the attorneys responsible for environmental protection to the Attorney General's Public Protection Unit and the Solicitor General's Unit. Pruitt stated that \"the [[Oklahoma Department of Environmental Quality]] \u2013 not the Office of Attorney General \u2013 has primary responsibility for implementing and enforcing environmental laws in Oklahoma.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Hearing entitled, \"Nomination of Attorney General Scott Pruitt to be Administrator of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency\"|url=https://www.epw.senate.gov/public/_cache/files/6d95005c-bd1a-4779-af7e-be831db6866a/scott-pruitt-qfr-responses-01.18.2017.pdf|publisher=Senate Environment and Public Works Committee|accessdate=February 15, 2017|date=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPruitt instead created a \"Federalism Unit\" in the Attorney General's office dedicated to fighting President [[Barack Obama]]'s regulatory agenda and suing the administration over its immigration policy, the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], and the [[Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]].<ref name=\"WashPo8Dec\">{{cite news | last1=Mooney| first1=Chris | last2=Dennis | first2=Brady | last3=Mufson | first3=Steven|title=Trump names Scott Pruitt, Oklahoma attorney general suing EPA on climate change, to head the EPA | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2016/12/07/trump-names-scott-pruitt-oklahoma-attorney-general-suing-epa-on-climate-change-to-head-the-epa/ | accessdate=December 9, 2016 | work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=December 8, 2016|page=A1}}</ref>\n\nPruitt was successful in raising campaign contributions from the energy industry, helping him to become chairman of the Republican Attorneys General Association.<ref name=NYT8Dec/> The [[oil and gas industry]] contributed over $300,000 to Pruitt's campaigns over the years.<ref name=\"300K\">{{cite web|last1=Dennis|first1=Brady|title=Judge orders EPA nominee Pruitt to release emails with oil, gas, coal industry|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/politics/ct-scott-pruitt-epa-emails-20170216-story.html|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Pruitt kept Oklahoma out of the [[2010 United States foreclosure crisis#National Mortgage Settlement|mortgage settlement]] reached by 49 other states with five national lenders ([[Ally Financial]]/GMAC, [[Bank of America]], [[Citigroup|Citi]], [[JPMorgan Chase]], and [[Wells Fargo]]), with Pruitt citing differing philosophies of government.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://newsok.com/oklahoma-is-lone-maverick-in-national-mortgage-settlement-signed-by-49-states/article/3647630|title=Oklahoma is lone maverick in national mortgage settlement signed by 49 states | work=[[The Oklahoman]] | accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Pruitt brought a lawsuit targeting the Affordable Care Act, ''Oklahoma [[ex rel.]] E. Scott Pruitt v. Burwell'', alleging that federal cost-sharing subsidies were not authorized by the Act.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://newsok.com/lawsuits-by-oklahoma-attorney-general-scott-pruitt-others-challenge-obamacare-subsidies/article/3911239 | title=Lawsuits by Oklahoma Attorney General Scott Pruitt, others challenge Obamacare subsidies|work=The Oklahoman|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Allen\">Silas Allen, [http://newsok.com/lawsuits-by-oklahoma-attorney-general-scott-pruitt-others-challenge-obamacare-subsidies/article/3911239 Scott Pruitt was first state AG to challenge Obamacare subsidies], ''Oklahoman'' (December 7, 2016).</ref> In ''[[King v. Burwell]]'' (2015), a decision addressing identical claims brought by other Republican attorneys general,<ref>Chris Casteel, [http://newsok.com/article/5387985 U.S. Supreme Court won't add Oklahoma case to crucial Affordable Care Act review], ''Oklahoman'' (January 27, 2015).</ref><ref>Lisa Schencker, [http://www.modernhealthcare.com/article/20150126/NEWS/301269848 Supreme Court rejects second insurance subsidy case, focus to remain on King v. Burwell], ''Modern Healthcare'' (January 26, 2015).</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=McIntyre | first=Adrianna | date=October 1, 2014 | title=High court declines to review Oklahoma case against Affordable Care Act | url=https://www.vox.com/2014/10/1/6875579/another-court-strikes-down-obamacare-subsidies-in-36-states |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] | publisher =[[Vox Media]]}}</ref> the Supreme Court upheld the federal subsidies, holding that they were authorized under the Act.<ref>Adam Liptak, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/26/us/obamacare-supreme-court.html Supreme Court Allows Nationwide Health Care Subsidies], ''New York Times'' (June 25, 2015).</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Harold Hamm]], CEO of [[Continental Resources]], co-chaired Pruitt's reelection campaign.<ref name=NYT8Dec>{{cite news | last1=Coral Davenport | last2=Eric Lipton|title=Trump Picks Scott Pruitt, Climate Change Denialist, to Lead E.P.A.| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/07/us/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-trump.html | accessdate=December 9, 2016 | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=December 8, 2016 | ref=NYT8Dec | page=A1}}</ref> Pruitt ran unopposed in the 2014 primary election and won the November 2014 election for a new term as Attorney General.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ballotpedia.org/Oklahoma_Attorney_General_election,_2014|title=Oklahoma Attorney General election, 2014|publisher=Ballotpedia.org|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref> Pruitt then jointly filed a lawsuit against a federal regulation alongside the [[Oklahoma Gas & Electric]] and an energy industry group funded by Hamm.<ref name=NYT8Dec/>\n\nPruitt's office sued the EPA to block its [[Clean Power Plan]] and [[Waters of the United States]] rule.<ref name=WashPo8Dec/> Pruitt also sued the EPA on behalf of Oklahoma utilities unwilling to take on the burdens of additional regulation of their coal-fired plants, and criticized the agency in a congressional hearing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/oklahoma-attorney-general-scott-pruitt-criticizes-epa-at-congressional-hearing/article/3904818|title=Oklahoma Attorney General Scott Pruitt criticizes EPA at congressional hearing|work=The Oklahoman|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stateimpact.npr.org/oklahoma/2013/10/03/an-insiders-guide-to-oklahoma-attorney-general-scott-pruitts-war-with-the-epa/|title=An Insider's Guide to Oklahoma Attorney General Scott Pruitt's War With the EPA|work=StateImpact Oklahoma|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref> As of June 2014, all of Pruitt's lawsuits against the EPA had failed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stateimpact.npr.org/oklahoma/2014/06/12/court-losses-wont-deter-attorney-general-scott-pruitt-in-his-fight-with-the-epa/|title=Court Losses Won't Deter Attorney General Scott Pruitt In His Fight With The EPA|work=StateImpact Oklahoma|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref> By January 2017, Pruitt had sued the EPA 13 times.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mosbergen|first1=Dominique|title=Scott Pruitt Has Sued The Environmental Protection Agency 13 Times. Now He Wants To Lead It.|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/scott-pruitt-environmental-protection-agency_us_5878ad15e4b0b3c7a7b0c29c|accessdate=February 7, 2017|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=January 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Pruitt supported the Oklahoma legislature's bid to join four other states trying to restrict [[medical abortions]] by limiting or banning off-label uses of drugs, via House Bill 1970. After the state Supreme Court upheld a lower court's ruling that the abortion law was unconstitutional, Pruitt requested that the [[United States Supreme Court]] review the case. Pruitt was unhappy with the [[United States Supreme Court]]'s rejection of the Oklahoma case.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.newson6.com/story/23134460/attorney-general-files-brief-in-supreme-court-review-of-oklahoma-abortion-law|title=Attorney General Supports Supreme Court Review of Oklahoma Abortion Law|publisher=Newson6.com|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.krmg.com/news/news/local/okla-ag-pruitt-reacts-abortion-ruling/nbhCx/ | title=Okla. AG Pruitt reacts to abortion ruling|publisher=Krmg.com|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, Pruitt maintained that the Supreme Court's decision to strike down a provision of [[DOMA]], a federal law that denied federal benefits to homosexual married couples did not affect Oklahoma's laws on the subject.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.krmg.com/news/news/local/attorney-general-says-supreme-court-gay-rights-rul/nYWrz/|title=Attorney General says Supreme Court ruling doesn't affect Okla. | publisher=Krmg.com |date=June 26, 2013| accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Washington D.C. watchdog organization [[Campaign for Accountability]] sued Pruitt's successor as Oklahoma Attorney General for the failure of the office to release documentation that had been withheld from the public concerning corruption allegations involving the management of the Tar Creek Reclamation Superfund lead-contaminated waste site near [[Miami, Oklahoma]]. In 2014, Pruitt asked Oklahoma's State Auditor and Inspector Gary Jones to audit the financial corruption by contractors performing the cleanup. Pruitt blocked Jones from following his intention to release the audit results.<ref>[https://www.eenews.net/greenwire/stories/1060067351/ Watchdogs sue for Okla. audit Pruitt withheld], ''[[Environment & Energy Publishing|E&E News]]'', Mike Soraghan, November 27, 2017. Retrieved November 28, 2017.</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2014, Pruitt joined a lawsuit targeting California's prohibition on the sale of eggs laid by caged hens kept in conditions more restrictive than those approved by California voters. Less than a week later, Pruitt announced that he would investigate the [[Humane Society of the United States]], one of the principal proponents of the California law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oklahomafarmreport.com/wire/news/2014/03/06793_PruittCaliforniaLawsuit03072014_052320.php|title=Oklahoma Farm Report \u2013 Oklahoma Attorney General Pruitt Joins Other States in Egg Lawsuit Against California|publisher=Oklahoma Farm Report |date=March 7, 2014|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/homepagelatest/state-ag-s-office-issues-alert-against-humane-society-of/article_8924aaa0-aa4f-11e3-90a2-001a4bcf6878.html|title=State AG's office issues alert against Humane Society of the United States|work=[[Tulsa World]]|accessdate=January 5, 2015 |first=Randy |last=Krehbiel |date=March 12, 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, a California judge dismissed the lawsuit, rejecting the arguments of Pruitt and the other attorneys-general concerning [[California's Proposition 2]], a 2008 ballot initiative. Judge [[Kimberly Mueller]] ruled that Oklahoma and the other states lacked legal standing to sue on behalf of their residents and that Pruitt and other plaintiffs were representing the interests of egg farmers, rather than \"a substantial statement of their populations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.sfgate.com/food/article/Judge-tosses-suit-by-6-states-over-California-law-5797844.php|title=Judge tosses suit by 6 states over California law on eggs|work=SFGate|accessdate=January 5, 2015 |first=Bob |last=Egelko |date= October 2, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.politico.com/tipsheets/morning-agriculture/2014/10/lawsuit-against-california-egg-law-dismissed-fda-report-stokes-debate-over-antibiotics-us-revokes-special-treatment-for-canadian-produce-212543 | title=Lawsuit against California egg law dismissed \u2013 FDA report stokes debate over antibiotics \u2013 U.S. revokes special treatment for Canadian produce | first1=Jason |last1=Huffman | work=[[Politico]]|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.sacbee.com/2014/10/02/6757006/judge-tosses-lawsuit-challenging.html | title=Judge tosses lawsuit challenging California egg laws|work=sacbee|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, an Oklahoma trial court found the state's execution drug supply law was unconstitutional, and after the [[Oklahoma Court of Criminal Appeals]] refused to order a stop to executions, the [[Oklahoma Supreme Court]] did.<ref name=theatlantic2015june>{{cite news|last1=Stern|first1=Jeffrey E.|title=The Cruel and Unusual Execution of Clayton Lockett|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2015/06/execution-clayton-lockett/392069/|accessdate=April 5, 2017|work=[[The Atlantic]]|issue=June 2015}}</ref>  Pruitt then filed a motion arguing that the Supreme Court was acting outside its authority, complaining it was causing a \"constitutional crisis\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eckholm|first1=Erik|title=Execution Case Roils Oklahoma Courts|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/23/us/legal-clashes-continue-in-oklahoma-lethal-injection-case.html|accessdate=April 5, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 23, 2014|page=A15}}</ref>  After the Supreme Court refused Pruitt's motion, Governor [[Mary Fallin]] faced conflicting court orders, so she issued a declaration rejecting the Supreme Court's authority and scheduling executions.<ref name=theatlantic2015june/>  After the state then botched the [[execution of Clayton Lockett]], and the U.S. Supreme Court subsequently approved of Oklahoma's method in ''[[Glossip v. Gross]]'', Pruitt asked to delay all scheduled executions in Oklahoma upon discovering executioners had accidentally used the wrong drug in a lethal injection.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Segura|first1=Liliana|last2=Smith|first2=Jordan|title=OKLAHOMA'S INSANE RUSH TO EXECUTE|url=https://theintercept.com/2016/05/24/oklahomas-insane-rush-to-execute/|accessdate=April 5, 2017|work=[[The Intercept]]|date=May 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPruitt expressed his dissatisfaction when a federal court ruled that Oklahoma's voter-approved amendment in 2004 to the [[Oklahoma State Constitution]] that defined marriage as only the union of one man and one woman was a violation of the [[U.S. Constitution]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/01/14/oklahoma-gay-marriage-ban/4480277/|title=Federal judge strikes down Okla. same-sex marriage ban | author=Michael Winter | date=January 14, 2014|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref> In October 2014, Pruitt criticized the Supreme Court's refusal to hear Oklahoma's appeal in the definition of marriage case.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ktul.com/story/26717916/attorney-general-scott-pruitt-statement-on-same-sex-marriage-decision | title=Attorney General Scott Pruitt Statement on Same-Sex Marriage Decision | publisher=Ktul.com | accessdate=January 5, 2015 |first=Nathan |last=Altadonna |date=October 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, after the Oklahoma Supreme Court blocked the enforcement of two abortion-related laws until after their constitutionality was litigated (which could take up to a year or more), Pruitt's office communicated the Attorney General's intention to support their implementation and enforcement.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://newsok.com/oklahoma-supreme-court-puts-on-hold-two-abortion-laws-pending-constitutional-challenges/article/5363467 | title=Oklahoma Supreme Court puts on hold two abortion laws pending constitutional challenges | work=The Oklahoman|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jurist.org/paperchase/2014/11/oklahoma-supreme-court-blocks-enforcement-of-abortion-laws.php | title=Oklahoma Supreme Court blocks enforcement of abortion laws | author=William Helbling | date=November 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn December 7, 2014, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published a front-page story highlighting that Pruitt had used his office's stationery to send form letters written by energy industry lobbyists to federal agencies during [[public comment]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=[[Eric Lipton]]|title=Energy Firms in Secretive Alliance With Attorneys General|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/07/us/politics/energy-firms-in-secretive-alliance-with-attorneys-general.html|accessdate=December 9, 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 7, 2014|page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Pruitt wrote a letter to school superintendents stating that schools can lawfully allow the dissemination of religious literature on campus.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eger|first1=Andrea|title=Oklahoma Attorney General Scott Pruitt defends Bible distribution in schools, says 'religious freedoms are under attack'| url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/education/oklahoma-attorney-general-scott-pruitt-defends-bible-distribution-in-schools/article_592d20aa-2c46-51f6-a3fb-f11480542217.html | accessdate=April 18, 2015|newspaper=[[Tulsa World]]|date=April 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the [[Oklahoma Supreme Court]] rejected Pruitt's defense of the new [[Ten Commandments Monument (Oklahoma City)|Ten Commandments Monument]] on the [[Oklahoma State Capitol]] grounds.<ref name=newyorker2april18/>\n\nIn the Op-Ed co-written with Luther Strange in May 2016, Pruitt contended, \"...our job is to hold the EPA accountable to the laws that created it and to fulfill our statutory duties ...\" \"We will continue to pursue those goals and to present our arguments in the courts and in the public square, treating our opponents with the respect they deserve. But we call upon them to press those beliefs through debate, not through governmental intimidation of those who disagree with them. Few things could be more un-American.\"<ref name=Strange />\n\nIn 2016, the U.S. Supreme Court refused to hear Pruitt's [[original jurisdiction of the Supreme Court of the United States|original lawsuit]] against the legalization of [[cannabis in Colorado]].<ref name=newyorker2april18/><ref>{{cite web|title=Nebraska and Oklahoma v. Colorado|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/nebraska-and-oklahoma-v-colorado/|website=[[SCOTUSblog]]|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the organization Oklahomans for Health collected the legally required number of signatures for a referendum ballot on the legalization of medical marijuana, in August 2016, Pruitt's office moved to rewrite the ballot title, but not in time for the November 2016 election. The measure appeared on the 2018 ballot; Question 788 passed with 57% voting \"yes.\"<ref>{{cite news| work=[[KFOR-TV|KFOR]].com | title=\"This is a huge hurdle\", state officials will decide whether 67,000 signatures on medical marijuana petition make ballot| url=http://kfor.com/2016/08/24/this-is-a-huge-hurdle-state-officials-will-decide-whether-67000-signatures-on-medical-marijuana-petition-make-ballot/}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Oklahoma Medical Marijuana Legalization Initiative, State Question 788 (2018) | work=[[Ballotpedia]]| url=https://ballotpedia.org/Oklahoma_Medical_Marijuana_Legalization_Initiative,_State_Question_788_(2018)|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPruitt was an advisor to the [[Jeb Bush presidential campaign, 2016]]. In February 2016, he said that [[Donald Trump]] would be \"more abusive to the Constitution than Barack Obama\".<ref name=newyorker2april18/>\n\n[[File:Gina Loudon & Scott Pruitt (32775218220).jpg|thumb|Pruitt at the CPAC in February 2017]]\nIn February 2017, Pruitt was ordered by the Oklahoma District Court to release thousands of emails of communication with fossil fuel industries in order to comply with [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] requests filed over a two-year period by the liberal watchdog group [[Center for Media and Democracy]].<ref name=\"300K\"/>\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' reported in July 2017 that emails and other records released by the Oklahoma attorney general's office showed a close relationship between Pruitt and various [[Political activities of the Koch brothers|Koch brothers-backed]] advocacy groups, including the [[American Legislative Exchange Council]].<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/> The documents showed that while serving as Oklahoma attorney general, Pruitt \"acted in close concert with oil and gas companies to challenge environmental regulations, even putting his letterhead to a complaint filed by one firm, [[Devon Energy]].\"<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/>  Devon has since benefited from policies implemented by Pruitt.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/20/business/energy-environment/devon-energy.html|title=How Rollbacks at Scott Pruitt's E.P.A. Are a Boon to Oil and Gas|last1=Tabuchi|first1=Hiroko|date=May 21, 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 28, 2018|last2=Lipton|first2=Eric|page=A1}}</ref>  Emails showed that [[American Fuel and Petrochemical Manufacturers]] \"provided Pruitt's office with template language to oppose ozone limits and the renewable fuel standard program in 2013.\"<ref name=\"theguardian.com\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/3472961-2013-Pruitt-and-American-Fuel-and-Petrochemical.html|title=Renewable Fuel Standard \u2013 Background Information|date=July 13, 2013|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency ==\n=== Nomination and confirmation ===\n[[File:Stop Pruitt, Rally To Oppose EPA Nominee Scott Pruitt (32119365773).jpg|thumb|Stop Pruitt sign, at a rally to oppose his nomination]]\nOn December 7, 2016, President-elect [[Donald Trump]] announced his intention to nominate Pruitt as the [[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency]].<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-epa-idUSKBN13W2HE|title=Trump to tap Oklahoma attorney general to lead EPA: transition team|date=December 7, 2016|work=Reuters}}</ref> President-elect Trump said that the EPA had an \"anti-energy agenda that has destroyed millions of jobs\" and that Pruitt, \"the highly respected Attorney General from the state of Oklahoma, will reverse this trend and restore the EPA's essential mission of keeping our air and our water clean and safe.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In response to the nomination, Pruitt said, \"I intend to run this agency in a way that fosters both responsible protection of the environment and freedom for American businesses.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/2016/12/07/donald-trump-scott-pruitt-environmental-protection-agency/95104512/ |title=Scott Pruitt, Trump's pick to head the EPA, has sued the EPA |last=Jackson |first=David}}</ref>\n\nPruitt was endorsed by the [[American Legislative Exchange Council]] (ALEC).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alec.org/article/attorney-general-scott-pruitt-selected-to-run-epa/|title=Attorney General Scott Pruitt Selected to Run EPA|last1=Eick|first1=John|website=American Legislative Exchange Council|accessdate=July 26, 2017}}</ref> Following Pruitt's nomination hearing, Republican Senator [[John Barrasso]] stated that \"Pruitt ... has demonstrated his qualifications to lead the EPA.\" West Virginia Attorney General [[Patrick Morrisey]], who worked with Pruitt on multiple cases, said of Pruitt that \"He cares passionately about the rule of law\" and that \"All the actions he's been involved in are rooted in the firm belief that what the [Obama] administration was doing was unlawful.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nMany science advocates and environmentalists voiced concerns about Pruitt's nomination. [[Gene Karpinski]], the president of the [[League of Conservation Voters]] said that Pruitt's past actions as Oklahoma AG made the nomination \"like the fox guarding the henhouse ... Time and again, he has fought to pad the profits of Big Polluters at the expense of public health.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-epa-idUSKBN13W2HE|title=Trump to pick foe of Obama climate agenda to run EPA -source|date=December 7, 2016|work=Reuters|author=Valerie Volcovici and David Shepardson}}</ref> Ken Kimmell, president of the [[Union of Concerned Scientists]], has said, \"Pruitt's record gives us no reason to believe that he will vigorously hold polluters accountable or enforce the law ... everything we do know makes it clear that he can't and won't do the job.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/02/us/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-senate.html?_r=0|title=Scott Pruitt, Trump's E.P.A. Pick, Is Approved by Senate Committee|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 5, 2017}}</ref> Saying that Pruitt had deliberately given misleading information about his position on the regulation of mercury emissions, a spokesperson from the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] said, \"It is a serious matter to give misleading testimony to Senators during a confirmation hearing.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article128535064.html#storylink=cpy|title=Trump's EPA pick gets a boost but is still opposed by Senate Democrats|work=mcclatchydc|access-date=February 28, 2017}}</ref> 447 former EPA employees penned a joint letter to oppose Pruitt's nomination, arguing that his lawsuits against the EPA \"strongly suggest that he does not share the vision or agree with the underlying principles of our environmental laws\" and that they believed that he had not \"put the public's welfare ahead of private interests\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/318081-former-epa-employees-urge-senate-to-oppose-pruitt|title=Former EPA employees urge Senate to oppose Pruitt|last1=Henry|first1=Devin|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=February 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSenate Democrats unsuccessfully attempted to delay a vote until after the release of a batch of emails ordered by an Oklahoma judge.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite web|title=New EPA head Scott Pruitt's emails reveal close ties with fossil fuel interests|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/feb/22/scott-pruitt-emails-oklahoma-fossil-fuels-koch-brothers|website=The Guardian|accessdate=July 26, 2017}}</ref> On February 17, 2017, the Senate confirmed Pruitt, by a vote of 52\u201346, to be the [[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency]].<ref>{{cite web | last1=Chakraborty | first1=Barnini | title=Pruitt Narrowly Confirmed to Head EPA Over Democratic Objections | url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/02/17/pruitt-narrowly-confirmed-to-head-epa-over-democratic-objections.html | date=February 17, 2017 | publisher=[[Fox News]] | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Scott Pruitt: Controversial Trump Environment Nominee Sworn In | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39010374 | date=February 18, 2017 | work=BBC News | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> The vote was mostly along party lines, with Republican [[Susan Collins]] voting against, and Democrats [[Joe Manchin]] and [[Heidi Heitkamp]] voting in favor (Republican [[John McCain]] and Democrat [[Joe Donnelly]] did not vote).<ref>{{cite web | title=U.S. Senate: Roll Call Vote | url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=115&session=1&vote=00071 | date=February 17, 2017 | website=senate.gov | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Pruitt was sworn in the same day by Supreme Court Justice [[Samuel Alito]].<ref>{{cite news | last1=Boyer | first1=Dave | title=Scott Pruitt Sworn in as EPA Administrator | url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/feb/17/scott-pruitt-sworn-in-as-epa-administrator/ | date=February 17, 2017 | work=[[The Washington Times]] | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure as EPA Administrator ===\nAt the end of 2017, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' summarized Pruitt's leadership of the EPA in 2017 as follows:\n\n<blockquote>In legal maneuvers and executive actions, in public speeches and closed-door meetings with industry groups, he has moved to shrink the agency's reach, alter its focus, and pause or reverse numerous environmental rules. The effect has been to steer the EPA in the direction sought by those being regulated. Along the way, Pruitt has begun to dismantle former president [[Barack Obama]]'s environmental legacy, halting the agency's efforts to combat climate change and to shift the nation away from its reliance on [[fossil fuel]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/under-scott-pruitt-a-year-of-tumult-and-transformation-at-epa/2017/12/26/f93d1262-e017-11e7-8679-a9728984779c_story.html|title=How Scott Pruitt turned the EPA into one of Trump's most powerful tools|last=Dennis|first=Brady|date=2017-12-31|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-01-02|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|issn=0190-8286}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nA 2018 study in the ''[[American Journal of Public Health]]'' found that in the first six months of Pruitt's tenure as EPA head that the agency had adopted a pro-business attitude unlike that of any previous administration. The study argued \"that the Pruitt-led EPA has moved away from the public interest and explicitly favored the interests of the regulated industries.\" The study found that the agency was vulnerable to [[regulatory capture]] and that the consequences for public and environmental health could be far-reaching.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dillon|first=Lindsey|last2=Sellers|first2=Christopher|last3=Underhill|first3=Vivian|last4=Shapiro|first4=Nicholas|last5=Ohayon|first5=Jennifer Liss|last6=Sullivan|first6=Marianne|last7=Brown|first7=Phil|last8=Harrison|first8=Jill|last9=Wylie|first9=Sara|date=April 2018|title=The Environmental Protection Agency in the Early Trump Administration: Prelude to Regulatory Capture|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=108|issue=S2|pages=S89\u2013S94|doi=10.2105/ajph.2018.304360|issn=0090-0036|pmc=5922212|pmid=29698086}}</ref> According to a 2018 [[Harvard University]] analysis, the Trump administration's rollbacks and proposed reversals of environmental rules under Pruitt would under the most conservative estimate likely \"cost the lives of over 80\u202f000 US residents per decade and lead to respiratory problems for many more than 1 million people.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cutler|first=David|last2=Dominici|first2=Francesca|date=June 12, 2018|title=A Breath of Bad Air: Cost of the Trump Environmental Agenda May Lead to 80\u202f000 Extra Deaths per Decade|journal=JAMA|volume=319|issue=22|pages=2261\u20132262|doi=10.1001/jama.2018.7351|pmid=29896617|issn=0098-7484}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, ''[[The Politico (newspaper)|Politico]]'' disputed the narrative that Pruitt had been effective in overturning Obama's environmental legacy.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2018/04/07/scott-pruitt-epa-accomplishments-rollback-217834|title=The Myth of Scott Pruitt's EPA Rollback|work=POLITICO Magazine|access-date=April 8, 2018}}</ref> According to ''Politico'', \"Pruitt has yet to create new regulations that would outlast his tenure or Trump's, or to rescind any of the regulations Obama created. He's only been able to delay a few that were already on hold before he took office because they were mired in litigation.\"<ref name=\":23\" /> ''The New York Times'' and ''The Washington Post'' noted that while Pruitt was prolific in undoing government regulations, legal experts said that Pruitt did so hastily and through poorly crafted legal arguments that lacked legal, scientific and technical data.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/07/climate/scott-pruitt-epa-rollbacks.html|title=In His Haste to Roll Back Rules, Scott Pruitt, E.P.A. Chief, Risks His Agenda|last=Davenport|first=Coral|date=April 7, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 7, 2018|last2=Friedman|first2=Lisa|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://js.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/epas-pruitt-praised-for-effectiveness-hits-bumps-in-his-rollback-campaign/2018/05/20/c6ca13d8-53b3-11e8-abd8-265bd07a9859_story.html|title=Amid ethics scrutiny, EPA's Pruitt also finds his regulatory rollbacks hitting bumps|work=Washington Post|access-date=May 21, 2018}}</ref> As a result, legal experts considered it likely that some of the rollbacks may be reversed in the courts.<ref name=\":22\" /> Legal experts described the legal arguments made by Pruitt's EPA as unprecedented and a departure from previous Republican and Democratic administrations.<ref name=\":22\" /> Rutgers University professor Stuart Shapiro said that while Pruitt had weakened enforcement of existing regulations, he had not been successful at repealing regulations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2018/04/28/epa-scandals-scott-pruitt-fails-undo-obama-environmental-regulations-column/555721002/|title=EPA scandals overshadow Scott Pruitt failure to undo Obama environmental regulations|work=USA TODAY|access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> By April 2018, six of Pruitt's rollbacks had been struck down by courts, and Pruitt had withdrawn two of his proposed rollbacks.<ref name=\":22\" /> Pruitt's legal document outlining the rationale to roll back a regulation on greenhouse emissions from vehicle tailpipes was 38 pages long, lacked the kind of data that courts expect in cases involving environmental regulations, and was mostly direct quotes from public comments made by automaker lobbyists.<ref name=\":22\" /> In contrast, the Obama administration's rationale for implementing the regulation in the first place was 1,217 pages long.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nOn March 9, 2017, in an interview on CNBC's [[Squawk Box]], Pruitt stated that he \"would not agree that\" carbon dioxide is \"a primary contributor to the global warming that we see\" backing up his claim by stating that \"measuring with precision human activity on the climate is something very challenging to do and there's tremendous disagreement about the degree of impact.\"<ref name=\"cnbc\">{{cite web|last1=DiChristopher|first1=Tom|title=EPA chief Scott Pruitt says carbon dioxide is not a primary contributor to global warming|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/03/09/epa-chief-scott-pruitt.html|website=CNBC|publisher=NBC Universal |date=March 9, 2017|accessdate=March 9, 2017|ref=Pruitt believes Carbon Dioxide is not a contributor to Global Warming}}</ref> This was in direct contradiction with EPA's public stance that was published on their official website which stated: \"Carbon dioxide is the primary [[greenhouse gas]] that is contributing to recent climate change\".<ref name=\"nyt3\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/09/us/politics/epa-scott-pruitt-global-warming.html | title=E.P.A. Chief Doubts Consensus View of Climate Change |author=Coral Davenport |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=April 30, 2017| work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> By April 28\u2014the day before the [[People's Climate March (2017)|climate change mass protests]]\u2014EPA announced that the website \"would be 'undergoing changes' to better represent the new direction the agency is taking\" which included \"the removal of several agency websites containing detailed climate data and scientific information\" including the site that \"had been cited to challenge Pruitt's Squawk Box statements.\"<ref name=\"wp_websiteremoved\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/04/28/epa-website-removes-climate-science-site-from-public-view-after-two-decades/\n|title=EPA website removes climate science site from public view after two decades\n|first1=Chris |last1=Mooney |first2=Juliet |last2=Eilperin |date=April 29, 2017 |accessdate=April 30, 2017 |work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> A March 9 analysis by fact-checking website ''[[Snopes.com]]'' found that \"Pruitt's statements to CNBC are misrepresentative of the scientific consensus on carbon dioxide's role as a greenhouse gas\u2014a consensus that has essentially existed for more than a century.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snopes.com/2017/03/09/pruitt-global-warming-scientific-consensus/ |title=Do Scott Pruitt's Statements on CO2 and Global Warming Misrepresent Scientific Consensus? |publisher=Snopes.com |date= |accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Atlantic]]'' published an article on the same day, pointing out that in 2007, the [[United States Supreme Court]] had acknowledged the link between carbon dioxide and global warming\u2014in 2013 the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] stated the probability of carbon dioxide causing global warming was at least 95%.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2017/03/trumps-epa-chief-rejects-that-carbon-dioxide-emissions-cause-climate-change/519054/ |title=Scott Pruitt Rejects the Scientific Fact of Climate Change |magazine=The Atlantic |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPruitt's chosen deputy, chief of staff, and deputy chief of staff are all former members of Senator [[Jim Inhofe]]'s (R-OK) staff.<ref name=NYT8march17>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=E.P.A. Head Stacks Agency With Climate Change Skeptics|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/07/us/politics/scott-pruitt-environmental-protection-agency.html|accessdate=May 9, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 8, 2017|page=A17}}</ref>  Pruitt picked Washington State senators [[Don Benton]] and [[Doug Ericksen]] to be, respectively, a White House liaison and a regional administrator.<ref name=NYT8march17/> [[Andrew R. Wheeler]] was nominated to be Pruitt's deputy administrator.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=Trump Nominates a Coal Lobbyist to Be No. 2 at E.P.A.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/05/climate/trump-epa-andrew-wheeler.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=October 5, 2017}}</ref>  Pruitt's principal deputy at the EPA's Office of Chemical Safety and Pollution Prevention was previously an executive at the [[American Chemistry Council]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipton|first1=Eric|title=Why Has the E.P.A. Shifted on Toxic Chemicals? An Industry Insider Helps Call the Shots|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/21/us/trump-epa-chemicals-regulations.html|work=The New York Times|date=October 22, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>  In December 2017, [[Michael Dourson]] withdrew his nomination to be Pruitt's assistant administrator.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kaplan|first1=Sheila|last2=Lipton|first2=Eric|title=Trump's E.P.A. Chemical Safety Nominee Withdraws|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/13/science/epa-chemical-safety-trump.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=December 14, 2017|page=A20}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2018 United States federal budget|President's first budget]] instructs Pruitt to cut the agency's budget by 24% and reduce its 15,000 employees by 20%.<ref name=NYT8march17/>  Pruitt has sought to end EPA funding for the [[United States Department of Justice Environment and Natural Resources Division]], which relies on $20 million a year from the EPA for 27% of its budget.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Savage|first1=Charlie|title=E.P.A. Threatens to Stop Funding Justice Dept. Environmental Work|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/27/us/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-justice-department-funding.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=September 28, 2017|page=A19}}</ref>  Pruitt has issued a directive to stop litigants from pressuring the EPA to regulate, referring to the practice as \"sue and settle\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=Administrator Pruitt Issues Directive to End EPA \"Sue & Settle\"|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/administrator-pruitt-issues-directive-end-epa-sue-settle|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=October 16, 2017}}</ref>  In response, 57 former EPA counsels signed a letter criticizing Pruitt's directive.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reilly|first1=Amanda|title=LAW: Former EPA lawyers assail Pruitt's 'sue and settle' directive|url=https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060066359|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=[[Environment & Energy Publishing]]|date=November 13, 2017}}</ref>  Pruitt has offered himself as a replacement of U.S. Attorney General [[Jeff Sessions]].<ref name=nyt18march18>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=Scott Pruitt, Trump's Rule-Cutting E.P.A. Chief, Plots His Political Future|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/climate/scott-pruitt-political-ambitions.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=March 18, 2018|page=A1}}</ref>\n\nOn April 28, 2017, Pruitt fired scientists from the agency's 18-member Board of Scientific Counselors (BOSC), indicating he intended to replace them with industry representatives.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=E.P.A. Widens An Open Door For Businesses \u2014 At Least Five Scientists Ousted From a Board|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/07/us/politics/epa-dismisses-members-of-major-scientific-review-board.html|accessdate=May 8, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 8, 2017|page=A1}}</ref> Ryan Jackson, Pruitt's chief of staff, asked the BOSC's chair to change testimony she had submitted before a May 23 hearing of the [[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|House Science Committee]], causing her to complain she felt \"bullied.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mervis|first1=Jeffrey|title=Scientist tells her story in latest partisan battle on House science panel|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/06/scientist-tells-her-story-latest-partisan-battle-house-science-panel|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]|date=June 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=E.P.A. Official Pressured Scientist on Congressional Testimony, Emails Show|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/26/us/politics/epa-official-pressured-scientist-on-congressional-testimony-emails-show.html|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 27, 2017|page=A15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A hearing entitled Expanding the Role of States in EPA Rulemaking|url=https://science.house.gov/legislation/hearings/environment-subcommittee-hearing-expanding-role-states-epa-rulemaking|accessdate=July 5, 2017|publisher=U.S. House Committee on Science, Space, & Technology Subcommittee on Environment|date=May 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Pruitt removed several scientists from EPA advisory panels and forbade any scientist who receives a grant from the EPA from then serving those panels.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=Pruitt Bars Some Scientists From Advising E.P.A.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/31/climate/pruitt-epa-science-advisory-boards.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=November 1, 2017|page=A9}}</ref>  By December 2017, 700 staff had left EPA during Pruitt's tenure, including over 200 scientists.  During that time, Pruitt hired 129 people, including 7 scientists.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|last2=Affo|first2=Marina|last3=Kravitz|first3=Derek|title=E.P.A. Officials, Disheartened by Agency's Direction, Are Leaving in Droves|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/22/climate/epa-buyouts-pruitt.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=December 23, 2017|page=A16}}</ref>  In March 2018, Pruitt proposed to restrict the EPA from considering research that relies on confidential information, such as medical data.  The proposal was modeled on a stalled Congressional bill.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=The E.P.A. Says It Wants Research Transparency. Scientists See an Attack on Science.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/26/climate/epa-scientific-transparency-honest-act.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=March 26, 2018|page=A1}}</ref><ref>{{USBill|115|HR|1430|}} 115th Cong.(2017)</ref> It was expected that by August 2017, 47 of 58 serving scientists would have been removed from their positions, though they typically serve three year terms and which are renewed after they first expire.<ref>[https://thinkprogress.org/epa-dismisses-more-scientists-pruitt-trump-7530dc37dcf/ EPA accelerates purge of scientists Members of the EPA's Board of Scientific Counselors were told that they would not see their tenure renewed], ''[[Think Progress]]'', Natasha Geiling, June 21, 2017. Retrieved April 12, 2018.</ref>\n\nOn June 29, 2017, Pruitt attended a board meeting of the [[American Coalition for Clean Coal Electricity]], and told them that he will have researchers publicly debate the human role in [[climate change]], adopting [[Steven E. Koonin]]'s suggestion to hold a \"red team blue team\" exercise.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Plumer|first1=Brad|last2=Davenport|first2=Coral|title=E.P.A. to Give Dissenters a Voice on Climate, No Matter the Consensus|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/30/climate/scott-pruitt-climate-change-red-team.html|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 1, 2017|page=A12}}</ref>  In December 2017, White House Chief of Staff [[John F. Kelly]] rejected the debate idea.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|last2=Davis|first2=Julie Hirschfeld|title=The E.P.A. Chief Wanted a Climate Science Debate. Trump's Chief of Staff Stopped Him.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/09/climate/pruitt-red-team-climate-debate-kelly.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=March 11, 2018|page=A19}}</ref>  Pruitt has met with industry representatives almost daily while rarely meeting with environmentalists.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipton|first1=Eric|last2=Friedman|first2=Lisa|title=E.P.A. Chief's Calendar: A Stream of Industry Meetings and Trips Home|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/03/us/politics/epa-scott-pruitt-calendar-industries-coal-oil-environmentalists.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=October 3, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>\n\nPruitt and other agency heads delayed the public release of the Climate Change Report within the [[National Climate Assessment]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=Scientists Fear Trump Will Dismiss Blunt Climate Report|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/07/climate/climate-change-drastic-warming-trump.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=August 8, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>  The report was ultimately released in November 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|last2=Thrush|first2=Glenn|title=U.S. Report Says Humans Cause Climate Change, Contradicting Top Trump Officials|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/03/climate/us-climate-report.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=November 4, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, the [[Environmental Integrity Project]] determined that the administration was collecting 60% less money in civil environmental penalties than prior administrations.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=Civil Penalties Against Polluters Drop 60 Percent So Far Under Trump|url=http://www.environmentalintegrity.org/news/penalties-drop-under-trump/|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=[[Environmental Integrity Project]]|date=August 10, 2017}}</ref>  Pruitt has sought injunctive relief valued at 12% of that sought by the prior administration.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipton|first1=Eric|authorlink1=Eric Lipton|last2=Ivory|first2=Danielle|title=Under Trump, E.P.A. Has Slowed Actions Against Polluters, and Put Limits on Enforcement Officers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/10/us/politics/pollution-epa-regulations.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=December 11, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>  As of January 2018, the administration had removed, relaxed, or delayed 67 environmental rules.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Popovich|first1=Nadja|title=67 Environmental Rules on the Way Out Under Trump|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/10/05/climate/trump-environment-rules-reversed.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=October 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, ''Time'' magazine reviewed the status of the EPA's website after a year of Pruitt's tenure. The magazine reported that the website's Climate Change section was taken down in April 2017 after existing in various forms for more than twenty years. The message, \"This page is being updated\", was left in its place. In addition, searching for \"climate change\" produced 5,000 results compared to the previous 12,000. Resources on how local communities could combat climate change were cut from 380 to 170 pages, and a 50-page resource on \"a Student's Guide to Global Climate Change\" was not archived. On some pages, edits have been made to remove terms like \"climate change\", \"air pollutant\", \"greenhouse gas\", while \"carbon footprint\" and \"carbon accounting\" were replaced with \"environmental footprint\" and \"sustainability accounting\".<ref name=TIMEwebsite>{{cite web|last1=Barron|first1=Laignee|title=Here's What the EPA's Website Looks Like After a Year of Climate Change Censorship|url=http://time.com/5075265/epa-website-climate-change-censorship/|website=Time|accessdate=March 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCalling Pruitt on March 2, 2018, President Trump assured him, \"we've got your back,\" urging him to \"keep fighting,\" according to administration officials who remained anonymous. However, two additional officials confirmed that presidential Chief of Staff [[John F. Kelly]] had expressed the administration's displeasure over being caught unaware by some of the ethical problems Pruitt's conduct raised.<ref>[https://www.seattlepi.com/news/politics/article/Trump-offers-support-to-embattled-EPA-head-12801686.php EPA chief's job not assured after Trump's praise \u2014 and ire], ''Seattle [[Post-Intelligencer]]'', Zeke Miller & Michael Biesecker (AP), March 3, 2018. Retrieved March 4, 2018.</ref> Senate Environment Committee Chair [[John Barrasso]] of Wyoming, supported Pruitt, as did Senators [[Rand Paul]] and [[Ted Cruz]].<ref>[https://www.mysanantonio.com/news/politics/article/GOP-Senate-chairman-backs-Pruitt-as-ethics-probes-12818580.php Republicans stand by Pruitt as ethics probes expand], ''[[Associated Press]]'', Matthew Daly, April 9, 2018. Retrieved April 11, 2018.</ref>\n\nFormer coal lobbyist [[Andrew R. Wheeler|Andrew Wheeler]]'s nomination as Deputy Administrator was submitted to become Pruitt's deputy in 2017, but was not confirmed. It was resubmitted in 2018. He was confirmed as Deputy Administrator of the EPA on April 12, 2018, by a mostly party line vote of 53\u201345, which included three Democratic Senators, [[Joe Manchin]], [[Heidi Heitkamp]], and [[Joe Donnelly]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/the-senate-is-about-to-confirm-a-coal-lobbyist-as-top-epa-deputy/2018/04/12/b1bb6844-3dbe-11e8-a7d1-e4efec6389f0 Senate confirms a former coal lobbyist as Scott Pruitt's second-in-command at EPA], ''[[Washington Post]]'', Steven Mufson, Brady Dennis & Dino Grandoni, April 12, 2018. Retrieved April 13, 2018.</ref>\n\n=== Secrecy ===\nIn contrast to prior EPA administrators since its founding in 1973, Pruitt neither provided lists of scheduled public speaking events nor disclosed most trips until afterward. He avoided news conferences. On one occasion journalists who became aware of an event beforehand were ejected from a venue after an EPA official threatened to call law enforcement. Looking at a recent batch of documents released through a [[Sierra Club]] [[Freedom of information|FOI]] request, the ''New York Times'' commented that it appeared that the Pruitt schedulers divided people into \"friendly\" and \"unfriendly\" camps and noted one case where a meeting was kept so secret that even the meeting hosts were confused about it. Commenting on Pruitt's claim that his unusually extensive security expenses were related to his need for security, the ''New York Times'' said, \"[The documents] show that the agency's close control of Mr. Pruitt's events is driven more by a desire to avoid tough questions from the public than by concerns about security, contradicting Mr. Pruitt's longstanding defense of his secretiveness.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/07/climate/epa-pruitt-emails-secrecy.html|title='Smoke and Mirrors': Emails Detail Pruitt's Drive for Secrecy at the E.P.A.|last=Lipton|first=Eric|date=May 7, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 18, 2018|last2=Friedman|first2=Lisa|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=transparency /><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/11/climate/pruitt-cardinal-pell-dinner.html Pruitt's Dinner With Cardinal Accused of Abuse Was Kept Off Public Schedule], ''[[The New York Times]]'', Eric Lipton & Lisa Friedman, May 11, 2018. Retrieved May 18, 2018.</ref>\n\nA [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] request from the [[Sierra Club]] showed that between February and December 2017, Pruitt had only sent one e-mail to anyone outside EPA from his government e-mail account, leading to questions of whether Pruitt was using a private account to conduct government business.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/06/22/scott-pruitt-where-are-his-emails-664285|title=New Pruitt question: Where are his emails?|work=POLITICO|access-date=June 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn EPA official said that Pruitt and his top aides kept \"secret\" schedules and calendars to hide controversial meetings with industry representatives, destroying or altering records that might reflect poorly on Pruitt.<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/07/02/politics/scott-pruitt-whistleblower-secret-calendar/index.html|title=Whistleblower: EPA's Pruitt kept secret calendar to hide meetings|author1=Scott Bronstein |author2=Curt Devine |author3=Drew Griffin|work=CNN|access-date=July 3, 2018}}</ref> A review by ''CNN'' of internal EPA emails and the official EPA calendar found discrepancies in Pruitt's official EPA calendar with more than two dozen meetings and calls omitted.<ref name=\":33\" /> Legal experts said that the practices of keeping a secret calendar and destroying or altering records with the intent to deceive the public could be considered a violation of federal law.<ref name=\":33\" />\n\n=== Controversies ===\nDue to the multiple ongoing scandals involving Pruitt,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-25/here-s-a-scorecard-of-the-scott-pruitt-investigations-quicktake |title=A Guide to the Scott Pruitt Investigations |author=Jennifer A. Dlouhy |date=April 25, 2018 |website=Bloomberg.com |publisher= |access-date=July 6, 2018}}</ref> at least 20 members of Congress, including three Republicans ([[Carlos Curbelo]], [[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]] and [[Elise Stefanik]]), called for his resignation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cassella|first1=Carly|title=Now, Even Some Republicans Want Scott Pruitt Booted From The EPA|url=https://www.sciencealert.com/scott-pruitt-environmental-protection-agency-democrats-republicans|website=Science Alert|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/381840-gop-lawmaker-calls-on-pruitt-to-resign|title=GOP lawmaker calls on Pruitt to resign|last1=Cama|first1=Timothy|website=The Hill|publisher=The Hill|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|author=Stephanie Ebbs|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/epa-chief-scott-pruitt-facing-calls-investigate-housing/story?id=54207260|title=EPA Chief Scott Pruitt facing more calls to investigate housing arrangement|date=April 3, 2018|publisher=ABC News|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref> Curbelo said that Pruitt's \"corruption scandals are an embarrassment to the Administration, and his conduct is grossly disrespectful to American taxpayers.\"<ref name=\":3\" />  On April 3, 2018, Senator Sheldon Whitehouse (D-RI) and Congressmen Ted Lieu (D-CA) and Don Beyer (D-VA) called for an investigation of Pruitt's housing arrangements by the EPA's inspector general.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite press release|date=April 3, 2018|title=REPS LIEU AND BEYER URGE IG INVESTIGATION INTO EPA ADMINISTRATOR SCOTT PRUITT|url=https://lieu.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/reps-lieu-and-beyer-urge-ig-investigation-epa-administrator-scott-pruitt|publisher=Office of U.S. Representative Ted Lieu}}</ref> House Oversight Committee Chairman Trey Gowdy, a Republican, started a probe into Pruitt in early April 2018 over his housing arrangements.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/382061-oversight-chairman-probes-pruitts-50-a-night-condo-deal#.WsgZt7Uvl8E.twitter|title=Oversight chairman probes Pruitt's $50-a-night condo deal|last=Cohn|first=Alicia|date=April 6, 2018|work=The Hill|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> President Donald Trump defended Pruitt, saying \"Rent was about market rate, travel expenses OK. Scott is doing a great job!\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/08/trump-defends-embattled-epa-chief-scott-pruitt.html|title=Trump says embattled EPA chief Pruitt's expenses are justified because he received 'death threats'|publisher=CNBC|date=April 8, 2018|access-date=April 8, 2018}}</ref> By early April 2018, ''Politico'' reported that the number of mushrooming scandals, leaks and staff disapproval of Pruitt's expenditures and ethical conflicts had created chaos at the EPA and put morale at an all-time low.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/06/epa-scott-pruitt-employees-467487|title=Inside the EPA: 'It's just a slow-motion train wreck'|work=Politico|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> Three Republican Senators joined the criticism, including Susan Collins, who had voted against his confirmation, as well as South Carolina's [[Lindsey Graham]] and Louisiana's [[John Neely Kennedy]]. Kennedy said, \"Now these are unforced errors. They are stupid. There are a lot of problems we can't solve. But you can behave.\"<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/three-republican-senators-voice-concern-about-epa-head-scott-pruitts-conduct/2018/04/08/22c85122-3b45-11e8-a7d1-e4efec6389f0_story.html Three Republican senators voice concern about EPA head Scott Pruitt's conduct], ''[[Washington Post]]'', Sean Sullivan, April 8, 2018. Retrieved April 9, 2018.</ref> South Dakota Senator [[Mike Rounds]] defended Pruitt on ''[[Meet the Press]]'', however, referring to the criticism by saying, \"I don't know how much of it is overblown and how much of it is accurate, to be honest.\"<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/gop-sen-rounds-pruitt-criticism-nitpicking-n863711 GOP Sen. Rounds: Pruitt criticism amounts to 'nitpick' of 'little things'], [[NBC News]], Kailani Koenig, April 8, 2018. Retrieved April 9, 2018.</ref> On June 5, 2018, Iowa Republican Senator [[Joni Ernst]] said Pruitt \"is about as swampy as you get here in Washington, D.C., and if the president wants to drain the swamp, he needs to take a look at his own cabinet.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-05/gop-senator-ernst-calls-epa-chief-pruitt-as-swampy-as-you-get|title=Republican Senator Calls Pruitt 'as Swampy as You Get'|date=June 5, 2018|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=June 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nTwo of Pruitt's top aides\u2014senior counsel Sarah Greenwalt, and director for scheduling and advance Millan Hupp\u2014were reported on June 6, 2018 to be resigning from the EPA. Both Greenwalt and Hupp were Pruitt associates from Oklahoma and had come under scrutiny regarding various controversies during his EPA tenure. When contacted for comment by a reporter from ''The Atlantic'', EPA spokesman Jahan Wilcox declined to comment apart from saying, \"You have a great day, you're a piece of trash.\" That same day, Trump stated, \"People are really impressed with the job that's being done at the EPA. Thank you very much, Scott.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/06/climate/pruitt-aides-resign-epa.html|title=Two Pruitt Aides Resign as E.P.A. Ethics Questions Continue|date=June 6, 2018|accessdate=June 7, 2018|work=New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/06/top-aide-to-epa-administrator-scott-pruitt-resigns/561974/|title=Pruitt Aide Resigns Amid Scandals|first=Elaina|last=Plott|date=June 6, 2018|work=The Atlantic|accessdate=June 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPruitt came under the scrutiny of the [[United States Office of Government Ethics]] regarding potential violations of [[Title 5 of the Code of Federal Regulations]] (CFR), which specifically incorporates, \"Employees shall not use public office for private gain,\" and  \"Employees shall endeavor to avoid any actions creating the appearance that they are violating the law or the ethical standards set forth in this part.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oge.gov/web/oge.nsf/All%20Documents/778D0B693D42FEE08525826A004F5471/$FILE/Letter%20to%20EPA%20DAEO.pdf?open |title=United States Office of Government Ethics (letter to Kevin Minoli, Principal Deputy General Counsel and Designated Agency Ethics Official) |author=[[David J. Apol]], Acting Director and General Counsel |date=April 6, 2018 |publisher=[[United States Office of Government Ethics]] |access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/commentary/ct-perspec-ethics-scott-pruitt-epa-0618-20180615-story.html |title=As ethics advisers, we thought we'd seen it all. Scott Pruitt shocks us. |authors=Virginia Canter and [[Norman L. Eisen]] |date=June 15, 2018 |website=[[Chicago Tribune]] |publisher= |access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.ecfr.gov/cgi-bin/text-idx?SID=48b2909b801315c551f1457d36c543ac&mc=true&node=pt5.3.2635&rgn=div5 Title 5: Administrative Personnel PART 2635\u2014STANDARDS OF ETHICAL CONDUCT FOR EMPLOYEES OF THE EXECUTIVE BRANCH], ''[[Electronic Code of Federal Regulations]]'', June 21, 2018. Retrieved June 24, 2018.</ref>\n\nEmails generated by EPA staffers, when Pruitt was the nominee for the EPA post, showed he considered running the agency at least part-time from Tulsa, his hometown, and sought office space in that city that would include room for his security detail. House Democratic committee members requested details from the EPA about his plans to open a Tulsa office, citing ethical concerns. \"Establishing a new EPA office in Tulsa may be personally convenient for you, but it seems ethically questionable, professionally unnecessary, and financially unjustified,\" they wrote in a May letter to Pruitt. EPA staff emails said Pruitt required a \"secure cabinet or safe\" as well as a secure room to receive classified information from President Donald Trump and his cabinet members. He also wanted the latitude to work from home at times. They ventured that the \"optics\" of receiving donated office space would be a public relations problem for Pruitt. An additional issue was the EPA didn't want the cost of such a space to appear as a line item in a congressional bill.<ref>[https://www.readfrontier.org/stories/emails-show-pruitt-mulled-running-the-epa-from-hometown-of-tulsa-though-plan-was-eventually-scrapped/ Emails show Pruitt mulled running the EPA from hometown of Tulsa, though plan was eventually scrapped], Brianna Bailey, June 23, 2018. Retrieved June 24, 2018.</ref>\n\n==== Management of agency ====\nEPA employees reported that the doors to the floor in the EPA's headquarters containing Pruitt's office were frequently locked, and employees were required to have escorts while visiting the floor. Some EPA employees also reported being told not to bring cellphones or take notes in meetings with Pruitt. Pruitt was also accompanied by armed guards even while at EPA's headquarters, an unprecedented level of security for an EPA administrator. Pruitt also ended the longstanding practice of making public the appointments of the administrator and other top agency officials.<ref name=\"Secret\">{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|last2=Lipton|first2=Eric|title=Scott Pruitt Is Carrying Out His E.P.A. Agenda in Secret, Critics Say|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/11/us/politics/scott-pruitt-epa.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=August 12, 2017|page=A1}}</ref> These measures prompted critics to charge that Pruitt was running the agency in secret.<ref name=\"Secret\"/>\n\nFive officials at the EPA \u2013 four of them high-ranking \u2013 were reassigned, demoted or pushed out of the EPA after they raised concerns about Pruitt's management of the agency, in particular Pruitt's expenditures.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/05/business/epa-officials-questioned-scott-pruitt.html|title=Job Changes for E.P.A. Officials Who Questioned Scott Pruitt|last=Lipton|first=Eric|date=April 5, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 5, 2018|last2=Vogel|first2=Kenneth P.|issn=0362-4331|last3=Friedman|first3=Lisa}}</ref> Several of these officials played a key role in reviewing Pruitt's travel plans; on occasions they put a halt to unjustifiably expensive travel plans.<ref name=\":19\" /> One political appointee was put on leave after voicing concerns about Pruitt to the White House's presidential personnel office.<ref name=\":19\" /> ''The New York Times'' reported that the appointee had objected to proposals considered by Pruitt's staff to buy a $100,000-a-month charter aircraft membership, spend $70,000 on two desks for Pruitt's office, and spend $43,000 on a sound-proof security booth.<ref name=\":19\" /> The appointee first asked Pruitt privately to rein in his spending, but then did it through intermediaries after he got frozen out.<ref name=\":19\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/18/climate/scott-pruitt-epa-investigations-guide.html|title=Expenses, Emails and a Phone Booth: The Investigations Faced by Scott Pruitt|date=April 18, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 20, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nEarly in his tenure, Pruitt asked his security detail to use flashing lights and sirens when they were stuck in D.C. traffic. Eric Weese, the lead agent of his security detail, told Pruitt that flashing lights and sirens were only used in emergency circumstances.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/scott-pruitt-asked-to-use-sirens-in-dc-traffic-and-was-told-no-for-non-emergency/|title=Scott Pruitt asked to use sirens in D.C. traffic and was told no for non-emergency|access-date=April 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":19\" /> One of the instances included a trip to Pruitt's favorite French restaurant in D.C.<ref name=\":19\" /> Less than two weeks later, the lead agent was reassigned.<ref name=\":20\" /><ref name=\":19\" /> Weese had also expressed a reluctance to sign off on requests that Pruitt needed to travel first class for security reasons.<ref name=\":19\" /> Agency staff questioned requests for a bulletproof sport utility vehicle, the construction of a special security booth in Pruitt's office, the tripling of the size of Pruitt's security detail, and the 24/7 work hours of his security detail.<ref name=\":19\" /> Reginald E. Allen, a career official at the EPA, was reassigned to an office within the EPA described as \"an unmarked grave\" after he objected to Pruitt's spending.<ref name=\":19\" /> Pruitt replaced Weese with Pasquale \"Nino\" Perrotta, a former Secret Service agent operating a private security company.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/e2fdc3fe88be432792817795a34fda46|title=AP sources: EPA chief spent millions on security and travel|work=AP News|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> Perrotta obtained a waiver to maintain outside employment while also heading Pruitt's security detail.<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/12/climate/epa-scott-pruitt-pasquale-perrotta.html|title=At E.P.A., Pruitt's 'Sheriff' Clashed With Critics of Spending|last=Vogel|first=Kenneth P.|date=April 12, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 13, 2018|last2=Lipton|first2=Eric|issn=0362-4331|last3=Friedman|first3=Lisa}}</ref> Under Perrotta, there was a rapid expansion of Pruitt's security detail, as he signed off on various requests by Pruitt's team.<ref name=\":21\" /> Perrotta also wrote an email to five EPA officials which indicated that it was Pruitt's preference to use lights and sirens on his vehicle.<ref name=Senate />\n\nDuring a trip to Italy, the EPA hired Italians to further support Pruitt's security detail who were reportedly friends of Perrotta.<ref name=\":21\" /> Perrotta travelled first class with Pruitt and shared, along with his men, a five-course meal with Pruitt at a restaurant in Rome (it is rare for security personnel to dine with those they are protecting).<ref name=\":24\" /> Perrotta also hired the vice president of his private security company to conduct bug sweeps in Pruitt's office (typically conducted by government personnel) and install biometric locks on doors at a cost of approximately $9,000.<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":21\" />  After Kevin Chmielewski, a former campaign staffer for Donald Trump, refused to retroactively approve return first class travel from Morocco for Pruitt's aide, Samantha Dravis, Perrotta ordered him to relinquish his staff credentials, and Chmielewski was terminated from his position. Chmielewski had also raised concerns regarding other expenditures and the ethics of Pruitt's condo lease.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/12/former-epa-staffer-pruitt-first-class-478291 Former EPA staffer: Refusal to OK first-class flight for Pruitt aide prompted firing], ''[[Politico]]'', Alex Guillen, April 12, 2018. Retrieved April 12, 2018.</ref> Besides Weese, Reginald E. Allen was moved to a job where he had less say in spending decisions and less interaction with Pruitt. A third career official, John E. Reeder, was told to find a new job and John C. Martin, who also served on the security detail, was removed from the team and had his gun and badge taken away after questioning how Pruitt's security was being handled. A sixth official, Mr. Pruitt's chief of staff, Ryan Jackson, also raised questions about Mr. Pruitt's spending, according to unnamed EPA officials, remaining in his position, but who considered resignation.<ref name=\":24\" />\n\nIn June 2018, it was reported that Pruitt had used agency staff to perform nonofficial duties for Pruitt.<ref name=\":29\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/06/07/pruitt-enlisted-security-detail-in-picking-up-dry-cleaning-moisturizing-lotion/|title=Pruitt enlisted security detail in picking up dry cleaning, moisturizing lotion|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=June 7, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=June 7, 2018|last2=Dawsey|first2=Josh|issn=0190-8286|last3=Dennis|first3=Brady}}</ref> He tasked members of his security detail to run errands like picking up his dry cleaning and driving him around to search for a favorite moisturizer.<ref name=\":29\" /> Pruitt also tasked staffers to look for apartments and to purchase a used mattress for his personal use.<ref name=\":29\" />\n\n===== Freedom of Information Act requests =====\nAs EPA administrator, Pruitt maintained four different email addresses. This prompted two Democrats on the [[Senate Committee on Environment and Public Works]] to request that the EPA inspector general look into \"whether the agency has properly searched these email addresses for responsive documents in response to [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] (FOIA) requests.\"<ref>Juliet Eilperin & Brady Dennis, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/04/12/scott-pruitt-has-four-different-epa-email-addresses-lawmakers-want-to-know-why/ Scott Pruitt has 4 different EPA email addresses. Lawmakers want to know why.], ''Washington Post'' (April 12, 2018).</ref>\n\nUnder Pruitt, EPA Chief of Staff Ryan Jackson created a pilot program to \"centralize\" FOIA requests that go through the various sub-offices that make up EPA's Office of the Administrator, as revealed by released emails. In internal emails from August 2017 (later turned over to the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]]), Jackson and another top Pruitt aide (Liz Bowman, the head of EPA's Office of Public Affairs) complained that career EPA officials had released records in response to a FOIA request from a news organization ([[E&E News]]), when such records could have been withheld for several additional weeks. The aides directed that they be notified prior to any release of Pruitt-related material. This approach was criticized by FOIA experts; Nate Jones, director of the FOIA Project at [[George Washington University]]'s [[National Security Archive]] said the process \"does look like the most burdensome review process that I've seen documented.\"<ref>[https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/06/pruitt-epa-document-requests-570289 EPA clamps down on document requests linked to Pruitt], ''[[Politico]]'', Alex Guillen, May 5, 2018. Retrieved May 7, 2018.</ref>\n\nPruitt hired the former treasurer of his political action committee, Elizabeth Beacham White to run the EPA office that handles Freedom of Information Act requests for Pruitt's office.<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/07/03/pruitt-pac-treasurer-public-records-releases-667031|title=Pruitt ally decides which of his records see the light of day|work=Politico|access-date=July 3, 2018}}</ref> The office run by White has been slow to meet FOIA requests, far exceeding legal deadlines and causing a massive surge in court challenges. Pruitt's office had the slowest response rate to FOIA requests of any section of the EPA.<ref name=\":34\" />\n\n==== Expenditures ====\nPruitt drew controversy in the late summer and fall of 2017 over his use of taxpayer funds.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/09/27/epas-pruitt-took-charter-military-flights-that-cost-taxpayers-more-than-58000/|title=EPA's Pruitt took charter, military flights that cost taxpayers more than $58,000|last=Dennis|first=Brady|date=September 27, 2017|work=Washington Post|access-date=September 28, 2017|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Unlike his predecessors, Pruitt has, as EPA head, regularly flown first or business class on commercial airlines, as well as chartered private jets and military planes at exorbitant costs.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/first-class-travel-distinguishes-scott-pruitts-epa-tenure/2018/02/11/5bb89afc-0b7d-11e8-8b0d-891602206fb7_story.html|title=First-class travel distinguishes Scott Pruitt's EPA tenure|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=February 11, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=February 12, 2018|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/epas-scott-pruitt-got-waiver-to-fly-business-class-on-non-u-s-carrier-from-italy-to-u-s/|title=EPA's Scott Pruitt got waiver to fly business class on foreign carrier from Italy to U.S.|access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> The cost of Pruitt's seats on those flights are often several times higher than the seats for his accompanying staffers.<ref name=\":12\" /> Pruitt also has a vastly larger around-the-clock security detail than his predecessors.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/at-epa-guarding-the-chief-pulls-agents-from-pursuing-environmental-crimes/2017/09/19/7b7b8b6c-9ce0-11e7-8ea1-ed975285475e_story.html|title=At EPA, guarding the chief pulls agents from pursuing environmental crimes|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=September 20, 2017|work=Washington Post|access-date=September 28, 2017|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref name=\"threats\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2017/10/23/politics/epa-pruitt-security-costs/index.html|title=Security costs skyrocket at EPA|authors=Rene Marsh and Gregory Wallace|publisher=CNN|date=October 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, the inspector general of the EPA launched a probe into Pruitt's travel to and from Oklahoma at taxpayer expense.<ref name=\":7\" /> In September 2017, it was revealed that Pruitt had used at least $58,000 worth of noncommercial charter flights and military flights during his tenure, and when traveling on commercial airlines had opted for business or first class when those seats were available.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-epa-pruitt/epas-pruitt-took-flights-costing-taxpayers-more-than-58000-washington-post-idUSKCN1C30E7|title=EPA's Pruitt took flights costing taxpayers more than $58,000: Washington Post|date=2017|agency=Reuters|access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref> In February 2018, a ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' investigation determined that Pruitt has thus far spent hundreds of thousands of dollars on first-class airline travel, charter flights, military aircraft and luxury hotel stays, potentially contravening federal travel regulations and contrary to the practices of his predecessors, who routinely traveled in economy class. On June 5, 2017, for example, Pruitt billed the government for a $1,641.43 first-class ticket on a flight from Washington, D.C. to New York.<ref name=\"WaPoTravel\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/first-class-travel-distinguishes-scott-pruitts-epa-tenure/2018/02/11/5bb89afc-0b7d-11e8-8b0d-891602206fb7_story.html First-class travel distinguishes Scott Pruitt's EPA tenure]. ''[[The Washington Post]]'', February 11, 2018</ref>\n\nPruitt defended his unprecedented travel costs as necessary for security reasons. His spokesman told ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' that Pruitt has a \"blanket waiver\" to travel regulations which normally prohibit first-class travel by federal employees.<ref name=\"HillTravel\">[http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/373747-pruitt-has-blanket-waiver-to-first-class-travel-rules Pruitt has 'blanket waiver' to first-class travel rules]. ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', February 13, 2018</ref> Pruitt's staff later elaborated that the security reasons included other passengers being uncivil, quoting one individual yelling a vulgarism at him, referring what he was doing to the environment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/02/15/scott-pruitt-first-class-travel-epa-351669|title=Pruitt's security threat? A passenger shouting, 'You're f\u2014ing up the environment'|work=POLITICO|access-date=February 16, 2018}}</ref> Despite the purported security threats to Pruitt, he opted to travel in coach on flights home to Oklahoma when taxpayers were not paying for his travel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/382060-pruitt-flew-coach-when-taxpayers-were-not-paying-for-his-travel|title=Pruitt flew coach when taxpayers were not paying for his travel: report|last=Anapol|first=Avery|date=April 6, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> Furthermore, according to a former top aide, Pruitt refused to stay at hotels which had been vetted by the U.S. Embassy while traveling abroad, opting instead for more expensive and less secure hotels.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/12/climate/pruitt-epa-ethics-letter-congress.html|title=Lawmakers' Letter Claims Further Spending Abuses by the E.P.A. Head, Scott Pruitt|last=Lipton|first=Eric|date=April 12, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 12, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nPruitt frequently opted to fly with Delta Airlines, despite US government contracts giving discounts on certain routes.<ref name=\":11\" /> According to one of Pruitt's former top aides, Pruitt wanted to fly Delta so that he could collect more frequent flyer miles.<ref name=\":2\" /> During one trip, Pruitt used [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]], a Dubai-based airline, requiring a waiver from the [[Fly America Act]], which normally requires federal employees to travel on American-owned airlines.<ref name=\":12\" /> Pruitt also tended to stay at high-end hotels during his trips.<ref name=\":11\" /> Pruitt was found to have spent 43 of the 92 days from March to May 2017 in Oklahoma or traveling there.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=Scott Pruitt Spent Much of Early Months at E.P.A. Traveling Home, Report Says|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/24/climate/scott-pruitt-epa-travel-expenses.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=July 24, 2017|page=A12}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the EPA spent what was thought to be $25,000 to build a [[Soundproofing|soundproof]] booth for Pruitt to use in his office. The EPA's spokesperson said that this was to protect against hacking and eavesdropping.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/26/climate/pruitt-epa.html|title=E.P.A. to Spend Nearly $25,000 on a Soundproof Booth for Pruitt|last=Friedman|first=Lisa|date=September 26, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 28, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In March 2018, it was revealed that the cost of the booth was even higher than initially reported; actually almost $43,000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/03/14/scott-pruitts-25000-soundproof-phone-booth-it-actually-cost-more-like-43000/|title=Scott Pruitt's $25,000 soundproof phone booth? It actually cost more like $43,000.|last=Dennis|first=Brady|date=March 14, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=March 14, 2018|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> [[Christine Todd Whitman]], EPA Administrator under [[George W. Bush]], noted that there was already a secure phone booth in the building.<ref>[[Margaret Talbot]], [https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/04/02/scott-pruitts-dirty-politics Scott Pruitt's Dirty Politics], ''The [[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]'' (April 2, 2018). Retrieved April 9, 2018.</ref> In April 2018, the [[Government Accountability Office]] concluded that Pruitt's purchase of the $43,000 soundproof booth violated federal spending laws.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/04/16/scott-pruitts-43000-soundproof-phone-booth-violated-spending-laws-federal-watchdog-finds/|title=Scott Pruitt's $43,000 soundproof phone booth violated spending laws, federal watchdog finds|last=Dennis|first=Brady|date=April 16, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 16, 2018|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nThe EPA also swept for bugs in Pruitt's office and installed biometric locks on his office doors, at a cost of approximately $9,000.<ref name=\":21\" /> In September 2017, it was reported that Pruitt's security detail had increased to 18 people who guarded him around the clock, which was without precedent in size for an EPA chief. Additional agents for Pruitt's security detail were reassigned from the EPA's Criminal Investigation Division, which more typically investigates environmental crimes.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/09/21/politics/epa-pruitt-agents/index.html|title=EPA pulls agents from investigations to guard Pruitt|author=Rene Marsh and Gregory Wallace|access-date=September 28, 2017|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref name=\":13\" /> The EPA justified the size of the detail, saying that it was because Pruitt faced greater security threats.<ref name=\"threats\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> However, an internal EPA report showed that EPA intelligence officials concluded there was no justification for the expansion of Pruitt's security detail and that there were no specific credible security threats against Pruitt; the career EPA official who approved the report was later dismissed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/04/10/internal-epa-documents-question-justification-for-pruitts-round-the-clock-security-detail/|title=Internal EPA documents question justification for Pruitt's round-the-clock security detail|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=April 10, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 10, 2018|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/10/documents-contradict-epa-claims-threats-984459|title=Exclusive: EPA removes staffer who OK'd report on Pruitt's security|work=Politico|access-date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> The Associated Press failed to find any case where someone had been charged or arrested for threatening Pruitt.<ref name=\":21\" /> In October 2017, CNN reported that Pruitt had requested a dozen more agents, which would cost the taxpayers at least $2 million per year in salaries alone.<ref name=\"threats\" /> By June 2018, the costs of Pruitt security was more than $4.6 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2018/06/20/scott-pruitt-epa-security-total-expenses-foia/|title=Scott Pruitt Has Spent a Total of $4.6 Million on Security, New Disclosures Show \u2014 Including $1,500 on \"Tactical Pants\"|last=Fang|first=Lee|last2=Surgey|first2=Nick|date=June 20, 2018|website=The Intercept|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, it was reported that Pruitt's aides had researched leasing a private jet on a monthly basis for Pruitt's travel. The estimated cost of this would have been approximately $100,000 per month.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/epa-explored-private-jet-lease-for-pruitts-travels-last-year/2018/04/02/8651deb8-3607-11e8-8fd2-49fe3c675a89_story.html|title=EPA explored private jet lease for Pruitt's travels last year|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=April 2, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 3, 2018|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> The aides evaluated such expenditures prior to the outbreak of a similar scandal regarding exorbitant travel costs by Health and Human Services Secretary [[Tom Price (American politician)|Tom Price]], which later led to Price's resignation.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\nIn April 2018, it was also reported that Pruitt had two of his aides and three security agents sent on a trip to Australia in August 2017 to set up future meetings for him; the five staff members flew business class, costing taxpayers a combined $45,000 for airfare alone.<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-pruitt-exclusive/exclusive-epa-chiefs-aides-security-agents-made-45000-trip-to-australia-idUSKBN1HQ2U7|title=Exclusive: EPA chief's aides, security agents made $45,000 trip to ...|last=Mason|first=Jeff|publisher=Reuters|access-date=April 19, 2018}}</ref> Each ticket cost $9,000 (an economy class ticket would have cost approximately $1,400).<ref name=\":25\" /> Pruitt's trip to Australia was canceled due to Hurricane Harvey.<ref name=\":25\" />\n\nResponding to allegations of ethics violations, in April 2018, thirty-nine members of the Senate and more than 130 members of the House of Representatives\ncalled for Pruitt's resignation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Record number of lawmakers sign resolution demanding Pruitt's resignation |url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/768375/record-number-lawmakers-sign-resolution-demanding-pruitts-resignation |website=The Week |accessdate=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, it was reported that Pruitt had spent approximately $1,500 on 12 customized fountain pens from a Washington jewelry store.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/06/01/epas-pruitt-spent-1560-on-12-customized-fountain-pens-from-washington-jewelry-store/|title=EPA's Pruitt spent $1,560 on 12 customized fountain pens from Washington jewelry store|last=Dennis|first=Brady|date=June 1, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=June 1, 2018|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n==== 2017 Morocco trip to encourage U.S. LNG sales ====\nIn 2018, Pruitt faced increased scrutiny concerning a December 2017 trip to Morocco. The trip was disclosed via a press release after Pruitt had returned.<ref name=\"EPAPress\">{{cite press release|title=Administrator Pruitt Promotes Environmental Cooperation with U.S. Partners in Morocco|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/administrator-pruitt-promotes-environmental-cooperation-us-partners-morocco|agency=U.S. Environmental Protection Agency|date=December 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"EilperinFourDays\">Juliet Eilperin, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/12/13/scott-pruitt-and-a-crew-of-epa-aides-just-spent-four-days-in-morocco-promoting-natural-gas/ Scott Pruitt and a crew of EPA aides just spent four days in Morocco promoting natural gas], ''Washington Post'' (December 13, 2017).</ref> During the trip, Pruitt met with Moroccan officials to discuss the [[United States-Morocco Free Trade Agreement|bilateral Morocco-U.S. agreement]] and promoted the export of [[liquified natural gas]] (LNG) to Morocco.<ref name=\"EPAPress\"/><ref name=\"EilperinFourDays\" /> Pruitt and his entourage spent four days in Morocco and some additional time in Paris, which an EPA spokesman said was due to weather delays.<ref name=\"DennisEilperinMar20\">{{cite news|last1=Dennis|first1=Brady|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|title=New documents show nearly $68,000 in recent premium flights, hotel stays for EPA's Pruitt|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/03/20/new-documents-show-nearly-68000-in-recent-premium-flights-hotel-stays-for-epas-pruitt/|accessdate=April 6, 2018|newspaper=Washington Post|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref> Pruitt's travel expenses for the trip cost $17,631; the costs for Pruitt's 10-person entourage were not disclosed.<ref name=\"DennisEilperinMar20\" />\n\nIn May 2018, it was revealed that Richard Smotkin, a former Comcast lobbyist and long-time friend of Pruitt's, arranged the trip to Morocco.<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/lobbyist-helped-broker-pruitts-100000-trip-to-morocco/2018/05/01/b2e20ee0-4d76-11e8-b725-92c89fe3ca4c_story.html |title=Lobbyist helped arrange Scott Pruitt's $100,000 trip to Morocco|last=Sullivan|first=Kevin|date=May 1, 2018|work=Washington Post|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|last3=Dennis|first3=Brady}}</ref> In April 2018, Smotkin received a $40,000-a-month contract (retroactive to January 2018) with the Moroccan government to lobby on behalf of the country.<ref name=\":26\" /> Ethics experts said that it was highly unusual for individuals outside of government to arrange trips such as these and that the trip raised questions as to whether it was intended to financially benefit Smotkin.<ref name=\":26\" />\n\nPruitt's Morocco trip was controversial, prompting criticism from Democrats and from the [[Sierra Club]], and prompting an expanded inquiry from the EPA inspector general. In a letter to Pruitt asking him to explain the trip, Senator [[Sheldon Whitehouse]] (D-RI) noted that the five-day trip consisted of one full workday, two days with a one-hour meeting for each, and a two-day, non-work layover in Paris over a weekend.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=A Trip to Morocco. A Condo Rental. Here's Why Scott Pruitt Is Under Fire.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/04/climate/scott-pruitt-condo-travel.html|accessdate=April 6, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Mosk\">{{cite news|last1=Mosk|first1=Matthew|last2=Ebbs|first2=Stephanie|last3=Turner|first3=Trish|title=More scrutiny for Pruitt's Morocco trip from Democrats, EPA inspector general|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/scrutiny-pruitts-morocco-trip-democrats-epa-inspector-general/story?id=54240618|accessdate=April 6, 2018|publisher=ABC News|date=April 4, 2018}}</ref> Critics also said that Pruitt's trip was improper because the export of liquified natural gas (LNG), a [[fossil fuel]], falls outside the EPA's mission of ensuring clean air and water, and because the Energy Department and [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]], not the EPA, oversee the export of LNG.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Biesecker|first1=Michael|title=EPA chief jets to Morocco to help promote fossil fuel use|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sns-bc-us--epa-pruitt-travel-morocco-20171213-story.html|agency=Associated Press|date=December 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Eilperin|first1=Juliet|title=Scott Pruitt and a crew of EPA aides just spent four days in Morocco promoting natural gas|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/12/13/scott-pruitt-and-a-crew-of-epa-aides-just-spent-four-days-in-morocco-promoting-natural-gas/|accessdate=April 6, 2018|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=December 13, 2017}}</ref> At the time of the trip, Pruitt's landlord's lobbying firm represented the only U.S. domestic exporter of LNG.<ref name =Cheniere /><ref name=Cheniere2 />\n\nIn December 2017, Senator [[Tom Carper]] (D-DE) wrote a letter to the EPA Inspector General, requesting that the IG expand the scope of the pending audit concerning Pruitt's travel to include the Morocco trip.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carper|first1=Thomas|title=12/18/17 Letter to EPA Inspector General from Senator Thomas Carper|url=https://www.epw.senate.gov/public/_cache/files/a/7/a7271e2f-169d-4421-8aa1-bd2aee769bb0/357ADF0B861CF8EE2E008EE37D270633.carper-asks-inspector-general-to-expand-investigation-into-epa-administrators-travel.pdf|publisher=U.S. Senate|accessdate=April 6, 2018}}</ref> In response to Carper's letter, \"the IG said he would expand the scope of the investigation of Pruitt's travel costs through the end of 2017 and would look at whether EPA followed all policies and procedures.\"<ref name=\"Mosk\"/>\n\nIn April 2018, Pruitt released his travel itinerary for the Morocco trip in response to Freedom of Information requests, but the bulk of the itinerary had been redacted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/scott-pruitts-moroccan-calendar-draws-blanks/story?id=54556574|title=Scott Pruitt's Moroccan calendar draws blanks|date=April 19, 2018|publisher=ABC News|access-date=April 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Housing arrangements ====\nIn March 2018, it was reported that Pruitt had leased a condominium [[townhouse]] in Washington D.C. from a lobbyist couple, Vicki and Steven Hart, at a price of $50 per night, which amounted to $6,100 over a six-month period.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-30/epa-chief-s-50-a-night-rental-said-to-raise-white-house-angst|title=EPA Chief's $50-a-Night Rental Raises White House Angst|date=March 30, 2018|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Daily Beast\">{{cite web|title=EPA Administrator Scott Pruitt's Lobbyist-Owned Pad Was GOP Fundraising Hub|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/epa-administrator-scott-pruitts-lobbyist-owned-pad-was-gop-fundraising-hub|website=Daily Beast|publisher=Daily Beast|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref> The average price for [[Airbnb]] lodging in the same neighborhood is $142 per night.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/03/30/as-new-details-emerge-scott-pruitts-housing-arrangements-come-under-scrutiny/|title=As new details emerge, Scott Pruitt's housing arrangements come under scrutiny|last=Dennis|first=Brady|date=March 30, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=March 31, 2018|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Pruitt's adult daughter also stayed for months in the condo's second bedroom while a White House intern, but was not charged for her stay.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/exclusive-epa-chief-pruitt-joined-family-condo-tied/story EXCLUSIVE: EPA chief Pruitt joined by family in condo tied to lobbyist 'power couple'], [[ABC News]], John Santucci, Matthew Mosk & Stephanie Ebbs, March 30, 2018. Retrieved March 31, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe Harts' firm was registered to lobby on behalf of at least a half a dozen clients in industries regulated by the EPA,<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/02/climate/epa-pruitt-pipeline-apartment.html|title=Pruitt Had a $50-a-Day Condo Linked to Lobbyists. Their Client's Project Got Approved.|last=Lipton|first=Eric|date=April 2, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 3, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/20/pruitt-condo-lobbyist-leaving-firm-543508|title=Lobbyist whose wife rented to Pruitt lobbied EPA despite denials|work=POLITICO|access-date=April 21, 2018}}</ref> including Canadian energy company Enbridge.<ref name=\"Cheniere\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/30/climate/scott-pruitt-epa-rental.html Scott Pruitt, E.P.A. Chief, Rented Residence From Wife of Energy Lobbyist], ''[[New York Times]]'', Brad Plumer & Eric Lipton, March 30, 2018. Retrieved April 11, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Cheniere2\">{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/exclusive-pruitts-epa-security-broke-door-lobbyist-condo/story?id=54129080|title=Pruitt's EPA security broke down door to lobbyist condo|date=March 30, 2018|publisher=ABC News|access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref> At the same time that Pruitt was renting the condo, the EPA approved Enbridge's plan to expand a pipeline carrying oil to the United States from Canadian tar sands.<ref name=\":15\" /> Enbridge had in 2010 been given the second-largest fine in EPA history for spilling crude oil into the [[Kalamazoo River]] in Michigan.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nA Pruitt spokesperson denied any link between the condo rental and the agency approvals, but government ethics experts said that the situation raised an [[Appearance of impropriety|appearance]] of a conflict of interests that made it reasonable to question the EPA's decision.<ref name=\":15\" /> In May 2018, emails showed that Hart had asked Pruitt to get three people appointed to the EPA's Science Advisory Board.<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/01/climate/epa-kelly-perrotta-resignations.html|title=Two Top Aides to Scott Pruitt Quit the E.P.A. Unexpectedly|date=May 1, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 2, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The three people were recommended by a company that Hart lobbied on behalf of.<ref name=\":27\" />\n\nIn March 2018, EPA's Designated Agency Ethics Official and principal deputy general counsel, Kevin Minoli, wrote that Pruitt's lease, which as drafted provided Pruitt with access to a single unlocked bedroom at a rate of $50 per night for the nights used up to a maximum of 37 nights, was not a violation of federal gift rules because of the limited use provided by the lease and the availability of other temporary housing in the area for a similar price.<ref>https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/4429953-MInoli-Memo.html</ref> However, Minoli emphasized he had only evaluated the narrow terms of the lease itself, not any other activities or benefits provided outside of the lease that the document did not address. Minoli issued a second memorandum on April 4, 2018, providing additional explanation of his determination and the factual information he considered.<ref>https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/4431672-Record-Re-Review-of-Lease2018-04-04-163433.html</ref> As to allegations that Pruitt's daughter stayed in a separate bedroom, Minoli's memorandum did not opine on the implication of those or other allegations explaining that to evaluate them \"would have required factual information that was not before\" the ethics office.<ref>https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/4431672-Record-Re-Review-of-Lease2018-04-04-163433.html at page 3.</ref> Minoli's memorandum also explained that it was limited only to the question of whether the rental agreement constituted a gift and \"did not address other portions of the Federal ethics regulations such as the impartiality rule.<ref>Id.</ref> Other apartments in the building complex, located in a prime location less than a block away from the U.S. Capitol, rented for as much as $5,000 per month.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/04/05/top-epa-ethics-official-says-he-lacked-key-facts-about-pruitts-condo-rental/|title=Top EPA ethics official says he lacked key facts about Pruitt's condo rental|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=April 5, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 5, 2018|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Furthermore, when the EPA ethics official reviewed the undated lease document, the name of the husband who had EPA interests had been struck through by Vicki Hart and her own name had instead been handwritten in.<ref name=\":18\" /> The owners were issued a notice of infraction by the District of Columbia because they lacked a license to rent out rooms.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/dc-officials-cite-pruitt-landlord-questions-rental-linger/story Scott Pruitt's landlord in controversial deal wasn't allowed to rent out room: Officials], [[ABC News]], Matthew Mosk, Benjamin Siegel and Stephanie Ebbs, April 6, 2018. Retrieved April 9, 2018.</ref> Pruitt's landlords gave him notice that he would have to move by July 2017, and changed the locks on the doors when he departed.<ref>[[Eliana Johnson]], [https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/06/pruitt-was-the-kato-kaelin-of-capitol-hill-505658 Lobbyist couple had to change the locks on Pruitt], ''Politico'' (April 6, 2018).</ref> On June 30, 2018, four days before Pruitt's resignation, the New York Times reported that Minoli had referred multiple allegations against Pruitt to the EPA's Inspector General, including aspects of Pruitt's use of the Hart's condo.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/30/climate/pruitt-epa-ethics.html The E.P.A.\u2019s Ethics Officer Once Defended Pruitt. Then He Urged Investigations, Lipton, Eric (June 30, 2018)</ref>\n\nThe townhouse rented by Pruitt was also used as a Republican fundraising hub while he and his adult daughter were living there.<ref name=\"Daily Beast\"/> The Harts hosted a fundraising reception for Pruitt in 2014 (at the expense of $1,616.43) and contributed $1750 to Pruitt's campaign for Oklahoma attorney general over the period 2010\u20132012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/03/30/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-white-house/index.html|title=White House frustrated with EPA's Pruitt|authors=Dan Merica, Pamela Brown, Jim Acosta & Rene Marsh|publisher=CNN|date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, 2017, Pruitt's security detail, unable to reach him, broke down the front door to the apartment building to gain entrance. The EPA eventually reimbursed the condo association $2,460 for the necessary repairs.<ref name=\"Cheniere2\" />\n\nIn July 2018, it was reported that Pruitt had requested help from two EPA aides, both of whom were attorneys, in a dispute that he had with a separate landlord.<ref name=\":32\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/pruitt-aides-reveal-new-details-of-his-spending-and-management-at-epa/2018/07/02/71b87384-7aec-11e8-80be-6d32e182a3bc_story.html|title=Pruitt aides reveal new details of his spending and management at EPA |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=July 2, 2018 |first=Juliet |last=Eilperin |first2=Josh |last2=Dawsey |first3=Brady |last3=Dennis |archive-date=July 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703012152/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/pruitt-aides-reveal-new-details-of-his-spending-and-management-at-epa/2018/07/02/71b87384-7aec-11e8-80be-6d32e182a3bc_story.html?utm_term=.204e235cc1ec}}</ref>\n\n==== No-bid contract to Republican opposition research firm ====\n\nIn December 2017, [[Definers Public Affairs]] was paid $120,000 in a [[no-bid contract]] from the EPA for services which included searching for \"resistance figures\" opposing Pruitt's agenda.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/15/us/politics/epa-scott-pruitt-foia.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |title=Executive at Consultancy Hired by E.P.A. Scrutinized Agency Employees Critical of Trump |first=Eric |last=Lipton |first2=Lisa |last2=Friedman |date=December 15, 2017 |access-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usaspending.gov/transparency/Pages/TransactionDetails.aspx?RecordID=53D2AF0E-B566-47BB-8EB4-728DAC00CEB7&AwardID=59978626&AwardType=C \n|title=DEFINERS CORP EP18H000025 |publisher=[[Office of Management and Budget]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216051716/https://www.usaspending.gov/transparency/Pages/TransactionDetails.aspx?RecordID=53D2AF0E-B566-47BB-8EB4-728DAC00CEB7&AwardID=59978626&AwardType=C |archive-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"MJ\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2017/12/the-epa-hired-a-major-republican-opposition-research-firm-to-track-press-activity/|title=The EPA Hired a Major Republican Opposition Research Firm to Track Press Activity |magazine=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|first=Rebecca|last=Leber |first2=Andy|last2=Kroll |first3=Russ |last3=Choma |date=December 15, 2017 |access-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref> During the bid Definers listed erroneously itself as a \"[[small business|small]] [[disadvantaged business enterprise|disadvantaged business]]\", a preferred designation corrected after Definers received the contract.<ref>Eric Lipton & Lisa Friedman, [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/19/climate/epa-definers-public-affairs-contract.html Consulting Firm Whose Staff Scoured E.P.A. Employees' Emails Loses Media Contract], ''New York Times'' (December 19, 2017).</ref> Definers cancelled the contract following a public backlash.<ref>{{cite news |quote=The Republican media monitoring firm Definers Public Affairs canceled its $120,000 contract with Environmental Protection Agency after a media backlash because of the company's links to GOP opposition research firm America Rising. |title=GOP firm ends controversial media monitoring contract with EPA |first=Emily |last=Holden |date=December 19, 2017 |work=[[Politico]] |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/12/19/definers-public-affairs-epa-contract-304980}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=PounderFile |number=943172637202755584 |date=December 19, 2017 |title=Below is my statement regarding the EPA contract ...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/12/19/epa-to-end-controversial-contract-with-conservative-media-monitoring-firm/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |first=Brady |last=Dennis |date=December 19, 2017 |title=EPA to end controversial contract with conservative 'media monitoring' firm |quote=But an agency spokesman confirmed Tuesday that the EPA and the company had agreed to terminate the contract. In a separate conversation, the company's president, Joe Pounder, said the decision was a mutual one. \"Definers offered EPA a better and more efficient news clipping service that would give EPA's employees real-time news at a lower cost than what previous administrations paid for more antiquated clipping services,\" Pounder said in an emailed statement. \"But it's become clear this will become a distraction.\"}}</ref>\n\n==== Oklahoma associates' hiring and salary increase ====\nIn April 2018, it became known that Pruitt had raised the salaries of two of his closest aides whom he'd brought from Oklahoma, despite rejection of the submitted increases by the White House.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/04/pruitt-epa/557123/|title=Scott Pruitt Bypassed the White House to Give Big Raises to Favorite Aides|last=Meyer|first=Elaina Plott and Robinson|work=The Atlantic|access-date=April 3, 2018}}</ref> Pruitt sought to increase the salary from $107,435 to $164,200 for one aide and from $86,460 to $114,590 for the other. The provision was intended to allow the EPA administrator to hire specialists into unique roles in especially stressed offices.<ref name=\":17\" /> Instead, Pruitt circumvented the process by using a provision of the Safe Drinking Water Act which allowed him to autonomously determine the salaries for the two aides.<ref name=\":17\" /> The compensation of the two staffers was substantially higher than the salaries of staff in similar positions in the Obama administration.<ref name=\":17\" /> The method of raising their pay also allowed both to avoid signing ethics pledges meant to deter conflicts of interest, an issue raised by Democratic Senators [[Tom Carper]] and [[Sheldon Whitehouse]] for consideration of an investigation.<ref name=\":17\" />  While Pruitt claimed in an April 4, 2018 televised interview with Fox News correspondent Ed Henry that he didn't know anything about the raises to his two close aides, the Washington Post reported on April 5, 2018 that two EPA officials and a White House official told The Post that Pruitt instructed staff to award substantial pay boosts to both women, who had worked in different roles for him in Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eilperin|first1=Juliet|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|last3=Dawsey|first3=Josh|title=Scott Pruitt's Job in jeopardy amid expanding ethics issues|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/04/05/top-epa-ethics-official-says-he-lacked-key-facts-about-pruitts-condo-rental/|accessdate=April 6, 2018|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPruitt hired former Oklahoma banker Albert Kelly to head the [[Superfund]] program, which is responsible for cleaning up the nation's most contaminated land.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2017/12/28/scott-pruitt-failed-banker-running-epa-superfund-program/|title=Banned From the Banking Industry for Life, a Scott Pruitt Friend Finds a New Home at the EPA|last=Lerner|first=Sharon|date=December 28, 2017|website=The Intercept|access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060059295|title=EPA: Pruitt's Superfund point man penalized by banking regulators|publisher=[[E&E News]]|access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.apnews.com/649fb04caa70402789c667792019a0f5|title=Adviser to EPA chief cited for federal banking violations|work=AP News|access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> Kelly completely lacked any experience with environmental issues, and had just received a lifetime ban from working in [[banking]], his career until then, due to \"unfitness to serve\".<ref name=\":10\" /> The [[Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation]] (FDIC) also fined him $125,000 and said he had made loans that harmed the bank.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.americanbanker.com/news/epa-official-banned-from-banking-rep-elijah-cummings-wants-answers|title=EPA official banned from banking; congressman wants answers|author=Rob Blackwell|date=September 21, 2017|access-date=January 21, 2017}}</ref> Kelly had a long-standing financial relationship with Pruitt as head of a [[SpiritBank Event Center#Ownership|SpiritBank]], which held extensive outstanding loans to Pruitt.<ref name=\":10\" /> In his new position, Kelly earned $172,100 a year.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n==== Reactions from ex-EPA administrators ====\nFormer EPA Administrators have been critical of Pruitt's tenure. [[William Ruckelshaus]], the first and fifth EPA Administrator under [[Richard Nixon]] and [[Ronald Reagan]] respectively, characterized Pruitt as disbelieving of \"the mission of the agency\" while believing that the EPA was \"over-regulating\". Ruckelshaus accused Pruitt of having an \"ideological approach ... that affects the large contributors in his party in Oklahoma\". Ruckelshaus also described the ideological opposition to the scientific consensus on climate change as a national \"threat\", and that \"lives will be sacrificed\" with further inaction.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kaufman|first1=Alexander|title=EPA Chief Under Nixon And Reagan: GOP's Climate Denial Is 'Killing Everything'|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/ruckelshaus-climate-gop_us_5a6b96f1e4b06e25326783fd|work=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=January 29, 2018}}</ref> Ruckelshaus has also criticized Pruitt for lacking transparency.<ref name=transparency>{{cite news|last1=Ruckelshaus|first1=William|title=Pruitt is turning his back on transparency at the EPA|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/pruitt-is-turning-his-back-on-transparency-at-the-epa/2017/11/01/cd2c1b84-bd88-11e7-8444-a0d4f04b89eb_story.html|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=January 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Carol Browner]], EPA Administrator under [[Bill Clinton]], said, \"Under Pruitt, what they're doing is conscientiously tearing the place down.\" [[Christine Todd Whitman]], EPA Administrator under [[George W. Bush]], said it was \"mindless\" that under Pruitt, policies enacted under Obama were being reversed regardless of their merits or shortcomings. [[Gina McCarthy]], EPA Administrator under Barack Obama, said that Pruitt's EPA had created a \"wealth of uncertainty\" in undoing so many regulations because businesses would not know if they should \"take rules seriously\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kaufman|first1=Alexander|title=Scott Pruitt's First Year Set The EPA Back Anywhere From A Few Years To 3 Decades|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/pruitt-one-year_us_5a610a5ce4b074ce7a06beb4|work=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=January 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe EPA's overhaul of their website under Pruitt has also drawn flak from former administrators. Whitman has argued that the website's credibility was damaged, and that \"undermining science means there is no basis on which to act based on fact, which is dangerous.\" McCarthy described the EPA's website changes as \"censoring scientific data\" and carrying out \"a dangerous assault on public health safeguards that protect all Americans.\"<ref name=TIMEwebsite/>\n\n==== Establishment of legal defense fund ====\nAt a May 16, 2018 hearing of the [[Senate Appropriations Committee]]'s Interior, Environment and Related Agencies Appropriations Subcommittee, Pruitt affirmed that he had set up a legal defense fund that will enable \"friends, allies, lobbyists and others\" to  help defray any legal costs Pruitt may face due to numerous charges of spending and ethics violations.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cama |first1=Timothy |title=Pruitt confirms he has a legal defense fund |url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/387943-pruitt-confirms-he-has-a-legal-defense-fund |website=The Hill |accessdate=July 5, 2018}}</ref> Maryland Democrat [[Chris Van Hollen]] asked Pruitt if sources of donations would be publicly disclosed. Pruitt agreed they would be and added that his attorney would be working with the [[General Accounting Office]] (GAO) to assure the fund met legal requirements. The subcommittee's ranking member, New Mexico's [[Tom Udall]] remarked, \"It's hard to know what to begin with today.  Every day, there seems to be a new scandal, and you at the center of it.\" Subcommittee Chairwoman, Alaska Senator [[Lisa Murkowski]] stated said she's \"constantly asked\" about his management of the agency, continuing, \"I think there are legitimate questions that need to be answered.\"<ref name=Senate />\n\n==== Special favors for family members ====\nIn June 2018, it was revealed that Pruitt had used his official position at the EPA to line up special favors and business opportunities for his wife and daughter.<ref name=\":28\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/scott-pruitt-enlisted-an-epa-aide-to-help-his-wife-find-a-job--at-chick-fil-a/2018/06/05/b798e4e4-5eac-11e8-9ee3-49d6d4814c4c_story.html|title=Scott Pruitt enlisted an EPA aide to help his wife find a job \u2014 with Chick-fil-A|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=June 5, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=June 5, 2018|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|issn=0190-8286|last3=Dawsey|first3=Josh}}</ref><ref name=\":31\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/15/us/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-aides.html|title=For Pruitt Aides, the Boss's Personal Life Was Part of the Job|access-date=June 15, 2018}}</ref> Three months after being sworn in as head of the EPA, Pruitt's scheduler sent an email to [[Dan Cathy]], the chairman, president, and CEO of fast-food chain [[Chick-fil-A]], about \"a potential business opportunity\".<ref name=\":28\" /> The business interest entailed granting Pruitt's wife, Marlyn, license to set up a Chick-fil-A franchise. Pruitt also approached the CEO of Concordia, a New York nonprofit organization which sets up summits to build [[public-private partnership]]s, about hiring his wife to plan summits.<ref name=\":28\" /> Pruitt also had a top EPA aide contact major Republican donors for job opportunities for his wife.<ref name=\":30\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/epa-chief-scott-pruitt-tapped-aide-donors-to-help-wife-land-job-at-conservative-group/2018/06/13/f54c87fa-6db1-11e8-afd5-778aca903bbe_story.html|title=EPA chief Scott Pruitt tapped aide, donors to help wife land job at conservative group|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=June 13, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=June 13, 2018|last2=Dawsey|first2=Josh|issn=0190-8286|last3=Dennis|first3=Brady|last4=Boburg|first4=Shawn}}</ref> When one such donor said that it would be a conflict of interest to offer a job to Pruitt's wife, Pruitt continued to solicit the donor's help in finding job opportunities.<ref name=\":30\" /> The [[Judicial Crisis Network]] ended up hiring Pruitt's wife temporarily after [[Leonard Leo]], executive vice president of the [[Federalist Society]], sent the group her resume.<ref name=\":30\" /> Federal ethics law prohibits public officials from using their public positions for private gain.<ref name=\":28\" /> Pruitt instructed one of his aides to contact the Republican Attorneys General Association about finding a job for his wife, but the aide refused as she considered it an ethics violation.<ref name=\":32\" />\n\nPruitt also instructed at least three EPA aides to help secure a White House internship for his daughter, after which she received such a post.<ref name=\":31\" /> Pruitt obtained Rose Bowl tickets via the head of a firm, Saxum, doing public affairs work for energy companies. Representative [[Elijah Cummings]] requested documents pertaining to assistance Pruitt received to obtain the prized tickets. The Oklahoma City-based firm represented Plains All American Pipeline LP, which has a pending petition at the EPA to permit discharge of hydrostatic test water from a Corpus Christi, Texas, pipeline.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-15/epa-s-pruitt-got-rose-bowl-tickets-democrats-want-to-know-how EPA's Pruitt Snagged Rose Bowl Tickets. Democrats Ask How], ''[[Bloomberg News]]'', Terrence Dopp and Jennifer A. Dlouhy, June 15, 2018. Retrieved June 25, 2018.</ref> Pruitt's security detail accompanied the family to the game.<ref>[https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/30/politics/epa-pruitt-travel-whitehouse-rose-bowl-disneyland/index.html Senator: Pruitt security included Disneyland, Rose Bowl trips], ''[[CNN]]'', Sara Ganim and Rene Marsh, April 3, 2018. Retrieved June 25, 2018.</ref>\n\n=== Resignation ===\nFollowing the assorted ethics and management scandals, Pruitt announced on July 5, 2018, he would be resigning effective July 6. Following Pruitt's resignation, EPA Deputy Administrator [[Andrew R. Wheeler]] became acting administrator.<ref name=globe2018>Brady Dennis & Juliet Eilperin, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/trump-epa-head-steps-down-after-wave-of-ethics-management-scandals/2018/07/05/39f4251a-6813-11e8-bea7-c8eb28bc52b1_story.html Scott Pruitt steps down as EPA head after ethics, management scandals], ''Washington Post'' (July 5, 2018).</ref> The EPA  Office of Inspector General continued its probes of Pruitt after the resignation,<ref>Jory Heckman, [https://federalnewsradio.com/agency-oversight/2018/07/epa-inspector-general-to-continue-pruitt-related-audits-following-resignation/ EPA inspector general to continue Pruitt-related audits following resignation], Federal News Radio (July 12, 2018).</ref><ref>Juana Summers & Sara Ganim, [https://www.cnn.com/politics/live-news/epa-scott-pruitt-resigns/h_1800b39181f455f35e5fb22025f500b4 The EPA's inspector general will continue investigating Pruitt], CNN (July 5, 2018).</ref> but in November 2018 the EPA Inspector General's Office closed two probes as inconclusive because it could not interview Pruitt after his resignation.<ref name=\"Inconclusive\">Juliet Eilperin & Brady Dennis, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/energy-environment/2018/11/29/epa-watchdog-closes-two-probes-into-scott-pruitts-conduct-citing-his-resignation/ EPA watchdog closes two probes into Scott Pruitt's conduct, citing his resignation], ''Washington Post'' (November 29, 2018).</ref> (The office lacks the ability to [[subpoena]] officials who have resigned.<ref name=\"Inconclusive\"/>)\n\n== Post-EPA career ==\nAfter resigning from the EPA, Pruitt has sought to establish an energy consulting business. He promoted overseas coal sales for coal baron [[Joe Craft|Joseph Craft III]]. ''The Washington Post'' reported that Pruitt had meetings with officials from the same industries that he regulated while EPA head. Pruitt's lawyer said that Pruitt had not and would not violate the five-year ban on lobbying the EPA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2018/national/scott-pruitt-epa-expenses/|title=Scott Pruitt: After the High Life, a Job Hunt|author=Juliet Eilperin, Brady Dennis & Josh Dawsey|date=December 28, 2018|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> On April 18, 2019 Pruitt registered as a compensated lobbyist with the Indiana Lobby Registration Commission specifying that he anticipates his lobbying efforts would relate to energy and natural resources. His sole client listed is connected to Sunrise Coal, which operates four coal mines in the state at the time of the filing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Biesecker |first1=Michael |title=Ex-EPA chief Pruitt registers as energy lobbyist in Indiana |url=https://www.apnews.com/a1318acdfba24a0cb02f045254cd2419 |accessdate=20 April 2019 |agency=The Associated Press |date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Pruitt's environmental views ==\n{{See also|Environmental policy of the Donald Trump administration}}\n[[File:Re (32295962460).jpg|thumb|Resist Trump Rally, NYC, 2017]]\n\n=== Rejection of scientific consensus on climate change ===\nPruitt rejects the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus on climate change]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/washington/la-na-essential-washington-updates-1489078393-htmlstory.html|title=House committee advances Obamacare repeal plan but GOP opposition remains|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=March 9, 2017|issn=0458-3035}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/09/us/politics/epa-scott-pruitt-global-warming.html|title=E.P.A. Chief Doubts Consensus View of Climate Change|last=Davenport|first=Coral|date=March 9, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 9, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/07/us/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-trump.html | title=Trump Picks Scott Pruitt, Climate Change Denialist, to Lead E.P.A. | date=December 7, 2016 |access-date=April 30, 2017| work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2017/mar/10/scott-pruitt/epa-head-scott-pruitt-says-carbon-dioxide-not-prim/|title=EPA head Pruitt: CO2 is not a main cause of global warming|work=@politifact|access-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref>  During his January 18, 2017, confirmation hearing to be EPA Administrator, he said that \"the climate is changing, and human activity contributes to that in some manner\".<ref name=\"theclimate\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/01/18/bernie-sanders-to-scott-pruitt-why-is-the-climate-changing/?|title=Bernie Sanders to Scott Pruitt: Why is the climate changing?|date=January 18, 2017|work=[[The Washington Post]]|last2=Erickson|first2=Andee|last1=Mooney|first1=Chris|accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, Pruitt said that he does not believe that human activities, specifically carbon dioxide emissions, are a primary contributor to climate change, a view which is in contradiction with the scientific consensus.<ref name=\"cnbc\"/><ref name=\":4\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4696658/scott-pruitt-epa-carbon-climate-change/|title=EPA Chief Says Carbon Isn't a 'Primary Contributor' to Climate Change|website=Time|access-date=April 30, 2017 |date=March 9, 2017 |first=Justin |last=Worland}}</ref> On June 2, 2017, Pruitt acknowledged that global warming is occurring, and that \"human activity contributes to it in some manner.\" However he added \"Measuring with precision, from my perspective, the degree of human contribution is very challenging.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=David Smith in Washington |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/jun/02/us-paris-climate-deal-epa-chief-scott-pruitt |title=US has nothing to apologize for on climate change, says defiant EPA chief &#124; Environment |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=July 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Pruitt and [[Luther Strange]] authored an [[op-ed]] in the ''[[National Review]]'' criticizing a group of Democratic attorneys general for investigating [[ExxonMobil]] in connection with the [[ExxonMobil climate change controversy]]. In part, Pruitt and Strange wrote:\n\n<blockquote>[The global warming] debate is far from settled. [[Scientific opinion on climate change|Scientists continue to disagree]] about the degree and extent of [[global warming]] and its connection to the actions of mankind. That debate should be encouraged \u2014 in classrooms, public forums, and the halls of Congress. It should not be silenced with threats of prosecution. Dissent is not a crime.<ref name=Strange>{{cite news| url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/435470/climate-change-attorneys-general | title=The Climate-Change Gang | newspaper=[[National Review]] | accessdate=December 8, 2016}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAdditionally, Pruitt joined 12 other Republican attorneys general in writing a letter that stated that \"If it is possible to minimize the risks of climate change, then the same goes for exaggeration. If minimization is fraud, exaggeration is fraud.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/jun/16/gop-ags-dems-climate-alarmists-can-be-prosecuted/?platform=hootsuite|title=GOP AGs warn Dems that if climate skeptics can be prosecuted for 'fraud,' so can alarmists|last=Richardson|first=Valerie|newspaper=The Washington Times|access-date=February 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to one person, Pruitt suggested debates to President Trump, stating to him, \"We can show that most scientists don't even believe in global warming.\" Trump was said to have liked the idea, but the concept was rejected by White House Chief of Staff [[John F. Kelly]], according to several officials involved in the discussions.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/for-pruitt-gaining-trumps-favor--and-keeping-it--came-through-fierce-allegiance/2018/06/16/84025ccc-6fe2-11e8-bd50-b80389a4e569_story.html For Pruitt, gaining Trump's favor \u2014 and keeping it \u2014 came through fierce allegiance], ''[[Washington Post]]'', Josh Dawsey, Juliet Eilperin and Brady Dennis, June 16, 2018. Retrieved June 18, 2018.</ref>\n\nA May 2017 study in ''[[Scientific Reports]]'' examined Pruitt's claim that \"over the past two decades satellite data indicates there has been a leveling off of warming.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Santer|first=Benjamin D.|last2=Solomon|first2=Susan|last3=Wentz|first3=Frank J.|last4=Fu|first4=Qiang|last5=Po-Chedley|first5=Stephen|last6=Mears|first6=Carl|last7=Painter|first7=Jeffrey F.|last8=Bonfils|first8=C\u00e9line|date=May 24, 2017|title=Tropospheric Warming Over The Past Two Decades|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=7|issue=1|pages=2336|doi=10.1038/s41598-017-02520-7|pmid=28539644|issn=2045-2322|pmc=5443760}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/epa-scott-pruitt-climate-change-denial-scientific-paper-nature-scientific-reports-a7754871.html|title=Scientists publish entire study taking down Trump environment chief's climate change views|date=May 25, 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=May 25, 2017}}</ref> The study found that the claim was false: \"[[Satellite temperature measurements]] do not support the claim of a \"leveling off of warming\" over the past two decades\".<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn an interview with Las Vegas television station [[KSNV]], Pruitt, in contradiction to the EPA's own scientific position, argued that an increase in global temperate might not be \"a bad thing\" and that it is \"arrogant\" to say what \"the ideal surface temperature should be in the year 2100.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/02/07/scott-pruitt-asks-if-global-warming-necessarily-is-a-bad-thing/|title=EPA's Scott Pruitt asks whether global warming 'necessarily is a bad thing'|first1=Dino|last1=Grandoni|first2=Brady|last2=Dennis|first3=Chris|last3=Mooney|date=February 8, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=June 6, 2018|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n\nPruitt opposes the [[Paris Agreement]].<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|author=Glenn Kessler|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2017/04/14/epa-administrator-scott-pruitts-claim-that-china-and-india-have-no-obligations-until-2030-under-the-paris-accord/|title=Fact Checker: EPA Administrator Scott Pruitt's claim that China and India have 'no obligations' until 2030 under the Paris Accord|website=Washington Post|date=April 4, 2017}}</ref> He has incorrectly asserted that [[China]] and [[India]] have \"no obligations\" until 2030 under the Paris Agreement.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite news|author=Vanessa Schipani|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2017/03/pruitt-paris-accord/|title=Pruitt on the Paris Accord|work=[[FactCheck.org]]|publisher=Annenberg Public Policy Center|date=March 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Lawsuits against the Environmental Protection Agency===\nPruitt has described himself as \"a leading advocate against the EPA's activist agenda.\"<ref name=\"WashPo8Dec\"/> Upon taking office as Oklahoma Attorney General, Pruitt established a \"federalism unit\" to fight \"unwarranted regulation and systematic overreach\" by the federal government, a first-of-its-kind.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/epa-nominee-has-long-sought-to-scale-back-the-federal-government/2017/01/17/d81c3034-d6b0-11e6-9f9f-5cdb4b7f8dd7_story.html|title=EPA nominee has long sought to scale back the federal government|website=Washington Post|access-date=February 28, 2017}}</ref> [[Andrew P. Miller|Andrew Miller]], a former Democratic attorney general of Virginia who later represented energy companies, recalled a meeting in 2013 with Pruitt and other attorneys general: \"[t]he issue of the day was discussed in a way that allowed Attorney General Pruitt, to his credit, to emerge as one of the leaders, if not the leader with respect to energy issues among the attorneys general.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eenews.net/stories/1060048547|title=EPA: How Scott Pruitt rode a wave of federalism to power|website=www.eenews.net|access-date=February 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs Oklahoma Attorney General, Pruitt sued the EPA at least 14 times. Regulated industry companies or trade associations who were financial donors to Pruitt's political causes were co-parties in 13 of these 14 cases. These cases included suing to block the anti-climate change [[Clean Power Plan]] four times, challenging [[mercury pollution]] limits twice, [[ozone]] pollution limits once, fighting the [[Cross-State Air Pollution Rule]] and the [[Clean Water Rule]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Pruitt v. EPA: 14 Challenges of EPA Rules by the Oklahoma Attorney General|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/01/14/us/politics/document-Pruitt-v-EPA-a-Compilation-of-Oklahoma-14.html?_r=0|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 5, 2017}}</ref> as well as fighting regulations on [[methane emissions]].<ref name=\"WashPo8Dec\" /> Pruitt stated at his Senate confirmation hearing in January 2017 that the EPA has an \"obligation\" to regulate carbon dioxide in accordance with a 2007 Supreme Court case and 2009 EPA decision establishing carbon emissions as a threat to public health.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/314970-five-takeaways-from-pruitts-epa-hearing|title=Five takeaways from Pruitt's EPA hearing|last=Swanson|first=Ian|date=January 18, 2017|work=TheHill|access-date=February 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nUnder Pruitt, Oklahoma sued the EPA and lost on challenges to the EPA's [[regulatory authority]] over mercury and other [[toxin]]s, as well as pollutants responsible for creating regional atmospheric [[haze]]. It challenged the manner in which EPA sued unrelated entities and for what Pruitt termed the agency's \"sue and settle\" practices. Oklahoma further sued and lost after the EPA declined to provide extensive records in a FOIA lawsuit, a request the federal judge hearing the case found to be overly broad and economically burdensome.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.readfrontier.org/stories/pruitt-failed-to-follow-law-on-reporting-outside-attorney-contracts |title=Frontier exclusive: Pruitt failed to follow law on reporting outside attorney contracts |work=[[The Frontier (website)|The Frontier]] |first1=Ziva |last1=Branstetter |first2=Kassie |last2=McClung |date=January 11, 2017 |accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Rulemaking===\nOn March 28, 2017, President Trump signed an [[executive order]] directing Pruitt to rescind the [[Clean Power Plan]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|last2=Rubin|first2=Alissa J.|title=TRUMP SIGNS RULE TO BLOCK EFFORTS ON AIDING CLIMATE \u2013 Executive Order Is Intended to Dismantle Obama Plan on Curbing Carbon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/28/climate/trump-executive-order-climate-change.html|accessdate=May 8, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 29, 2017|page=A1}}</ref> Pruitt has refused to rescind EPA's endangerment finding which determined that [[carbon dioxide]] emissions threaten [[public health]], prompting criticism from some Trump supporters.  Pruitt has stated that a move to rescind would almost certainly be overturned by the courts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=Scott Pruitt Faces Anger From Right Over E.P.A. Finding He Won't Fight|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/12/climate/scott-pruitt-epa-endangerment-finding.html|accessdate=May 9, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 13, 2017|page=A15}}</ref>  On October 10, 2017, Pruitt issued a [[notice of proposed rulemaking]] to repeal the Clean Power Plan.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|last2=Plumer|first2=Brad|title=E.P.A. Announces Repeal of Major Obama-Era Carbon Emissions Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/09/climate/clean-power-plan.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=October 10, 2017|page=A1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=EPA Takes Another Step To Advance President Trump's America First Strategy, Proposes Repeal Of \"Clean Power Plan\"|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-takes-another-step-advance-president-trumps-america-first-strategy-proposes-repeal|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=October 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn June 27, 2017, Pruitt released a proposal to rescind the [[Clean Water Rule]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=E.P.A. Moves to Rescind Contested Water Pollution Regulation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/27/climate/epa-rescind-water-pollution-regulation.html|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 4, 2017|page=D2}}</ref>  On January 31, 2018, Pruitt finalized repeal of the Clean Water Rule.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=E.P.A. Blocks Obama-Era Clean Water Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/31/climate/trump-water-wotus.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=February 1, 2018|page=A16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=EPA and Army Finalize \"Waters of the United States\" Applicability Date {{!}} US EPA|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-and-army-finalize-waters-united-states-applicability-date|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=January 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 1, 2018, Pruitt issued a proposed rule to relax regulation of [[coal ash]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dennis|first1=Brady|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|title=EPA moves to overhaul Obama-era safeguards on coal ash waste|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/03/01/epa-moves-to-overhaul-obama-era-safeguards-on-coal-ash-waste/|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The Washington Post|date=March 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=EPA Proposes First of Two Rules to Amend Coal Ash Disposal Regulations, Saving Up To $100M Per Year in Compliance Costs|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-proposes-first-two-rules-amend-coal-ash-disposal-regulations-saving-100m-year|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=March 1, 2018}}</ref>  Pruitt has finalized a rule postponing new [[effluent guidelines]] on power plants.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Buford|first1=Talia|title=What It's Like Inside the Trump Administration's Regulatory Rollback at the EPA|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/inside-trump-regulatory-rollback-epa|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=[[ProPublica]]|date=December 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=EPA Finalizes Rule to Postpone Steam Electric Power Plant Effluent Guidelines Rule|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-finalizes-rule-postpone-steam-electric-power-plant-effluent-guidelines-rule|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=September 13, 2017}}</ref>  Pruitt has rejected a proposed rule to require [[underground mining (hard rock)|hard rock miners]] to guarantee they can pay [[mine reclamation]] costs.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Preston|first1=Benjamin|title=Trump EPA rule change exploits taxpayers for mine cleanup, critics say|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/dec/17/donald-trump-epa-mining-pollution-rules|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=EPA Determines Risks from Hardrock Mining Industry Minimal and No Need for Additional Federal Requirements|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-determines-risks-hardrock-mining-industry-minimal-and-no-need-additional-federal|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=December 1, 2017}}</ref>  Pruitt has agreed to allow permitting to proceed for the [[Pebble Mine]] on [[Bristol Bay]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schlossberg|first1=Tatiana|title=In Reversal, E.P.A. Eases Path for a Mine Near Alaska's Bristol Bay|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/12/climate/in-reversal-epa-eases-path-for-a-mine-near-alaskas-bristol-bay.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=May 13, 2017|page=A17}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Pruitt announced that he would delay designating which areas met new [[National Ambient Air Quality Standards]] for [[ozone]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=EPA to Extend Deadline for 2015 Ozone NAAQS Area Designations|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-extend-deadline-2015-ozone-naaqs-area-designations|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=June 6, 2017}}</ref>  In August 2017, Pruitt said he would reverse that decision after being sued by 16 state Attorneys General.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=E.P.A. Reverses Course on Ozone Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/03/climate/epa-reverses-course-on-ozone-rule.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=August 4, 2017|page=A11}}</ref>  In March 2018, Pruitt was finally ordered to do so by U.S. District Judge [[Haywood Stirling Gilliam Jr.]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cama|first1=Timothy|title=Court: EPA broke law with smog rule delay|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/377977-court-epa-broke-law-with-smog-rule-delay|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=March 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=Attorney General Becerra Secures Ruling Requiring EPA to Implement Life-Saving Clean Air Protections|url=https://oag.ca.gov/news/press-releases/attorney-general-becerra-secures-ruling-requiring-epa-implement-life-saving|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=California Office of the Attorney General|date=March 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Pruitt began reconsidering new [[United States emission standards|car emissions standards]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grandoni|first1=Dino|title=Trump officials begin review of Obama emissions standards for cars|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/08/10/trump-officials-begin-review-of-obama-emissions-standards-for-cars/|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=Washington Post|date=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Midterm Evaluation of Light-Duty Vehicle Greenhouse Gas Emissions Standards for Model Years 2022\u20132025|url=https://www.epa.gov/regulations-emissions-vehicles-and-engines/midterm-evaluation-light-duty-vehicle-greenhouse-gas|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA}}</ref>  Pruitt has been planning to reduce federally mandated [[corporate average fuel economy]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|last2=Tabuchi|first2=Hiroko|title=E.P.A. Prepares to Roll Back Rules Requiring Cars to Be Cleaner and More Efficient|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/29/climate/epa-cafe-auto-pollution-rollback.html|accessdate=March 30, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=March 30, 2018|page=A1}}</ref>  Pruitt has proposed to repeal heightened emissions standards on \"glider trucks\", which are [[semi-trailer truck]]s that have new bodies but old engines.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipton|first1=Eric|title=How $225,000 Can Help Secure a Pollution Loophole at Trump's E.P.A.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/15/us/politics/epa-pollution-loophole-glider-trucks.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=February 15, 2018|page=A1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Regulations for Greenhouse Gas Emissions from Commercial Trucks & Buses|url=https://www.epa.gov/regulations-emissions-vehicles-and-engines/regulations-greenhouse-gas-emissions-commercial-trucks|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA}}</ref>  Pruitt had requested [[public comment]] on reductions to the [[Renewable Fuel Standard (United States)|Renewable Fuel Standard]] after being encouraged to do so by [[Carl Icahn]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tabuchi|first1=Hiroko|title=Score One for Corn: In Battle Over Biofuel, a Rare Setback for Big Oil|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/30/climate/trump-ethanol-biofuel.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=December 1, 2017|page=B3}}</ref>  Pruitt has since traveled to Iowa twice to promote the repeal of the Clean Water Rule and to promise support of [[corn ethanol]] production.<ref name=nyt18march18/>\n\nPruitt has indefinitely postponed regulations of [[methylene chloride]], [[N-methylpyrrolidone]], and [[trichloroethylene]] that had been called for by the [[Frank R. Lautenberg Chemical Safety for the 21st Century Act]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kaplan|first1=Sheila|title=E.P.A. Delays Bans on Uses of Hazardous Chemicals|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/19/health/epa-toxic-chemicals.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=December 20, 2017|page=A16}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the EPA, [[lead poisoning]] is the number one environmental health threat in the U.S. for children ages 6 and younger.  No new standards have been set since 2001, though it is agreed that the old standards need to be updated.  In December 2017, after Pruitt requested six more years to regulate lead levels, a divided federal appeals court issued a writ of [[mandamus]] ordering Pruitt to regulate lead within the next 90 days.  The Court called the lead paint risks for children \"severe\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=E.P.A. Wanted Years to Study Lead Paint Rule. It Got 90 Days.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/27/us/epa-lead-paint.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=December 28, 2017|page=A10}}</ref>\n\n====Chlorpyrifos ban====\n\n[[Chlorpyrifos]] is a pesticide that is used to kill a number of pests on crops, animals, and in buildings.  In a 2016 report, EPA scientists were not able to find any level of exposure to chlorpyrifos that was safe.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rabin|first1=Roni Caryn|title=A Strong Case Against a Pesticide Does Not Faze E.P.A. Under Trump|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/15/health/pesticides-epa-chlorpyrifos-scott-pruitt.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=May 16, 2017|page=D1}}</ref> The EPA 2016 report states in part \"...this assessment indicates that dietary risks from food alone are of concern ...\"  The report also states that previous published risk assessments for \"chlorpyrifos may not provide a [sufficient] ... human health risk assessment given the potential for neurodevelopmental outcomes.\"<ref name=\"EPA-HQ-OPP-2015-0653\">{{cite web|last1=Drew|first1=Danette|title=Chlorpyrifos Revised Human Health Risk Assessment (2016)|url=https://www.regulations.gov/contentStreamer?documentId=EPA-HQ-OPP-2015-0653-0454&contentType=pdf|website=Regulations.gov|publisher=EPA|accessdate=April 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, 2017, Pruitt denied an administrative petition by the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] and the [[Pesticide Action Network North America]] to ban [[chlorpyrifos]], explaining \"we are returning to using sound science in decision-making \u2013 rather than predetermined results\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=[[Eric Lipton]]|title=E.P.A. Chief, Rejecting Agency's Science, Chooses Not to Ban Insecticide|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/29/us/politics/epa-insecticide-chlorpyrifos.html|accessdate=May 8, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 30, 2017|page=A21}}</ref> On April 5, 2017, [[Earthjustice]] sued the EPA, again demanding that the pesticide be banned.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rabin|first1=Roni Caryn|title=Advocacy Groups Ask for Ban on Common Pesticide|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/05/well/advocacy-groups-ask-for-ban-on-common-pesticide.html|accessdate=May 8, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 6, 2017|page=A14}}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Academy of Pediatrics]] responded to the administration's decision, saying they were \"deeply alarmed\" by Pruitt's decision to allow the [[pesticide]]'s continued use.<ref name=AP30june17>{{cite news|title=EPA chief met with Dow Chemical CEO before deciding not to ban toxic pesticide|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-epa-pesticide-dow-20170627-story.html|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=June 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAsked in April whether he had met with [[Dow Chemical Company]] (who manufactures chlorpyrifos) executives or lobbyists before his decision, an EPA spokesman replied: \"We have had no meetings with Dow on this topic.\" In June, after several [[Freedom of Information Act]] requests, the EPA released a copy of Pruitt's March meeting schedule which showed that a meeting had been scheduled with Dow CEO [[Andrew Liveris]] at a hotel in [[Houston, Texas]], on March 9, 2017.<ref name=AP30june17/>  Internal documents show Pruitt worked closely with the [[American Farm Bureau Federation]] to permit continuation of the pesticide's use.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipton|first1=Eric|last2=Rabin|first2=Roni Caryn|title=E.P.A. Promised 'a New Day' for the Agriculture Industry, Documents Reveal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/18/us/politics/epa-agriculture-industry.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=August 19, 2017|page=A13}}</ref>\n\n====Methane rule====\nOn March 22, 2017, Pruitt had dinner at the Washington [[Old Post Office Pavilion|Trump International Hotel]] with 45 board members of the [[American Petroleum Institute]], where they asked for relief from a new regulation of [[methane]] leaks from their wells, which the industry estimates could cost it over $170 million.<ref name=NYT2july17>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=E.P.A. CHIEF VOIDS OBAMA-ERA RULES IN BLAZING START \u2014 COUNSELED BY INDUSTRY \u2014 Pruitt's Decision-Making Keeps Staff's Experts Largely Sidelined|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/01/us/politics/trump-epa-chief-pruitt-regulations-climate-change.html|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 2, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>  On June 13, Pruitt ordered the rule delayed for two years.<ref name=NYT2july17/>  On July 3, Judges [[David S. Tatel]] and [[Robert L. Wilkins]] of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] vacated that delay, finding Pruitt's order was \"arbitrary\" and \"capricious\" and in violation of the [[Clean Air Act (United States)|Clean Air Act]], over the dissent of Judge [[Janice Rogers Brown]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=Court Blocks E.P.A. Effort to Suspend Obama-Era Methane Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/03/climate/court-blocks-epa-effort-to-suspend-obama-era-methane-rule.html|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 4, 2017|page=A1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=''Clean Air Council v. Pruitt'', No. 17-1145 (D.C. Cir. 2017)|url=http://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/cadc/17-1145/17-1145-2017-07-03.html|website=Justia Law|accessdate=July 5, 2017}}</ref>  In October 2017, a federal magistrate judge ordered the administration to reimpose regulations it had repealed on methane [[gas flare]]s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipton|first1=Eric|title=Courts Thwart Administration's Effort to Rescind Obama-Era Environmental Regulations|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/06/climate/trump-administration-environmental-regulations.html|work=The New York Times|date=October 7, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>\n\n===PFOS and PFOA study publication withheld===\nJanuary 2018 emails between the EPA, the White House, and the [[Department of Health and Human Services]] (DHHS) made public following a [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] request showed that the White House and EPA under Pruitt decided to halt the publication of a study done by the DHHS [[Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry]] (ATSDR). The study, an assessment of the chemical pollutants [[PFOS]] and [[PFOA]], showed that the substances present dangers to human health at far lower levels than the EPA previously deemed safe. An email from a White House official said that the administration feared a \"potential public relations nightmare.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Snider|first1=Annie|title=White House, EPA headed off chemical pollution study|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/14/emails-white-house-interfered-with-science-study-536950|website=Politico|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe withholding of the study prompted widespread criticism from congressional Democrats, as well as at least three congressional Republicans. These critics called upon the EPA to provide answers to questions about suppression of scientific assessments on chemical pollution of water.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|last1=Snider|first1=Annie|title=EPA move on chemical study may trip up Pruitt|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/16/pruitt-chemical-study-epa-590947|website=Politico|accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPruitt conceded that his agency should take \"concrete action\" related to chemicals like PFAS, but testified that he was unaware of any delay in the release of the study.<ref name=Senate>[https://www.eenews.net/greenwire/2018/05/16/stories/1060081889 Legal defense fund in place \u2014 Pruitt], ''[[E&E News]]'', Kevin Bogardus, May 16, 2018. Retrieved May 17, 2018.</ref> At a May 2018 \"leadership summit\" on PFOA, PFOS and related chemicals attended by Pruitt,<ref name=\"auto\"/> some reporters were barred from attending, including those from  ''[[Politico]]'' (which first reported on the release of the emails), [[CNN]], and [[E&E News]] (which writes on environmental issues). An [[Associated Press]] correspondent, Ellen Knickmeyer, was physically ejected from the meeting room, and U.S. Representative [[Dan Kildee]] of Michigan, who represents a district dealing with the [[Flint water crisis]], said that a member of his staff was barred from the meeting. Kildee wrote to the EPA's inspector general to ask whether any open meetings laws were violated.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|last1=Ebbs|first1=Stephanie|title=EPA continues to face questions about blocking public from chemicals summit|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/epa-criticized-blocking-reporters-chemicals-summit/story?id=55362966|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=May 24, 2018}}</ref> An EPA spokesman asserted that the summit was not subject to the [[Federal Advisory Committee Act]].<ref>[https://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/for-second-day-reporters-barred-from-epa-event-on-toxic-chemicals For Second Day, Reporters Barred From EPA Event On Toxic Chemicals], ''[[Talking Points Memo]]'', Matt Shuham, May 23, 2018. Retrieved May 24, 2018.</ref> Senator [[Tom Udall]], in response, wrote a letter to Pruitt stating, \"This intimidation of journalists seeking to cover a federal official presiding over important policy-making is un-American and unacceptable. ... Clean drinking water is a public health issue that does not belong behind closed doors.\"<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nPruitt married Marlyn Lloyd in 1990, at [[Southeast Christian Church (Louisville, Kentucky)|Southeast Christian Church]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"LHL\"/> They have two children: daughter McKenna and son Cade.<ref name=everything>{{cite news | title=Everything You Need to Know About Donald Trump's Pick to Head EPA, Scott Pruitt | url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/donald-trumps-pick-head-epa-scott-pruitt/story?id=44046481 | publisher=[[ABC News]] | first1=Veronica |last1=Stracqualursi | date=December 8, 2016 |accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPruitt is [[Southern Baptist Convention|Southern Baptist]]. According to the Oklahoma Office of Attorney General, the Pruitts are members of the First Baptist Church of [[Broken Arrow, Oklahoma|Broken Arrow]], where Pruitt served as a [[deacon]]. Pruitt was a trustee at the [[Southern Baptist Theological Seminary]]. He expressed his views regularly on the radio in Tulsa, including advocating for passage of constitutional amendments to ban abortion and gay marriage, and objecting to what he feels is the suppression of majority religious beliefs.<ref name=Baptist>[https://baptistnews.com/article/trump-picks-a-southern-baptist-to-run-the-epa/#.WYsrx-mQzIV Trump picks climate-change denier, Southern Baptist to run the EPA], ''[[Baptist News Global]]'', Bob Allen, December 28, 2016. Retrieved March 19, 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.politico.com/story/2018/03/02/scott-pruitt-epa-evolution-theory-abortion-gay-marriage-433284 Pruitt tapes revealed: Evolution's a 'theory,' 'majority' religions under attack], ''[[Politico]]'', Emily Holden & Alex Guillen, March 2, 2018. Retrieved April 11, 2018.</ref>   In 2005, Pruitt told a radio interviewer that there are not \"sufficient scientific facts to [[creation-evolution controversy|establish]] the theory of [[evolution]].\"<ref name=newyorker2april18/>\n\n==Electoral history==\n'''''November 4, 2014, general election results for Attorney General'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Candidates\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|'''Scott Pruitt'''\n|Republican Party\n|n/a\n|100.00%\n|}\n\n'''''November 2, 2010, general election results for Attorney General'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Candidates\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|'''Scott Pruitt'''\n|Republican Party\n|666,407\n|65.11%\n|-\n|Jim Priest\n|Democratic Party\n|357,162\n|34.89%\n|}\n\n'''''July 27, 2010, Republican primary election results for Attorney General'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Candidates\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|'''Scott Pruitt'''\n|Republican Party\n|134,335\n|56.05%\n|-\n|Ryan Leonard\n|Republican Party\n|105,343\n|43.95%\n|}\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:95%; text-align:right;\"\n|+''August 22, 2006 Republican primary election results for Lt. Governor''\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Candidates\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|Party\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|Votes\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|'''Todd Hiett'''\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|'''66,220'''\n|'''50.92%'''\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|Scott Pruitt\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|63,817\n|49.08%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=\"6\"|Source:<ref>{{cite web | title=Lieutenant Governor Republican Runoff Primary Election \u2013 August 22, 2006 | url=https://www.ok.gov/elections/documents/06reprun.pdf | date=September 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:95%; text-align:right;\"\n|+''July 25, 2006 Republican primary election results for Lt. Governor''\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Candidates\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|Party\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|Votes\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|Todd Hiett\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|76,634\n|42.82%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|Scott Pruitt\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|60,367\n|33.73%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|Nancy Riley\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|41,984\n|23.46%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=\"6\"|Source:<ref>{{cite web | title=Lieutenant Governor Republican Primary Election \u2013 July 25, 2006 | url=https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/06reppri.pdf | date=September 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n|}\n'''''November 5, 2002, general election results for Oklahoma Senate, District 54'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Candidates\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|'''Scott Pruitt'''\n|Republican Party\n|n/a\n|100.00%\n|}\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:95%; text-align:right;\"\n|+''December 11, 2001, special election results for United States House of Representatives, District 1''\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Candidates\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|Party\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|Votes\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|'''John Sullivan'''\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|'''19,018'''\n|'''45.53%'''\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|Cathy Keating\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|12,736\n|30.49%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|Scott Pruitt\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|9,513\n|22.77%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|George E. Banasky\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|296\n|0.71%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|Evelyn R. Rogers\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|210\n|0.50%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=\"6\"|Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegreenpapers.com/G02/OK.phtml|title=Oklahoma 2002 Midterm Election|publisher=The Green Papers |date= September 8, 2003 |access-date=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n'''''November 3, 1998, general election results for Oklahoma Senate, District 54'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Candidates\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|'''Scott Pruitt'''\n|Republican Party\n|9,971\n|63.51%\n|-\n|Shannon Clark\n|Democratic Party\n|5,728\n|36.49%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=\"6\"|Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/98genleg.html | title=General Election Results November 3, 1998 |publisher=}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:95%; text-align:right;\"\n|+''September 5, 1998, Republican runoff election results for Oklahoma Senate, District 54''\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Candidates\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|Party\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|Votes\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|'''Scott Pruitt'''\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|'''2,326'''\n|'''56.33%'''\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|Gerald Wright\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|1,803\n|43.67%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=\"6\"|Source:<ref name=ballotpedia/>\n|}\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:95%; text-align:right;\"\n|+''August 25, 1998, Republican primary election results for Oklahoma Senate, District 54''\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Candidates\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|Party\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|Votes\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|Scott Pruitt\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|1,959\n|48.94%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|Gerald Wright\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|1,820\n|45.47%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|Douglas E. Meehan\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|224\n|5.59%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=\"6\"|Source:<ref>{{cite web | title=Republican Primary Election Results August 25, 1998 | url=https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/98reppri.html#SEN | date=November 26, 2008 }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q7437083|c=Category:Scott Pruitt|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|s=no|wikt=no|species=no}}\n* {{C-SPAN|epruitt}}\n* [https://www.epa.gov/aboutepa/epas-administrator EPA Administrator Scott Pruitt]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20161227151320/http://www.scottpruitt.com/ Archive of Scott Pruitt campaign website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Oklahoma state elections, 2006#Attorney general|James Dunn]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[Attorney General of Oklahoma]] | years = [[Oklahoma state elections, 2010#Attorney General|2010]], [[Oklahoma state elections, 2014#Attorney General|2014]]}}\n{{s-inc | recent}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Drew Edmondson]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Attorney General of Oklahoma]] | years = January 10, 2011 \u2013 February 17, 2017}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Cara Rodriguez]]<br>{{small|Acting}}<br>[[Michael J. Hunter|Mike Hunter]]<br>{{small|permanent}}}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Gina McCarthy]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title  = [[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency]] | years = February 17, 2017 \u2013 July 6, 2018}}\n{{s-aft | after  = [[Andrew R. Wheeler|Andrew Wheeler]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Oklahoma Attorneys General}}\n{{EPA}}\n{{Trump cabinet}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pruitt, Scott}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Administrators of the United States Environmental Protection Agency]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2006 United States elections]]\n[[Category:Climate change denial]]\n[[Category:Georgetown College (Kentucky) alumni]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Republicans]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma lawyers]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma Republicans]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma state senators]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Danville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Southern Baptists]]\n[[Category:Trump administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:University of Kentucky alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Tulsa College of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Kentucky]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the race car driver|Scott Pruett}}\n{{short description|14th Administrator of the EPA}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Scott Pruitt\n| image = File:Scott_Pruitt,_EPA_official_portrait_(cropped).jpg\n| office = 14th [[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency]]\n| deputy = Andrew Wheeler\n| term_start = February 17, 2017\n| term_end = July 6, 2018\n| predecessor = [[Gina McCarthy]]\n| successor = [[Andrew R. Wheeler|Andrew Wheeler]]\n| president = [[Donald Trump]]\n| office1 = 17th [[Attorney General of Oklahoma]]\n| governor1 = [[Mary Fallin]]\n| term_start1 = January 10, 2011\n| term_end1 = February 17, 2017\n| predecessor1 = [[Drew Edmondson]]\n| successor1 = [[Michael J. Hunter|Mike Hunter]]\n| office2    = Member of the<br>[[Oklahoma Senate]]\n| constituency2 = 54th district (1999\u20132003)<br>36th district (2003\u201307)\n| term_start2 = January 5, 1999\n| term_end2 = January 2, 2007\n| predecessor2 = [[Gerald Wright (politician)|Gerald Wright]]\n| successor2 = [[Bill Brown (American politician)|Bill Brown]]\n| birth_name = Edward Scott Pruitt<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbts.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2010/11/Catalog_directory_Aug2013.pdf|title=Southern Seminary Catalog \u2013 Directory, 2013\u20132014|publisher=|accessdate=June 6, 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|5|9}}\n| birth_place = [[Danville, Kentucky|Danville]], [[Kentucky]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = Marlyn Pruitt (1992\u2013present)\n| children = 2\n| education = [[University of Kentucky]]\n[[Georgetown College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[University of Tulsa]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n}}\n\n'''Edward Scott Pruitt''' (born May 9, 1968) is an American lawyer, lobbyist and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician from the state of [[Oklahoma]]. He served as the fourteenth [[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) from February 17, 2017, to July 6, 2018. He was nominated for the EPA position by President [[Donald Trump]] and was confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] to lead the EPA in a 52\u201346 vote. Pruitt [[Climate change denial|rejects]] the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus that human-caused carbon dioxide emissions are a primary contributor to climate change]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-ten-worst-things-scott-pruitts-epa-has-already-done|title=The Ten Worst Things Scott Pruitt's EPA Has Already Done|author=Jay Michaelson|date=December 29, 2017|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|access-date=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPruitt represented [[Tulsa County, Oklahoma|Tulsa]] and [[Wagoner County, Oklahoma|Wagoner]] counties in the [[Oklahoma Senate]] from 1998 until 2006.  In 2010, Pruitt was elected [[Attorney General of Oklahoma]]. In that role, he was pro-life, opposed [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|same-sex marriage]], the [[Affordable Care Act]], and [[environmental regulations]] as a self-described \"leading advocate against the EPA's activist agenda.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Brief biography of Attorney General Scott Pruitt|url=https://www.ok.gov/oag/Media/About_the_AG/|publisher=Oklahoma Office of the Attorney General E. Scott Pruitt|accessdate=February 4, 2017|archivedate=January 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108114336/https://www.ok.gov/oag/Media/About_the_AG/}}</ref> In his campaigns for [[Oklahoma Attorney General]], Pruitt received major corporate and employee [[campaign finance in the United States|campaign contributions]] from the [[fossil fuel industry]], taking in at least $215,574 between 2010 and 2014 even though he ran unopposed in the latter year. As Oklahoma's Attorney General, Pruitt sued the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] at least 14 times regarding the agency's actions. In 2012, Pruitt was elected as chairman of the Republican Attorneys General Association and re-elected for a second term in February 2013.\n\nBy July 2018, Pruitt was under at least 14 separate federal investigations by the [[Government Accountability Office]], the EPA inspector general, the [[Office of Management and Budget|White House Office of Management and Budget]], the [[United States Office of Special Counsel|U.S. Office of Special Counsel]], and two House committees over his spending habits, conflicts of interest, extreme secrecy, and management practices. Pruitt made frequent use of first-class travel as well as frequent charter and military flights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-environment/2019/05/16/epa-watchdog-suggests-agency-recover-p |title=EPA watchdog suggests agency recover $124,000 in Pruitt's 'excessive' travel expenses; Agency rejects the idea, calling 'cost recovery inappropriate' because officials had approved Pruitt's trips at the time |authors=Juliet Eilperin and Brady Dennis |date=May 16, 2019 |website=washingtonpost.com |publisher= |access-date=16 May 2019 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/ex-epa-chief-scott-pruitt-spent-nearly-124-000-excessive-n1006491 |title=Ex-EPA chief Scott Pruitt spent nearly $124,000 on 'excessive airfare,' agency says; The inspector general's report found there was not \"sufficient justification to support security concerns requiring the use of first- and business-class travel.\" |authors=Laura Strickler and Adiel Kaplan |date=16 May 2019 |website=nbcnews.com |publisher= |access-date=16 May 2019 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/16/politics/pruitt-airfare-inspector-general/index.html |title=Scott Pruitt wasted nearly $124,000 on first- and business-class travel, EPA IG says |author=Gregory Wallace |date=16 May 2019 |website=CNN |publisher= |access-date=16 May 2019 |quote=}}</ref>  As EPA administrator, Pruitt leased a condo in Washington, D.C., at a deeply discounted rate from a lobbyist whose clients were regulated by the EPA. Pruitt further caused ethics concerns by circumventing the White House and using a narrow provision of the Safe Drinking Water Act to autonomously give raises to his two closest aides of approximately $28,000 and $57,000 each, which were substantially higher than salaries paid to those in similar positions in the Obama administration, and which allowed both to avoid signing conflicts of interest pledges. By June 2018, amid a steady succession of revelations of misconduct, a growing chorus of conservatives had begun suggesting that Pruitt should resign. On July 5, 2018, Pruitt announced he would resign from office on July 6, leaving [[Andrew R. Wheeler]] as the acting head of the agency.<ref name=globe2018/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/05/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-resigns/index.html|title=EPA chief Scott Pruitt resigns amid ethics scandals|author1-link=Jeremy Diamond (journalist)|author1=Jeremy Diamond |author2=Eli Watkins |author3=Juana Summers|work=CNN|access-date=July 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/07/05/scott-pruitts-full-resignation-letter-to-president-trump.html|title=Scott Pruitt's full resignation letter to President Trump|date=July 5, 2018|work=Fox News|access-date=July 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPruitt was born in 1968 in [[Danville, Kentucky]], the eldest of three siblings,<ref name=\"EE\"/> and moved to Lexington as a boy. There, his father, Edward, owned steak houses and his mother, Linda Pruitt Warner,<ref name=\"LHL\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kentucky.com/news/local/counties/fayette-county/article119508878.html|title=Trump's pick to lead EPA grew up in Lexington, played baseball at Lafayette, UK|publisher=Lexington Herald Leader|author=Blackford, Linda|date=December 8, 2016}}</ref> was a homemaker.<ref name=\"EE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060047801|title=From 'The Possum' to EPA boss|publisher=E&E News|date=January 4, 2017|author=Bravender, Robin}}</ref><ref name=newyorker2april18>{{cite news|last1=Talbot|first1=Margaret|authorlink=Margaret Talbot|title=Scott Pruitt's Dirty Politics|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/04/02/scott-pruitts-dirty-politics|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=[[The New Yorker]]|issue=April 2, 2018}}</ref> He was a football and baseball player at [[Lafayette High School (Lexington, Kentucky)|Lafayette High School]], earning a baseball scholarship to the [[University of Kentucky]], where he played second base. After a year, he transferred to [[Georgetown College (Kentucky)|Georgetown College]] in Kentucky and graduated in 1990 with bachelor's degrees in political science and communications.<ref name=baseball>{{cite news|last1=Blackford|first1=Linda|title=Trump's pick to lead EPA grew up in Lexington, played baseball at Lafayette, UK|url=http://www.kentucky.com/news/local/counties/fayette-county/article119508878.html|accessdate=July 26, 2017|newspaper=Lexington Herald-Leader|date=December 7, 2016}}</ref> He then moved to [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], where he attended the [[University of Tulsa College of Law]] and earned a [[Juris Doctor]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Alec|title=The Trump Cabinet: Who is Scott Pruitt?|url=https://lawstreetmedia.com/blogs/politics-blog/the-trump-cabinet-scott-pruitt/|accessdate=February 7, 2017|publisher=Law Street|date=December 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Legal experience==\n\nAfter law school Pruitt started a solo legal practice in Tulsa that he named \"Christian Legal Services,\" which focused on defending Christians in religious liberty cases.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Michaelson|first1=Jay|title=Trump's EPA Pick Blends Conservative Christianity with Anti-Environmental Activism|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/trumps-epa-pick-blends-conservative-christianity-with-anti-environmental-activism|accessdate=April 6, 2018|website=Daily Beast|date=January 23, 2017}}</ref>  Pruitt worked as a lawyer for five years before running for state senate.\n\n==Early career==\n\nPruitt was elected to the [[Oklahoma Senate]] in 1998, representing [[Tulsa County, Oklahoma|Tulsa]] and [[Wagoner County, Oklahoma|Wagoner]] counties.<ref name=\"HistoricMembers\">{{cite web | title=Historic Members | url=http://www.oksenate.gov/Senators/# | publisher=Oklahoma State Senate | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> In 1999 and again in 2005, Pruitt introduced legislation to establish fathers' \"property rights\" over unborn fetuses, which meant that a pregnant woman would be required to get the consent of the father prior to an abortion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/scott-pruitt-abortion_us_5b06ce55e4b05f0fc845a4aa|title=Scott Pruitt Twice Introduced Anti-Abortion Bills Giving Men 'Property Rights' Over Fetuses|last=Kaufman|first=Alexander C.|date=May 24, 2018|work=Huffington Post|access-date=May 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/environment/2018/05/scott-pruitt-tried-to-give-men-property-rights-over-fetuses/|title=Scott Pruitt tried to give men \"property rights\" over fetuses|work=Mother Jones|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> After two years in the Senate, Pruitt was selected to serve as the Republican whip from 2001 to 2003. He was then selected to serve as the Republican Assistant Floor Leader, a position he held until he left the Senate in 2006.<ref name=ballotpedia>{{cite web | url=https://ballotpedia.org/Scott_Pruitt | title=Scott Pruitt \u2013 Ballotpedia | publisher=}}</ref> During that time he also sat as the chair of a task force for the [[American Legislative Exchange Council]].<ref name=governing2003>{{cite news|url=http://www.governing.com/topics/politics/What-Makes-Alec-Smart.html|title=What Makes Alec Smart?|date=October 2003|work=[[Governing (magazine)|Governing]]|first=Alan|last=Greenblatt}}</ref>  There, he worked to put limits on workers' compensation and sponsored a reform bill that sought to impose drug tests on workers who were involved in job injuries or accidents.<ref name=newyorker2april18/>\n\nIn 2001, while a freshman state legislator, Pruitt sought his party's nomination to succeed [[Steve Largent]] as the representative for [[Oklahoma's 1st congressional district]] but was unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite web|title=District 1: Previous Election Results|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/elections/OK/districts/OK01/profile/|website=Oklahoma: 2016 Election Center|publisher=The Washington Times|accessdate=February 7, 2017}}</ref>  In 2003, after his unsuccessful congressional campaign, Pruitt bought a share in a Triple-A baseball team, the Oklahoma City RedHawks, partnering with major Republican donor [[Robert A. Funk]] (reportedly for $11.5 million).<ref name=newyorker2april18/>  Pruitt, whose annual salary as a state senator was $38,400, financed his part of the purchase with a loan from SpiritBank.<ref name=newyorker2april18/>  In 2010, they sold the team for an undisclosed profit.<ref name=newyorker2april18/>\n\nIn October 2003, while a state senator, Pruitt purchased a home in Oklahoma City through a [[shell company]], Capitol House L.L.C., in which six partners held equal shares. The buyers included lobbyist Justin Whitefield, healthcare executive Jon Jiles, Robert Funk (who was Pruitt's PAC chairman), and attorney Ken Wagner. The home was purchased at about a $100,000 discount from its purchase price of a year earlier and included its furnishings. The seller was Marsha Lindsey, a lobbyist who advocated on behalf of a telecommunications company. Lindsey's loss was partly offset by her employer's retirement package. Pruitt and Whitefield both lived at the home while on business in the state capital. At the time, Whitefield was a registered lobbyist for industry-aligned groups that sought legislative changes to Oklahoma's [[workers' compensation]] laws; Pruitt was the major legislative supporter of these efforts. The home was sold by the L.L.C. in 2005, for $470,000. Pruitt failed to publicly disclose his financial relationships with Whitefield and the others, which were revealed by the press in 2018.<ref>Steve Eder & Hiroko Tabuchi [https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/03/us/scott-pruitt-lobbyist-house.html Pruitt's Coziness With Lobbyists Includes Secretly Buying a House With One], ''New York Times'' (May 3, 2018).</ref> In 2017, Wagner was hired by Pruitt as the EPA's state and regional affairs adviser.<ref>[https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060053058 Pruitt's friend joins agency as senior adviser], ''[[E&E News]]'', Kevin Bogardus and Mike Soraghan, April 13, 2017. Retrieved May 5, 2018.</ref>\n\n==Oklahoma Attorney General==\n{{See also|Oklahoma state elections, 2006#Lieutenant governor|Oklahoma state elections, 2010#Attorney General|Oklahoma elections, 2014#Attorney General}}\nIn 2006 Pruitt sought the Republican nomination to replace outgoing Republican [[Mary Fallin]] as [[Lieutenant Governor of Oklahoma]].  He was unsuccessful; Fallin later won the gubernatorial election and is the incumbent [[Governor of Oklahoma|Governor]].\nIn 2010, Pruitt again ran for the position of Attorney General of Oklahoma. He won the Republican primary on July 27, 2010, with 56.05% of the vote, defeating Ryan Leonard.<ref>{{cite web | title=Summary Results \u2013 Primary Election \u2013 July 27, 2010 | url=https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/10pri.html | publisher=Oklahoma State Election Board | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Pruitt went on to defeat the Democratic nominee, [[Oklahoma City]] defense attorney Jim Priest, in the November 2, 2010, general election with 65.11% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web | title=Summary Results \u2013 General Election \u2013 November 2, 2010 | url=https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/10gen.html | publisher=Oklahoma State Election Board | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref>  In 2014 Pruitt ran unopposed in both the primary and general elections.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Krehbiel | first1=Randy | title=Pruitt Re-Election Campaign Raised $300,000 After it Learned He Would Have No Opponent | url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/government/pruitt-re-election-campaign-raised-after-it-learned-he-would/article_74bdafd2-8020-5fc5-aaa9-5e6694c01589.html | date=December 16, 2014 | website=tulsaworld.com | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nAfter winning election in 2010, Pruitt dissolved the Environmental Protection Unit in the Attorney General's office.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pooley|first1=Eric|title=Donald Trump's EPA Pick Imperils Science\u2014And Earth|url=http://time.com/4635162/scott-pruitt-science-denial/|accessdate=February 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Dennis|first1=Brady|last2=Weigel|first2=David|title=EPA nominee Scott Pruitt won't say if he would recuse himself from his own lawsuits against the agency|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/can-the-epas-main-antagonist-become-its-next-leader/2017/01/17/d24308ca-dcf7-11e6-ad42-f3375f271c9c_story.html|website=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=February 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Washington|first1=Wayne|title=Florida congressman gets little traction on legislation to abolish EPA|url=http://www.mypalmbeachpost.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/florida-congressman-gets-little-traction-legislation-abolish-epa/eRqNfdiat9JEoo1E4O0xHM/|work=[[The Palm Beach Post]]|accessdate=February 15, 2017}}</ref> He stated a desire to increase operational efficiency and shifted the attorneys responsible for environmental protection to the Attorney General's Public Protection Unit and the Solicitor General's Unit. Pruitt stated that \"the [[Oklahoma Department of Environmental Quality]] \u2013 not the Office of Attorney General \u2013 has primary responsibility for implementing and enforcing environmental laws in Oklahoma.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Hearing entitled, \"Nomination of Attorney General Scott Pruitt to be Administrator of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency\"|url=https://www.epw.senate.gov/public/_cache/files/6d95005c-bd1a-4779-af7e-be831db6866a/scott-pruitt-qfr-responses-01.18.2017.pdf|publisher=Senate Environment and Public Works Committee|accessdate=February 15, 2017|date=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPruitt instead created a \"Federalism Unit\" in the Attorney General's office dedicated to fighting President [[Barack Obama]]'s regulatory agenda and suing the administration over its immigration policy, the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], and the [[Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]].<ref name=\"WashPo8Dec\">{{cite news | last1=Mooney| first1=Chris | last2=Dennis | first2=Brady | last3=Mufson | first3=Steven|title=Trump names Scott Pruitt, Oklahoma attorney general suing EPA on climate change, to head the EPA | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2016/12/07/trump-names-scott-pruitt-oklahoma-attorney-general-suing-epa-on-climate-change-to-head-the-epa/ | accessdate=December 9, 2016 | work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=December 8, 2016|page=A1}}</ref>\n\nPruitt was successful in raising campaign contributions from the energy industry, helping him to become chairman of the Republican Attorneys General Association.<ref name=NYT8Dec/> The [[oil and gas industry]] contributed over $300,000 to Pruitt's campaigns over the years.<ref name=\"300K\">{{cite web|last1=Dennis|first1=Brady|title=Judge orders EPA nominee Pruitt to release emails with oil, gas, coal industry|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/politics/ct-scott-pruitt-epa-emails-20170216-story.html|website=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=February 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Pruitt kept Oklahoma out of the [[2010 United States foreclosure crisis#National Mortgage Settlement|mortgage settlement]] reached by 49 other states with five national lenders ([[Ally Financial]]/GMAC, [[Bank of America]], [[Citigroup|Citi]], [[JPMorgan Chase]], and [[Wells Fargo]]), with Pruitt citing differing philosophies of government.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://newsok.com/oklahoma-is-lone-maverick-in-national-mortgage-settlement-signed-by-49-states/article/3647630|title=Oklahoma is lone maverick in national mortgage settlement signed by 49 states | work=[[The Oklahoman]] | accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Pruitt brought a lawsuit targeting the Affordable Care Act, ''Oklahoma [[ex rel.]] E. Scott Pruitt v. Burwell'', alleging that federal cost-sharing subsidies were not authorized by the Act.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://newsok.com/lawsuits-by-oklahoma-attorney-general-scott-pruitt-others-challenge-obamacare-subsidies/article/3911239 | title=Lawsuits by Oklahoma Attorney General Scott Pruitt, others challenge Obamacare subsidies|work=The Oklahoman|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Allen\">Silas Allen, [http://newsok.com/lawsuits-by-oklahoma-attorney-general-scott-pruitt-others-challenge-obamacare-subsidies/article/3911239 Scott Pruitt was first state AG to challenge Obamacare subsidies], ''Oklahoman'' (December 7, 2016).</ref> In ''[[King v. Burwell]]'' (2015), a decision addressing identical claims brought by other Republican attorneys general,<ref>Chris Casteel, [http://newsok.com/article/5387985 U.S. Supreme Court won't add Oklahoma case to crucial Affordable Care Act review], ''Oklahoman'' (January 27, 2015).</ref><ref>Lisa Schencker, [http://www.modernhealthcare.com/article/20150126/NEWS/301269848 Supreme Court rejects second insurance subsidy case, focus to remain on King v. Burwell], ''Modern Healthcare'' (January 26, 2015).</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=McIntyre | first=Adrianna | date=October 1, 2014 | title=High court declines to review Oklahoma case against Affordable Care Act | url=https://www.vox.com/2014/10/1/6875579/another-court-strikes-down-obamacare-subsidies-in-36-states |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] | publisher =[[Vox Media]]}}</ref> the Supreme Court upheld the federal subsidies, holding that they were authorized under the Act.<ref>Adam Liptak, [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/26/us/obamacare-supreme-court.html Supreme Court Allows Nationwide Health Care Subsidies], ''New York Times'' (June 25, 2015).</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[Harold Hamm]], CEO of [[Continental Resources]], co-chaired Pruitt's reelection campaign.<ref name=NYT8Dec>{{cite news | last1=Coral Davenport | last2=Eric Lipton|title=Trump Picks Scott Pruitt, Climate Change Denialist, to Lead E.P.A.| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/07/us/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-trump.html | accessdate=December 9, 2016 | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=December 8, 2016 | ref=NYT8Dec | page=A1}}</ref> Pruitt ran unopposed in the 2014 primary election and won the November 2014 election for a new term as Attorney General.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ballotpedia.org/Oklahoma_Attorney_General_election,_2014|title=Oklahoma Attorney General election, 2014|publisher=Ballotpedia.org|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref> Pruitt then jointly filed a lawsuit against a federal regulation alongside the [[Oklahoma Gas & Electric]] and an energy industry group funded by Hamm.<ref name=NYT8Dec/>\n\nPruitt's office sued the EPA to block its [[Clean Power Plan]] and [[Waters of the United States]] rule.<ref name=WashPo8Dec/> Pruitt also sued the EPA on behalf of Oklahoma utilities unwilling to take on the burdens of additional regulation of their coal-fired plants, and criticized the agency in a congressional hearing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/oklahoma-attorney-general-scott-pruitt-criticizes-epa-at-congressional-hearing/article/3904818|title=Oklahoma Attorney General Scott Pruitt criticizes EPA at congressional hearing|work=The Oklahoman|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stateimpact.npr.org/oklahoma/2013/10/03/an-insiders-guide-to-oklahoma-attorney-general-scott-pruitts-war-with-the-epa/|title=An Insider's Guide to Oklahoma Attorney General Scott Pruitt's War With the EPA|work=StateImpact Oklahoma|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref> As of June 2014, all of Pruitt's lawsuits against the EPA had failed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stateimpact.npr.org/oklahoma/2014/06/12/court-losses-wont-deter-attorney-general-scott-pruitt-in-his-fight-with-the-epa/|title=Court Losses Won't Deter Attorney General Scott Pruitt In His Fight With The EPA|work=StateImpact Oklahoma|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref> By January 2017, Pruitt had sued the EPA 13 times.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mosbergen|first1=Dominique|title=Scott Pruitt Has Sued The Environmental Protection Agency 13 Times. Now He Wants To Lead It.|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/scott-pruitt-environmental-protection-agency_us_5878ad15e4b0b3c7a7b0c29c|accessdate=February 7, 2017|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=January 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Pruitt supported the Oklahoma legislature's bid to join four other states trying to restrict [[medical abortions]] by limiting or banning off-label uses of drugs, via House Bill 1970. After the state Supreme Court upheld a lower court's ruling that the abortion law was unconstitutional, Pruitt requested that the [[United States Supreme Court]] review the case. Pruitt was unhappy with the [[United States Supreme Court]]'s rejection of the Oklahoma case.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.newson6.com/story/23134460/attorney-general-files-brief-in-supreme-court-review-of-oklahoma-abortion-law|title=Attorney General Supports Supreme Court Review of Oklahoma Abortion Law|publisher=Newson6.com|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.krmg.com/news/news/local/okla-ag-pruitt-reacts-abortion-ruling/nbhCx/ | title=Okla. AG Pruitt reacts to abortion ruling|publisher=Krmg.com|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2013, Pruitt maintained that the Supreme Court's decision to strike down a provision of [[DOMA]], a federal law that denied federal benefits to homosexual married couples did not affect Oklahoma's laws on the subject.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.krmg.com/news/news/local/attorney-general-says-supreme-court-gay-rights-rul/nYWrz/|title=Attorney General says Supreme Court ruling doesn't affect Okla. | publisher=Krmg.com |date=June 26, 2013| accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Washington D.C. watchdog organization [[Campaign for Accountability]] sued Pruitt's successor as Oklahoma Attorney General for the failure of the office to release documentation that had been withheld from the public concerning corruption allegations involving the management of the Tar Creek Reclamation Superfund lead-contaminated waste site near [[Miami, Oklahoma]]. In 2014, Pruitt asked Oklahoma's State Auditor and Inspector Gary Jones to audit the financial corruption by contractors performing the cleanup. Pruitt blocked Jones from following his intention to release the audit results.<ref>[https://www.eenews.net/greenwire/stories/1060067351/ Watchdogs sue for Okla. audit Pruitt withheld], ''[[Environment & Energy Publishing|E&E News]]'', Mike Soraghan, November 27, 2017. Retrieved November 28, 2017.</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2014, Pruitt joined a lawsuit targeting California's prohibition on the sale of eggs laid by caged hens kept in conditions more restrictive than those approved by California voters. Less than a week later, Pruitt announced that he would investigate the [[Humane Society of the United States]], one of the principal proponents of the California law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oklahomafarmreport.com/wire/news/2014/03/06793_PruittCaliforniaLawsuit03072014_052320.php|title=Oklahoma Farm Report \u2013 Oklahoma Attorney General Pruitt Joins Other States in Egg Lawsuit Against California|publisher=Oklahoma Farm Report |date=March 7, 2014|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/homepagelatest/state-ag-s-office-issues-alert-against-humane-society-of/article_8924aaa0-aa4f-11e3-90a2-001a4bcf6878.html|title=State AG's office issues alert against Humane Society of the United States|work=[[Tulsa World]]|accessdate=January 5, 2015 |first=Randy |last=Krehbiel |date=March 12, 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, a California judge dismissed the lawsuit, rejecting the arguments of Pruitt and the other attorneys-general concerning [[California's Proposition 2]], a 2008 ballot initiative. Judge [[Kimberly Mueller]] ruled that Oklahoma and the other states lacked legal standing to sue on behalf of their residents and that Pruitt and other plaintiffs were representing the interests of egg farmers, rather than \"a substantial statement of their populations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.sfgate.com/food/article/Judge-tosses-suit-by-6-states-over-California-law-5797844.php|title=Judge tosses suit by 6 states over California law on eggs|work=SFGate|accessdate=January 5, 2015 |first=Bob |last=Egelko |date= October 2, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.politico.com/tipsheets/morning-agriculture/2014/10/lawsuit-against-california-egg-law-dismissed-fda-report-stokes-debate-over-antibiotics-us-revokes-special-treatment-for-canadian-produce-212543 | title=Lawsuit against California egg law dismissed \u2013 FDA report stokes debate over antibiotics \u2013 U.S. revokes special treatment for Canadian produce | first1=Jason |last1=Huffman | work=[[Politico]]|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.sacbee.com/2014/10/02/6757006/judge-tosses-lawsuit-challenging.html | title=Judge tosses lawsuit challenging California egg laws|work=sacbee|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, an Oklahoma trial court found the state's execution drug supply law was unconstitutional, and after the [[Oklahoma Court of Criminal Appeals]] refused to order a stop to executions, the [[Oklahoma Supreme Court]] did.<ref name=theatlantic2015june>{{cite news|last1=Stern|first1=Jeffrey E.|title=The Cruel and Unusual Execution of Clayton Lockett|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2015/06/execution-clayton-lockett/392069/|accessdate=April 5, 2017|work=[[The Atlantic]]|issue=June 2015}}</ref>  Pruitt then filed a motion arguing that the Supreme Court was acting outside its authority, complaining it was causing a \"constitutional crisis\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eckholm|first1=Erik|title=Execution Case Roils Oklahoma Courts|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/23/us/legal-clashes-continue-in-oklahoma-lethal-injection-case.html|accessdate=April 5, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 23, 2014|page=A15}}</ref>  After the Supreme Court refused Pruitt's motion, Governor [[Mary Fallin]] faced conflicting court orders, so she issued a declaration rejecting the Supreme Court's authority and scheduling executions.<ref name=theatlantic2015june/>  After the state then botched the [[execution of Clayton Lockett]], and the U.S. Supreme Court subsequently approved of Oklahoma's method in ''[[Glossip v. Gross]]'', Pruitt asked to delay all scheduled executions in Oklahoma upon discovering executioners had accidentally used the wrong drug in a lethal injection.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Segura|first1=Liliana|last2=Smith|first2=Jordan|title=OKLAHOMA'S INSANE RUSH TO EXECUTE|url=https://theintercept.com/2016/05/24/oklahomas-insane-rush-to-execute/|accessdate=April 5, 2017|work=[[The Intercept]]|date=May 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPruitt expressed his dissatisfaction when a federal court ruled that Oklahoma's voter-approved amendment in 2004 to the [[Oklahoma State Constitution]] that defined marriage as only the union of one man and one woman was a violation of the [[U.S. Constitution]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/01/14/oklahoma-gay-marriage-ban/4480277/|title=Federal judge strikes down Okla. same-sex marriage ban | author=Michael Winter | date=January 14, 2014|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref> In October 2014, Pruitt criticized the Supreme Court's refusal to hear Oklahoma's appeal in the definition of marriage case.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ktul.com/story/26717916/attorney-general-scott-pruitt-statement-on-same-sex-marriage-decision | title=Attorney General Scott Pruitt Statement on Same-Sex Marriage Decision | publisher=Ktul.com | accessdate=January 5, 2015 |first=Nathan |last=Altadonna |date=October 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, after the Oklahoma Supreme Court blocked the enforcement of two abortion-related laws until after their constitutionality was litigated (which could take up to a year or more), Pruitt's office communicated the Attorney General's intention to support their implementation and enforcement.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://newsok.com/oklahoma-supreme-court-puts-on-hold-two-abortion-laws-pending-constitutional-challenges/article/5363467 | title=Oklahoma Supreme Court puts on hold two abortion laws pending constitutional challenges | work=The Oklahoman|accessdate=January 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.jurist.org/paperchase/2014/11/oklahoma-supreme-court-blocks-enforcement-of-abortion-laws.php | title=Oklahoma Supreme Court blocks enforcement of abortion laws | author=William Helbling | date=November 5, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn December 7, 2014, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published a front-page story highlighting that Pruitt had used his office's stationery to send form letters written by energy industry lobbyists to federal agencies during [[public comment]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=[[Eric Lipton]]|title=Energy Firms in Secretive Alliance With Attorneys General|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/07/us/politics/energy-firms-in-secretive-alliance-with-attorneys-general.html|accessdate=December 9, 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 7, 2014|page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Pruitt wrote a letter to school superintendents stating that schools can lawfully allow the dissemination of religious literature on campus.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eger|first1=Andrea|title=Oklahoma Attorney General Scott Pruitt defends Bible distribution in schools, says 'religious freedoms are under attack'| url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/education/oklahoma-attorney-general-scott-pruitt-defends-bible-distribution-in-schools/article_592d20aa-2c46-51f6-a3fb-f11480542217.html | accessdate=April 18, 2015|newspaper=[[Tulsa World]]|date=April 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the [[Oklahoma Supreme Court]] rejected Pruitt's defense of the new [[Ten Commandments Monument (Oklahoma City)|Ten Commandments Monument]] on the [[Oklahoma State Capitol]] grounds.<ref name=newyorker2april18/>\n\nIn the Op-Ed co-written with Luther Strange in May 2016, Pruitt contended, \"...our job is to hold the EPA accountable to the laws that created it and to fulfill our statutory duties ...\" \"We will continue to pursue those goals and to present our arguments in the courts and in the public square, treating our opponents with the respect they deserve. But we call upon them to press those beliefs through debate, not through governmental intimidation of those who disagree with them. Few things could be more un-American.\"<ref name=Strange />\n\nIn 2016, the U.S. Supreme Court refused to hear Pruitt's [[original jurisdiction of the Supreme Court of the United States|original lawsuit]] against the legalization of [[cannabis in Colorado]].<ref name=newyorker2april18/><ref>{{cite web|title=Nebraska and Oklahoma v. Colorado|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/nebraska-and-oklahoma-v-colorado/|website=[[SCOTUSblog]]|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the organization Oklahomans for Health collected the legally required number of signatures for a referendum ballot on the legalization of medical marijuana, in August 2016, Pruitt's office moved to rewrite the ballot title, but not in time for the November 2016 election. The measure appeared on the 2018 ballot; Question 788 passed with 57% voting \"yes.\"<ref>{{cite news| work=[[KFOR-TV|KFOR]].com | title=\"This is a huge hurdle\", state officials will decide whether 67,000 signatures on medical marijuana petition make ballot| url=http://kfor.com/2016/08/24/this-is-a-huge-hurdle-state-officials-will-decide-whether-67000-signatures-on-medical-marijuana-petition-make-ballot/}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Oklahoma Medical Marijuana Legalization Initiative, State Question 788 (2018) | work=[[Ballotpedia]]| url=https://ballotpedia.org/Oklahoma_Medical_Marijuana_Legalization_Initiative,_State_Question_788_(2018)|accessdate=December 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPruitt was an advisor to the [[Jeb Bush presidential campaign, 2016]]. In February 2016, he said that [[Donald Trump]] would be \"more abusive to the Constitution than Barack Obama\".<ref name=newyorker2april18/>\n\n[[File:Gina Loudon & Scott Pruitt (32775218220).jpg|thumb|Pruitt at the CPAC in February 2017]]\nIn February 2017, Pruitt was ordered by the Oklahoma District Court to release thousands of emails of communication with fossil fuel industries in order to comply with [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] requests filed over a two-year period by the liberal watchdog group [[Center for Media and Democracy]].<ref name=\"300K\"/>\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' reported in July 2017 that emails and other records released by the Oklahoma attorney general's office showed a close relationship between Pruitt and various [[Political activities of the Koch brothers|Koch brothers-backed]] advocacy groups, including the [[American Legislative Exchange Council]].<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/> The documents showed that while serving as Oklahoma attorney general, Pruitt \"acted in close concert with oil and gas companies to challenge environmental regulations, even putting his letterhead to a complaint filed by one firm, [[Devon Energy]].\"<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/>  Devon has since benefited from policies implemented by Pruitt.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/20/business/energy-environment/devon-energy.html|title=How Rollbacks at Scott Pruitt's E.P.A. Are a Boon to Oil and Gas|last1=Tabuchi|first1=Hiroko|date=May 21, 2017|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 28, 2018|last2=Lipton|first2=Eric|page=A1}}</ref>  Emails showed that [[American Fuel and Petrochemical Manufacturers]] \"provided Pruitt's office with template language to oppose ozone limits and the renewable fuel standard program in 2013.\"<ref name=\"theguardian.com\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/3472961-2013-Pruitt-and-American-Fuel-and-Petrochemical.html|title=Renewable Fuel Standard \u2013 Background Information|date=July 13, 2013|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency ==\n=== Nomination and confirmation ===\n[[File:Stop Pruitt, Rally To Oppose EPA Nominee Scott Pruitt (32119365773).jpg|thumb|Stop Pruitt sign, at a rally to oppose his nomination]]\nOn December 7, 2016, President-elect [[Donald Trump]] announced his intention to nominate Pruitt as the [[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency]].<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-epa-idUSKBN13W2HE|title=Trump to tap Oklahoma attorney general to lead EPA: transition team|date=December 7, 2016|work=Reuters}}</ref> President-elect Trump said that the EPA had an \"anti-energy agenda that has destroyed millions of jobs\" and that Pruitt, \"the highly respected Attorney General from the state of Oklahoma, will reverse this trend and restore the EPA's essential mission of keeping our air and our water clean and safe.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In response to the nomination, Pruitt said, \"I intend to run this agency in a way that fosters both responsible protection of the environment and freedom for American businesses.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2016/2016/12/07/donald-trump-scott-pruitt-environmental-protection-agency/95104512/ |title=Scott Pruitt, Trump's pick to head the EPA, has sued the EPA |last=Jackson |first=David}}</ref>\n\nPruitt was endorsed by the [[American Legislative Exchange Council]] (ALEC).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alec.org/article/attorney-general-scott-pruitt-selected-to-run-epa/|title=Attorney General Scott Pruitt Selected to Run EPA|last1=Eick|first1=John|website=American Legislative Exchange Council|accessdate=July 26, 2017}}</ref> Following Pruitt's nomination hearing, Republican Senator [[John Barrasso]] stated that \"Pruitt ... has demonstrated his qualifications to lead the EPA.\" West Virginia Attorney General [[Patrick Morrisey]], who worked with Pruitt on multiple cases, said of Pruitt that \"He cares passionately about the rule of law\" and that \"All the actions he's been involved in are rooted in the firm belief that what the [Obama] administration was doing was unlawful.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nMany science advocates and environmentalists voiced concerns about Pruitt's nomination. [[Gene Karpinski]], the president of the [[League of Conservation Voters]] said that Pruitt's past actions as Oklahoma AG made the nomination \"like the fox guarding the henhouse ... Time and again, he has fought to pad the profits of Big Polluters at the expense of public health.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-epa-idUSKBN13W2HE|title=Trump to pick foe of Obama climate agenda to run EPA -source|date=December 7, 2016|work=Reuters|author=Valerie Volcovici and David Shepardson}}</ref> Ken Kimmell, president of the [[Union of Concerned Scientists]], has said, \"Pruitt's record gives us no reason to believe that he will vigorously hold polluters accountable or enforce the law ... everything we do know makes it clear that he can't and won't do the job.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/02/02/us/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-senate.html?_r=0|title=Scott Pruitt, Trump's E.P.A. Pick, Is Approved by Senate Committee|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 5, 2017}}</ref> Saying that Pruitt had deliberately given misleading information about his position on the regulation of mercury emissions, a spokesperson from the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] said, \"It is a serious matter to give misleading testimony to Senators during a confirmation hearing.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article128535064.html#storylink=cpy|title=Trump's EPA pick gets a boost but is still opposed by Senate Democrats|work=mcclatchydc|access-date=February 28, 2017}}</ref> 447 former EPA employees penned a joint letter to oppose Pruitt's nomination, arguing that his lawsuits against the EPA \"strongly suggest that he does not share the vision or agree with the underlying principles of our environmental laws\" and that they believed that he had not \"put the public's welfare ahead of private interests\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/318081-former-epa-employees-urge-senate-to-oppose-pruitt|title=Former EPA employees urge Senate to oppose Pruitt|last1=Henry|first1=Devin|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|accessdate=February 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSenate Democrats unsuccessfully attempted to delay a vote until after the release of a batch of emails ordered by an Oklahoma judge.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{cite web|title=New EPA head Scott Pruitt's emails reveal close ties with fossil fuel interests|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/feb/22/scott-pruitt-emails-oklahoma-fossil-fuels-koch-brothers|website=The Guardian|accessdate=July 26, 2017}}</ref> On February 17, 2017, the Senate confirmed Pruitt, by a vote of 52\u201346, to be the [[Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency]].<ref>{{cite web | last1=Chakraborty | first1=Barnini | title=Pruitt Narrowly Confirmed to Head EPA Over Democratic Objections | url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/02/17/pruitt-narrowly-confirmed-to-head-epa-over-democratic-objections.html | date=February 17, 2017 | publisher=[[Fox News]] | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Scott Pruitt: Controversial Trump Environment Nominee Sworn In | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-39010374 | date=February 18, 2017 | work=BBC News | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> The vote was mostly along party lines, with Republican [[Susan Collins]] voting against, and Democrats [[Joe Manchin]] and [[Heidi Heitkamp]] voting in favor (Republican [[John McCain]] and Democrat [[Joe Donnelly]] did not vote).<ref>{{cite web | title=U.S. Senate: Roll Call Vote | url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=115&session=1&vote=00071 | date=February 17, 2017 | website=senate.gov | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Pruitt was sworn in the same day by Supreme Court Justice [[Samuel Alito]].<ref>{{cite news | last1=Boyer | first1=Dave | title=Scott Pruitt Sworn in as EPA Administrator | url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/feb/17/scott-pruitt-sworn-in-as-epa-administrator/ | date=February 17, 2017 | work=[[The Washington Times]] | accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure as EPA Administrator ===\nAt the end of 2017, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' summarized Pruitt's leadership of the EPA in 2017 as follows:\n\n<blockquote>In legal maneuvers and executive actions, in public speeches and closed-door meetings with industry groups, he has moved to shrink the agency's reach, alter its focus, and pause or reverse numerous environmental rules. The effect has been to steer the EPA in the direction sought by those being regulated. Along the way, Pruitt has begun to dismantle former president [[Barack Obama]]'s environmental legacy, halting the agency's efforts to combat climate change and to shift the nation away from its reliance on [[fossil fuel]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/under-scott-pruitt-a-year-of-tumult-and-transformation-at-epa/2017/12/26/f93d1262-e017-11e7-8679-a9728984779c_story.html|title=How Scott Pruitt turned the EPA into one of Trump's most powerful tools|last=Dennis|first=Brady|date=2017-12-31|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-01-02|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|issn=0190-8286}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nA 2018 study in the ''[[American Journal of Public Health]]'' found that in the first six months of Pruitt's tenure as EPA head that the agency had adopted a pro-business attitude unlike that of any previous administration. The study argued \"that the Pruitt-led EPA has moved away from the public interest and explicitly favored the interests of the regulated industries.\" The study found that the agency was vulnerable to [[regulatory capture]] and that the consequences for public and environmental health could be far-reaching.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dillon|first=Lindsey|last2=Sellers|first2=Christopher|last3=Underhill|first3=Vivian|last4=Shapiro|first4=Nicholas|last5=Ohayon|first5=Jennifer Liss|last6=Sullivan|first6=Marianne|last7=Brown|first7=Phil|last8=Harrison|first8=Jill|last9=Wylie|first9=Sara|date=April 2018|title=The Environmental Protection Agency in the Early Trump Administration: Prelude to Regulatory Capture|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=108|issue=S2|pages=S89\u2013S94|doi=10.2105/ajph.2018.304360|issn=0090-0036|pmc=5922212|pmid=29698086}}</ref> According to a 2018 [[Harvard University]] analysis, the Trump administration's rollbacks and proposed reversals of environmental rules under Pruitt would under the most conservative estimate likely \"cost the lives of over 80\u202f000 US residents per decade and lead to respiratory problems for many more than 1 million people.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cutler|first=David|last2=Dominici|first2=Francesca|date=June 12, 2018|title=A Breath of Bad Air: Cost of the Trump Environmental Agenda May Lead to 80\u202f000 Extra Deaths per Decade|journal=JAMA|volume=319|issue=22|pages=2261\u20132262|doi=10.1001/jama.2018.7351|pmid=29896617|issn=0098-7484}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, ''[[The Politico (newspaper)|Politico]]'' disputed the narrative that Pruitt had been effective in overturning Obama's environmental legacy.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2018/04/07/scott-pruitt-epa-accomplishments-rollback-217834|title=The Myth of Scott Pruitt's EPA Rollback|work=POLITICO Magazine|access-date=April 8, 2018}}</ref> According to ''Politico'', \"Pruitt has yet to create new regulations that would outlast his tenure or Trump's, or to rescind any of the regulations Obama created. He's only been able to delay a few that were already on hold before he took office because they were mired in litigation.\"<ref name=\":23\" /> ''The New York Times'' and ''The Washington Post'' noted that while Pruitt was prolific in undoing government regulations, legal experts said that Pruitt did so hastily and through poorly crafted legal arguments that lacked legal, scientific and technical data.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/07/climate/scott-pruitt-epa-rollbacks.html|title=In His Haste to Roll Back Rules, Scott Pruitt, E.P.A. Chief, Risks His Agenda|last=Davenport|first=Coral|date=April 7, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 7, 2018|last2=Friedman|first2=Lisa|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://js.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/epas-pruitt-praised-for-effectiveness-hits-bumps-in-his-rollback-campaign/2018/05/20/c6ca13d8-53b3-11e8-abd8-265bd07a9859_story.html|title=Amid ethics scrutiny, EPA's Pruitt also finds his regulatory rollbacks hitting bumps|work=Washington Post|access-date=May 21, 2018}}</ref> As a result, legal experts considered it likely that some of the rollbacks may be reversed in the courts.<ref name=\":22\" /> Legal experts described the legal arguments made by Pruitt's EPA as unprecedented and a departure from previous Republican and Democratic administrations.<ref name=\":22\" /> Rutgers University professor Stuart Shapiro said that while Pruitt had weakened enforcement of existing regulations, he had not been successful at repealing regulations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2018/04/28/epa-scandals-scott-pruitt-fails-undo-obama-environmental-regulations-column/555721002/|title=EPA scandals overshadow Scott Pruitt failure to undo Obama environmental regulations|work=USA TODAY|access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> By April 2018, six of Pruitt's rollbacks had been struck down by courts, and Pruitt had withdrawn two of his proposed rollbacks.<ref name=\":22\" /> Pruitt's legal document outlining the rationale to roll back a regulation on greenhouse emissions from vehicle tailpipes was 38 pages long, lacked the kind of data that courts expect in cases involving environmental regulations, and was mostly direct quotes from public comments made by automaker lobbyists.<ref name=\":22\" /> In contrast, the Obama administration's rationale for implementing the regulation in the first place was 1,217 pages long.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nOn March 9, 2017, in an interview on CNBC's [[Squawk Box]], Pruitt stated that he \"would not agree that\" carbon dioxide is \"a primary contributor to the global warming that we see\" backing up his claim by stating that \"measuring with precision human activity on the climate is something very challenging to do and there's tremendous disagreement about the degree of impact.\"<ref name=\"cnbc\">{{cite web|last1=DiChristopher|first1=Tom|title=EPA chief Scott Pruitt says carbon dioxide is not a primary contributor to global warming|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/03/09/epa-chief-scott-pruitt.html|website=CNBC|publisher=NBC Universal |date=March 9, 2017|accessdate=March 9, 2017|ref=Pruitt believes Carbon Dioxide is not a contributor to Global Warming}}</ref> This was in direct contradiction with EPA's public stance that was published on their official website which stated: \"Carbon dioxide is the primary [[greenhouse gas]] that is contributing to recent climate change\".<ref name=\"nyt3\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/09/us/politics/epa-scott-pruitt-global-warming.html | title=E.P.A. Chief Doubts Consensus View of Climate Change |author=Coral Davenport |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=April 30, 2017| work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> By April 28\u2014the day before the [[People's Climate March (2017)|climate change mass protests]]\u2014EPA announced that the website \"would be 'undergoing changes' to better represent the new direction the agency is taking\" which included \"the removal of several agency websites containing detailed climate data and scientific information\" including the site that \"had been cited to challenge Pruitt's Squawk Box statements.\"<ref name=\"wp_websiteremoved\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/04/28/epa-website-removes-climate-science-site-from-public-view-after-two-decades/\n|title=EPA website removes climate science site from public view after two decades\n|first1=Chris |last1=Mooney |first2=Juliet |last2=Eilperin |date=April 29, 2017 |accessdate=April 30, 2017 |work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> A March 9 analysis by fact-checking website ''[[Snopes.com]]'' found that \"Pruitt's statements to CNBC are misrepresentative of the scientific consensus on carbon dioxide's role as a greenhouse gas\u2014a consensus that has essentially existed for more than a century.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snopes.com/2017/03/09/pruitt-global-warming-scientific-consensus/ |title=Do Scott Pruitt's Statements on CO2 and Global Warming Misrepresent Scientific Consensus? |publisher=Snopes.com |date= |accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Atlantic]]'' published an article on the same day, pointing out that in 2007, the [[United States Supreme Court]] had acknowledged the link between carbon dioxide and global warming\u2014in 2013 the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] stated the probability of carbon dioxide causing global warming was at least 95%.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2017/03/trumps-epa-chief-rejects-that-carbon-dioxide-emissions-cause-climate-change/519054/ |title=Scott Pruitt Rejects the Scientific Fact of Climate Change |magazine=The Atlantic |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPruitt's chosen deputy, chief of staff, and deputy chief of staff are all former members of Senator [[Jim Inhofe]]'s (R-OK) staff.<ref name=NYT8march17>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=E.P.A. Head Stacks Agency With Climate Change Skeptics|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/07/us/politics/scott-pruitt-environmental-protection-agency.html|accessdate=May 9, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 8, 2017|page=A17}}</ref>  Pruitt picked Washington State senators [[Don Benton]] and [[Doug Ericksen]] to be, respectively, a White House liaison and a regional administrator.<ref name=NYT8march17/> [[Andrew R. Wheeler]] was nominated to be Pruitt's deputy administrator.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=Trump Nominates a Coal Lobbyist to Be No. 2 at E.P.A.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/05/climate/trump-epa-andrew-wheeler.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=October 5, 2017}}</ref>  Pruitt's principal deputy at the EPA's Office of Chemical Safety and Pollution Prevention was previously an executive at the [[American Chemistry Council]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipton|first1=Eric|title=Why Has the E.P.A. Shifted on Toxic Chemicals? An Industry Insider Helps Call the Shots|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/21/us/trump-epa-chemicals-regulations.html|work=The New York Times|date=October 22, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>  In December 2017, [[Michael Dourson]] withdrew his nomination to be Pruitt's assistant administrator.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kaplan|first1=Sheila|last2=Lipton|first2=Eric|title=Trump's E.P.A. Chemical Safety Nominee Withdraws|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/13/science/epa-chemical-safety-trump.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=December 14, 2017|page=A20}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2018 United States federal budget|President's first budget]] instructs Pruitt to cut the agency's budget by 24% and reduce its 15,000 employees by 20%.<ref name=NYT8march17/>  Pruitt has sought to end EPA funding for the [[United States Department of Justice Environment and Natural Resources Division]], which relies on $20 million a year from the EPA for 27% of its budget.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Savage|first1=Charlie|title=E.P.A. Threatens to Stop Funding Justice Dept. Environmental Work|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/27/us/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-justice-department-funding.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=September 28, 2017|page=A19}}</ref>  Pruitt has issued a directive to stop litigants from pressuring the EPA to regulate, referring to the practice as \"sue and settle\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=Administrator Pruitt Issues Directive to End EPA \"Sue & Settle\"|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/administrator-pruitt-issues-directive-end-epa-sue-settle|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=October 16, 2017}}</ref>  In response, 57 former EPA counsels signed a letter criticizing Pruitt's directive.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reilly|first1=Amanda|title=LAW: Former EPA lawyers assail Pruitt's 'sue and settle' directive|url=https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060066359|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=[[Environment & Energy Publishing]]|date=November 13, 2017}}</ref>  Pruitt has offered himself as a replacement of U.S. Attorney General [[Jeff Sessions]].<ref name=nyt18march18>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=Scott Pruitt, Trump's Rule-Cutting E.P.A. Chief, Plots His Political Future|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/17/climate/scott-pruitt-political-ambitions.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=March 18, 2018|page=A1}}</ref>\n\nOn April 28, 2017, Pruitt fired scientists from the agency's 18-member Board of Scientific Counselors (BOSC), indicating he intended to replace them with industry representatives.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=E.P.A. Widens An Open Door For Businesses \u2014 At Least Five Scientists Ousted From a Board|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/07/us/politics/epa-dismisses-members-of-major-scientific-review-board.html|accessdate=May 8, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 8, 2017|page=A1}}</ref> Ryan Jackson, Pruitt's chief of staff, asked the BOSC's chair to change testimony she had submitted before a May 23 hearing of the [[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|House Science Committee]], causing her to complain she felt \"bullied.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mervis|first1=Jeffrey|title=Scientist tells her story in latest partisan battle on House science panel|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/06/scientist-tells-her-story-latest-partisan-battle-house-science-panel|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|publisher=[[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]|date=June 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=E.P.A. Official Pressured Scientist on Congressional Testimony, Emails Show|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/26/us/politics/epa-official-pressured-scientist-on-congressional-testimony-emails-show.html|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 27, 2017|page=A15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=A hearing entitled Expanding the Role of States in EPA Rulemaking|url=https://science.house.gov/legislation/hearings/environment-subcommittee-hearing-expanding-role-states-epa-rulemaking|accessdate=July 5, 2017|publisher=U.S. House Committee on Science, Space, & Technology Subcommittee on Environment|date=May 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Pruitt removed several scientists from EPA advisory panels and forbade any scientist who receives a grant from the EPA from then serving those panels.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=Pruitt Bars Some Scientists From Advising E.P.A.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/31/climate/pruitt-epa-science-advisory-boards.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=November 1, 2017|page=A9}}</ref>  By December 2017, 700 staff had left EPA during Pruitt's tenure, including over 200 scientists.  During that time, Pruitt hired 129 people, including 7 scientists.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|last2=Affo|first2=Marina|last3=Kravitz|first3=Derek|title=E.P.A. Officials, Disheartened by Agency's Direction, Are Leaving in Droves|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/22/climate/epa-buyouts-pruitt.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=December 23, 2017|page=A16}}</ref>  In March 2018, Pruitt proposed to restrict the EPA from considering research that relies on confidential information, such as medical data.  The proposal was modeled on a stalled Congressional bill.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=The E.P.A. Says It Wants Research Transparency. Scientists See an Attack on Science.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/26/climate/epa-scientific-transparency-honest-act.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=March 26, 2018|page=A1}}</ref><ref>{{USBill|115|HR|1430|}} 115th Cong.(2017)</ref> It was expected that by August 2017, 47 of 58 serving scientists would have been removed from their positions, though they typically serve three year terms and which are renewed after they first expire.<ref>[https://thinkprogress.org/epa-dismisses-more-scientists-pruitt-trump-7530dc37dcf/ EPA accelerates purge of scientists Members of the EPA's Board of Scientific Counselors were told that they would not see their tenure renewed], ''[[Think Progress]]'', Natasha Geiling, June 21, 2017. Retrieved April 12, 2018.</ref>\n\nOn June 29, 2017, Pruitt attended a board meeting of the [[American Coalition for Clean Coal Electricity]], and told them that he will have researchers publicly debate the human role in [[climate change]], adopting [[Steven E. Koonin]]'s suggestion to hold a \"red team blue team\" exercise.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Plumer|first1=Brad|last2=Davenport|first2=Coral|title=E.P.A. to Give Dissenters a Voice on Climate, No Matter the Consensus|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/30/climate/scott-pruitt-climate-change-red-team.html|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 1, 2017|page=A12}}</ref>  In December 2017, White House Chief of Staff [[John F. Kelly]] rejected the debate idea.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|last2=Davis|first2=Julie Hirschfeld|title=The E.P.A. Chief Wanted a Climate Science Debate. Trump's Chief of Staff Stopped Him.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/09/climate/pruitt-red-team-climate-debate-kelly.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=March 11, 2018|page=A19}}</ref>  Pruitt has met with industry representatives almost daily while rarely meeting with environmentalists.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipton|first1=Eric|last2=Friedman|first2=Lisa|title=E.P.A. Chief's Calendar: A Stream of Industry Meetings and Trips Home|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/03/us/politics/epa-scott-pruitt-calendar-industries-coal-oil-environmentalists.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=October 3, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>\n\nPruitt and other agency heads delayed the public release of the Climate Change Report within the [[National Climate Assessment]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=Scientists Fear Trump Will Dismiss Blunt Climate Report|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/07/climate/climate-change-drastic-warming-trump.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=August 8, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>  The report was ultimately released in November 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|last2=Thrush|first2=Glenn|title=U.S. Report Says Humans Cause Climate Change, Contradicting Top Trump Officials|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/03/climate/us-climate-report.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=November 4, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, the [[Environmental Integrity Project]] determined that the administration was collecting 60% less money in civil environmental penalties than prior administrations.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=Civil Penalties Against Polluters Drop 60 Percent So Far Under Trump|url=http://www.environmentalintegrity.org/news/penalties-drop-under-trump/|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=[[Environmental Integrity Project]]|date=August 10, 2017}}</ref>  Pruitt has sought injunctive relief valued at 12% of that sought by the prior administration.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipton|first1=Eric|authorlink1=Eric Lipton|last2=Ivory|first2=Danielle|title=Under Trump, E.P.A. Has Slowed Actions Against Polluters, and Put Limits on Enforcement Officers|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/10/us/politics/pollution-epa-regulations.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=December 11, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>  As of January 2018, the administration had removed, relaxed, or delayed 67 environmental rules.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Popovich|first1=Nadja|title=67 Environmental Rules on the Way Out Under Trump|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/10/05/climate/trump-environment-rules-reversed.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=October 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, ''Time'' magazine reviewed the status of the EPA's website after a year of Pruitt's tenure. The magazine reported that the website's Climate Change section was taken down in April 2017 after existing in various forms for more than twenty years. The message, \"This page is being updated\", was left in its place. In addition, searching for \"climate change\" produced 5,000 results compared to the previous 12,000. Resources on how local communities could combat climate change were cut from 380 to 170 pages, and a 50-page resource on \"a Student's Guide to Global Climate Change\" was not archived. On some pages, edits have been made to remove terms like \"climate change\", \"air pollutant\", \"greenhouse gas\", while \"carbon footprint\" and \"carbon accounting\" were replaced with \"environmental footprint\" and \"sustainability accounting\".<ref name=TIMEwebsite>{{cite web|last1=Barron|first1=Laignee|title=Here's What the EPA's Website Looks Like After a Year of Climate Change Censorship|url=http://time.com/5075265/epa-website-climate-change-censorship/|website=Time|accessdate=March 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nCalling Pruitt on March 2, 2018, President Trump assured him, \"we've got your back,\" urging him to \"keep fighting,\" according to administration officials who remained anonymous. However, two additional officials confirmed that presidential Chief of Staff [[John F. Kelly]] had expressed the administration's displeasure over being caught unaware by some of the ethical problems Pruitt's conduct raised.<ref>[https://www.seattlepi.com/news/politics/article/Trump-offers-support-to-embattled-EPA-head-12801686.php EPA chief's job not assured after Trump's praise \u2014 and ire], ''Seattle [[Post-Intelligencer]]'', Zeke Miller & Michael Biesecker (AP), March 3, 2018. Retrieved March 4, 2018.</ref> Senate Environment Committee Chair [[John Barrasso]] of Wyoming, supported Pruitt, as did Senators [[Rand Paul]] and [[Ted Cruz]].<ref>[https://www.mysanantonio.com/news/politics/article/GOP-Senate-chairman-backs-Pruitt-as-ethics-probes-12818580.php Republicans stand by Pruitt as ethics probes expand], ''[[Associated Press]]'', Matthew Daly, April 9, 2018. Retrieved April 11, 2018.</ref>\n\nFormer coal lobbyist [[Andrew R. Wheeler|Andrew Wheeler]]'s nomination as Deputy Administrator was submitted to become Pruitt's deputy in 2017, but was not confirmed. It was resubmitted in 2018. He was confirmed as Deputy Administrator of the EPA on April 12, 2018, by a mostly party line vote of 53\u201345, which included three Democratic Senators, [[Joe Manchin]], [[Heidi Heitkamp]], and [[Joe Donnelly]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/the-senate-is-about-to-confirm-a-coal-lobbyist-as-top-epa-deputy/2018/04/12/b1bb6844-3dbe-11e8-a7d1-e4efec6389f0 Senate confirms a former coal lobbyist as Scott Pruitt's second-in-command at EPA], ''[[Washington Post]]'', Steven Mufson, Brady Dennis & Dino Grandoni, April 12, 2018. Retrieved April 13, 2018.</ref>\n\n=== Secrecy ===\nIn contrast to prior EPA administrators since its founding in 1973, Pruitt neither provided lists of scheduled public speaking events nor disclosed most trips until afterward. He avoided news conferences. On one occasion journalists who became aware of an event beforehand were ejected from a venue after an EPA official threatened to call law enforcement. Looking at a recent batch of documents released through a [[Sierra Club]] [[Freedom of information|FOI]] request, the ''New York Times'' commented that it appeared that the Pruitt schedulers divided people into \"friendly\" and \"unfriendly\" camps and noted one case where a meeting was kept so secret that even the meeting hosts were confused about it. Commenting on Pruitt's claim that his unusually extensive security expenses were related to his need for security, the ''New York Times'' said, \"[The documents] show that the agency's close control of Mr. Pruitt's events is driven more by a desire to avoid tough questions from the public than by concerns about security, contradicting Mr. Pruitt's longstanding defense of his secretiveness.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/07/climate/epa-pruitt-emails-secrecy.html|title='Smoke and Mirrors': Emails Detail Pruitt's Drive for Secrecy at the E.P.A.|last=Lipton|first=Eric|date=May 7, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 18, 2018|last2=Friedman|first2=Lisa|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=transparency /><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/11/climate/pruitt-cardinal-pell-dinner.html Pruitt's Dinner With Cardinal Accused of Abuse Was Kept Off Public Schedule], ''[[The New York Times]]'', Eric Lipton & Lisa Friedman, May 11, 2018. Retrieved May 18, 2018.</ref>\n\nA [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] request from the [[Sierra Club]] showed that between February and December 2017, Pruitt had only sent one e-mail to anyone outside EPA from his government e-mail account, leading to questions of whether Pruitt was using a private account to conduct government business.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/06/22/scott-pruitt-where-are-his-emails-664285|title=New Pruitt question: Where are his emails?|work=POLITICO|access-date=June 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn EPA official said that Pruitt and his top aides kept \"secret\" schedules and calendars to hide controversial meetings with industry representatives, destroying or altering records that might reflect poorly on Pruitt.<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/07/02/politics/scott-pruitt-whistleblower-secret-calendar/index.html|title=Whistleblower: EPA's Pruitt kept secret calendar to hide meetings|author1=Scott Bronstein |author2=Curt Devine |author3=Drew Griffin|work=CNN|access-date=July 3, 2018}}</ref> A review by ''CNN'' of internal EPA emails and the official EPA calendar found discrepancies in Pruitt's official EPA calendar with more than two dozen meetings and calls omitted.<ref name=\":33\" /> Legal experts said that the practices of keeping a secret calendar and destroying or altering records with the intent to deceive the public could be considered a violation of federal law.<ref name=\":33\" />\n\n=== Controversies ===\nDue to the multiple ongoing scandals involving Pruitt,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-04-25/here-s-a-scorecard-of-the-scott-pruitt-investigations-quicktake |title=A Guide to the Scott Pruitt Investigations |author=Jennifer A. Dlouhy |date=April 25, 2018 |website=Bloomberg.com |publisher= |access-date=July 6, 2018}}</ref> at least 20 members of Congress, including three Republicans ([[Carlos Curbelo]], [[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]] and [[Elise Stefanik]]), called for his resignation.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cassella|first1=Carly|title=Now, Even Some Republicans Want Scott Pruitt Booted From The EPA|url=https://www.sciencealert.com/scott-pruitt-environmental-protection-agency-democrats-republicans|website=Science Alert|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/381840-gop-lawmaker-calls-on-pruitt-to-resign|title=GOP lawmaker calls on Pruitt to resign|last1=Cama|first1=Timothy|website=The Hill|publisher=The Hill|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|author=Stephanie Ebbs|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/epa-chief-scott-pruitt-facing-calls-investigate-housing/story?id=54207260|title=EPA Chief Scott Pruitt facing more calls to investigate housing arrangement|date=April 3, 2018|publisher=ABC News|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref> Curbelo said that Pruitt's \"corruption scandals are an embarrassment to the Administration, and his conduct is grossly disrespectful to American taxpayers.\"<ref name=\":3\" />  On April 3, 2018, Senator Sheldon Whitehouse (D-RI) and Congressmen Ted Lieu (D-CA) and Don Beyer (D-VA) called for an investigation of Pruitt's housing arrangements by the EPA's inspector general.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite press release|date=April 3, 2018|title=REPS LIEU AND BEYER URGE IG INVESTIGATION INTO EPA ADMINISTRATOR SCOTT PRUITT|url=https://lieu.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/reps-lieu-and-beyer-urge-ig-investigation-epa-administrator-scott-pruitt|publisher=Office of U.S. Representative Ted Lieu}}</ref> House Oversight Committee Chairman Trey Gowdy, a Republican, started a probe into Pruitt in early April 2018 over his housing arrangements.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/382061-oversight-chairman-probes-pruitts-50-a-night-condo-deal#.WsgZt7Uvl8E.twitter|title=Oversight chairman probes Pruitt's $50-a-night condo deal|last=Cohn|first=Alicia|date=April 6, 2018|work=The Hill|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> President Donald Trump defended Pruitt, saying \"Rent was about market rate, travel expenses OK. Scott is doing a great job!\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/08/trump-defends-embattled-epa-chief-scott-pruitt.html|title=Trump says embattled EPA chief Pruitt's expenses are justified because he received 'death threats'|publisher=CNBC|date=April 8, 2018|access-date=April 8, 2018}}</ref> By early April 2018, ''Politico'' reported that the number of mushrooming scandals, leaks and staff disapproval of Pruitt's expenditures and ethical conflicts had created chaos at the EPA and put morale at an all-time low.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/06/epa-scott-pruitt-employees-467487|title=Inside the EPA: 'It's just a slow-motion train wreck'|work=Politico|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> Three Republican Senators joined the criticism, including Susan Collins, who had voted against his confirmation, as well as South Carolina's [[Lindsey Graham]] and Louisiana's [[John Neely Kennedy]]. Kennedy said, \"Now these are unforced errors. They are stupid. There are a lot of problems we can't solve. But you can behave.\"<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/three-republican-senators-voice-concern-about-epa-head-scott-pruitts-conduct/2018/04/08/22c85122-3b45-11e8-a7d1-e4efec6389f0_story.html Three Republican senators voice concern about EPA head Scott Pruitt's conduct], ''[[Washington Post]]'', Sean Sullivan, April 8, 2018. Retrieved April 9, 2018.</ref> South Dakota Senator [[Mike Rounds]] defended Pruitt on ''[[Meet the Press]]'', however, referring to the criticism by saying, \"I don't know how much of it is overblown and how much of it is accurate, to be honest.\"<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/gop-sen-rounds-pruitt-criticism-nitpicking-n863711 GOP Sen. Rounds: Pruitt criticism amounts to 'nitpick' of 'little things'], [[NBC News]], Kailani Koenig, April 8, 2018. Retrieved April 9, 2018.</ref> On June 5, 2018, Iowa Republican Senator [[Joni Ernst]] said Pruitt \"is about as swampy as you get here in Washington, D.C., and if the president wants to drain the swamp, he needs to take a look at his own cabinet.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-05/gop-senator-ernst-calls-epa-chief-pruitt-as-swampy-as-you-get|title=Republican Senator Calls Pruitt 'as Swampy as You Get'|date=June 5, 2018|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=June 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nTwo of Pruitt's top aides\u2014senior counsel Sarah Greenwalt, and director for scheduling and advance Millan Hupp\u2014were reported on June 6, 2018 to be resigning from the EPA. Both Greenwalt and Hupp were Pruitt associates from Oklahoma and had come under scrutiny regarding various controversies during his EPA tenure. When contacted for comment by a reporter from ''The Atlantic'', EPA spokesman Jahan Wilcox declined to comment apart from saying, \"You have a great day, you're a piece of trash.\" That same day, Trump stated, \"People are really impressed with the job that's being done at the EPA. Thank you very much, Scott.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/06/climate/pruitt-aides-resign-epa.html|title=Two Pruitt Aides Resign as E.P.A. Ethics Questions Continue|date=June 6, 2018|accessdate=June 7, 2018|work=New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/06/top-aide-to-epa-administrator-scott-pruitt-resigns/561974/|title=Pruitt Aide Resigns Amid Scandals|first=Elaina|last=Plott|date=June 6, 2018|work=The Atlantic|accessdate=June 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPruitt came under the scrutiny of the [[United States Office of Government Ethics]] regarding potential violations of [[Title 5 of the Code of Federal Regulations]] (CFR), which specifically incorporates, \"Employees shall not use public office for private gain,\" and  \"Employees shall endeavor to avoid any actions creating the appearance that they are violating the law or the ethical standards set forth in this part.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oge.gov/web/oge.nsf/All%20Documents/778D0B693D42FEE08525826A004F5471/$FILE/Letter%20to%20EPA%20DAEO.pdf?open |title=United States Office of Government Ethics (letter to Kevin Minoli, Principal Deputy General Counsel and Designated Agency Ethics Official) |author=[[David J. Apol]], Acting Director and General Counsel |date=April 6, 2018 |publisher=[[United States Office of Government Ethics]] |access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/commentary/ct-perspec-ethics-scott-pruitt-epa-0618-20180615-story.html |title=As ethics advisers, we thought we'd seen it all. Scott Pruitt shocks us. |authors=Virginia Canter and [[Norman L. Eisen]] |date=June 15, 2018 |website=[[Chicago Tribune]] |publisher= |access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.ecfr.gov/cgi-bin/text-idx?SID=48b2909b801315c551f1457d36c543ac&mc=true&node=pt5.3.2635&rgn=div5 Title 5: Administrative Personnel PART 2635\u2014STANDARDS OF ETHICAL CONDUCT FOR EMPLOYEES OF THE EXECUTIVE BRANCH], ''[[Electronic Code of Federal Regulations]]'', June 21, 2018. Retrieved June 24, 2018.</ref>\n\nEmails generated by EPA staffers, when Pruitt was the nominee for the EPA post, showed he considered running the agency at least part-time from Tulsa, his hometown, and sought office space in that city that would include room for his security detail. House Democratic committee members requested details from the EPA about his plans to open a Tulsa office, citing ethical concerns. \"Establishing a new EPA office in Tulsa may be personally convenient for you, but it seems ethically questionable, professionally unnecessary, and financially unjustified,\" they wrote in a May letter to Pruitt. EPA staff emails said Pruitt required a \"secure cabinet or safe\" as well as a secure room to receive classified information from President Donald Trump and his cabinet members. He also wanted the latitude to work from home at times. They ventured that the \"optics\" of receiving donated office space would be a public relations problem for Pruitt. An additional issue was the EPA didn't want the cost of such a space to appear as a line item in a congressional bill.<ref>[https://www.readfrontier.org/stories/emails-show-pruitt-mulled-running-the-epa-from-hometown-of-tulsa-though-plan-was-eventually-scrapped/ Emails show Pruitt mulled running the EPA from hometown of Tulsa, though plan was eventually scrapped], Brianna Bailey, June 23, 2018. Retrieved June 24, 2018.</ref>\n\n==== Management of agency ====\nEPA employees reported that the doors to the floor in the EPA's headquarters containing Pruitt's office were frequently locked, and employees were required to have escorts while visiting the floor. Some EPA employees also reported being told not to bring cellphones or take notes in meetings with Pruitt. Pruitt was also accompanied by armed guards even while at EPA's headquarters, an unprecedented level of security for an EPA administrator. Pruitt also ended the longstanding practice of making public the appointments of the administrator and other top agency officials.<ref name=\"Secret\">{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|last2=Lipton|first2=Eric|title=Scott Pruitt Is Carrying Out His E.P.A. Agenda in Secret, Critics Say|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/11/us/politics/scott-pruitt-epa.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=August 12, 2017|page=A1}}</ref> These measures prompted critics to charge that Pruitt was running the agency in secret.<ref name=\"Secret\"/>\n\nFive officials at the EPA \u2013 four of them high-ranking \u2013 were reassigned, demoted or pushed out of the EPA after they raised concerns about Pruitt's management of the agency, in particular Pruitt's expenditures.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/05/business/epa-officials-questioned-scott-pruitt.html|title=Job Changes for E.P.A. Officials Who Questioned Scott Pruitt|last=Lipton|first=Eric|date=April 5, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 5, 2018|last2=Vogel|first2=Kenneth P.|issn=0362-4331|last3=Friedman|first3=Lisa}}</ref> Several of these officials played a key role in reviewing Pruitt's travel plans; on occasions they put a halt to unjustifiably expensive travel plans.<ref name=\":19\" /> One political appointee was put on leave after voicing concerns about Pruitt to the White House's presidential personnel office.<ref name=\":19\" /> ''The New York Times'' reported that the appointee had objected to proposals considered by Pruitt's staff to buy a $100,000-a-month charter aircraft membership, spend $70,000 on two desks for Pruitt's office, and spend $43,000 on a sound-proof security booth.<ref name=\":19\" /> The appointee first asked Pruitt privately to rein in his spending, but then did it through intermediaries after he got frozen out.<ref name=\":19\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/18/climate/scott-pruitt-epa-investigations-guide.html|title=Expenses, Emails and a Phone Booth: The Investigations Faced by Scott Pruitt|date=April 18, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 20, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nEarly in his tenure, Pruitt asked his security detail to use flashing lights and sirens when they were stuck in D.C. traffic. Eric Weese, the lead agent of his security detail, told Pruitt that flashing lights and sirens were only used in emergency circumstances.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/scott-pruitt-asked-to-use-sirens-in-dc-traffic-and-was-told-no-for-non-emergency/|title=Scott Pruitt asked to use sirens in D.C. traffic and was told no for non-emergency|access-date=April 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":19\" /> One of the instances included a trip to Pruitt's favorite French restaurant in D.C.<ref name=\":19\" /> Less than two weeks later, the lead agent was reassigned.<ref name=\":20\" /><ref name=\":19\" /> Weese had also expressed a reluctance to sign off on requests that Pruitt needed to travel first class for security reasons.<ref name=\":19\" /> Agency staff questioned requests for a bulletproof sport utility vehicle, the construction of a special security booth in Pruitt's office, the tripling of the size of Pruitt's security detail, and the 24/7 work hours of his security detail.<ref name=\":19\" /> Reginald E. Allen, a career official at the EPA, was reassigned to an office within the EPA described as \"an unmarked grave\" after he objected to Pruitt's spending.<ref name=\":19\" /> Pruitt replaced Weese with Pasquale \"Nino\" Perrotta, a former Secret Service agent operating a private security company.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/e2fdc3fe88be432792817795a34fda46|title=AP sources: EPA chief spent millions on security and travel|work=AP News|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> Perrotta obtained a waiver to maintain outside employment while also heading Pruitt's security detail.<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/12/climate/epa-scott-pruitt-pasquale-perrotta.html|title=At E.P.A., Pruitt's 'Sheriff' Clashed With Critics of Spending|last=Vogel|first=Kenneth P.|date=April 12, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 13, 2018|last2=Lipton|first2=Eric|issn=0362-4331|last3=Friedman|first3=Lisa}}</ref> Under Perrotta, there was a rapid expansion of Pruitt's security detail, as he signed off on various requests by Pruitt's team.<ref name=\":21\" /> Perrotta also wrote an email to five EPA officials which indicated that it was Pruitt's preference to use lights and sirens on his vehicle.<ref name=Senate />\n\nDuring a trip to Italy, the EPA hired Italians to further support Pruitt's security detail who were reportedly friends of Perrotta.<ref name=\":21\" /> Perrotta travelled first class with Pruitt and shared, along with his men, a five-course meal with Pruitt at a restaurant in Rome (it is rare for security personnel to dine with those they are protecting).<ref name=\":24\" /> Perrotta also hired the vice president of his private security company to conduct bug sweeps in Pruitt's office (typically conducted by government personnel) and install biometric locks on doors at a cost of approximately $9,000.<ref name=\":24\" /><ref name=\":21\" />  After Kevin Chmielewski, a former campaign staffer for Donald Trump, refused to retroactively approve return first class travel from Morocco for Pruitt's aide, Samantha Dravis, Perrotta ordered him to relinquish his staff credentials, and Chmielewski was terminated from his position. Chmielewski had also raised concerns regarding other expenditures and the ethics of Pruitt's condo lease.<ref>[https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/12/former-epa-staffer-pruitt-first-class-478291 Former EPA staffer: Refusal to OK first-class flight for Pruitt aide prompted firing], ''[[Politico]]'', Alex Guillen, April 12, 2018. Retrieved April 12, 2018.</ref> Besides Weese, Reginald E. Allen was moved to a job where he had less say in spending decisions and less interaction with Pruitt. A third career official, John E. Reeder, was told to find a new job and John C. Martin, who also served on the security detail, was removed from the team and had his gun and badge taken away after questioning how Pruitt's security was being handled. A sixth official, Mr. Pruitt's chief of staff, Ryan Jackson, also raised questions about Mr. Pruitt's spending, according to unnamed EPA officials, remaining in his position, but who considered resignation.<ref name=\":24\" />\n\nIn June 2018, it was reported that Pruitt had used agency staff to perform nonofficial duties for Pruitt.<ref name=\":29\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/06/07/pruitt-enlisted-security-detail-in-picking-up-dry-cleaning-moisturizing-lotion/|title=Pruitt enlisted security detail in picking up dry cleaning, moisturizing lotion|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=June 7, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=June 7, 2018|last2=Dawsey|first2=Josh|issn=0190-8286|last3=Dennis|first3=Brady}}</ref> He tasked members of his security detail to run errands like picking up his dry cleaning and driving him around to search for a favorite moisturizer.<ref name=\":29\" /> Pruitt also tasked staffers to look for apartments and to purchase a used mattress for his personal use.<ref name=\":29\" />\n\n===== Freedom of Information Act requests =====\nAs EPA administrator, Pruitt maintained four different email addresses. This prompted two Democrats on the [[Senate Committee on Environment and Public Works]] to request that the EPA inspector general look into \"whether the agency has properly searched these email addresses for responsive documents in response to [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] (FOIA) requests.\"<ref>Juliet Eilperin & Brady Dennis, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/04/12/scott-pruitt-has-four-different-epa-email-addresses-lawmakers-want-to-know-why/ Scott Pruitt has 4 different EPA email addresses. Lawmakers want to know why.], ''Washington Post'' (April 12, 2018).</ref>\n\nUnder Pruitt, EPA Chief of Staff Ryan Jackson created a pilot program to \"centralize\" FOIA requests that go through the various sub-offices that make up EPA's Office of the Administrator, as revealed by released emails. In internal emails from August 2017 (later turned over to the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]]), Jackson and another top Pruitt aide (Liz Bowman, the head of EPA's Office of Public Affairs) complained that career EPA officials had released records in response to a FOIA request from a news organization ([[E&E News]]), when such records could have been withheld for several additional weeks. The aides directed that they be notified prior to any release of Pruitt-related material. This approach was criticized by FOIA experts; Nate Jones, director of the FOIA Project at [[George Washington University]]'s [[National Security Archive]] said the process \"does look like the most burdensome review process that I've seen documented.\"<ref>[https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/06/pruitt-epa-document-requests-570289 EPA clamps down on document requests linked to Pruitt], ''[[Politico]]'', Alex Guillen, May 5, 2018. Retrieved May 7, 2018.</ref>\n\nPruitt hired the former treasurer of his political action committee, Elizabeth Beacham White to run the EPA office that handles Freedom of Information Act requests for Pruitt's office.<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/07/03/pruitt-pac-treasurer-public-records-releases-667031|title=Pruitt ally decides which of his records see the light of day|work=Politico|access-date=July 3, 2018}}</ref> The office run by White has been slow to meet FOIA requests, far exceeding legal deadlines and causing a massive surge in court challenges. Pruitt's office had the slowest response rate to FOIA requests of any section of the EPA.<ref name=\":34\" />\n\n==== Expenditures ====\nPruitt drew controversy in the late summer and fall of 2017 over his use of taxpayer funds.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/09/27/epas-pruitt-took-charter-military-flights-that-cost-taxpayers-more-than-58000/|title=EPA's Pruitt took charter, military flights that cost taxpayers more than $58,000|last=Dennis|first=Brady|date=September 27, 2017|work=Washington Post|access-date=September 28, 2017|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Unlike his predecessors, Pruitt has, as EPA head, regularly flown first or business class on commercial airlines, as well as chartered private jets and military planes at exorbitant costs.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/first-class-travel-distinguishes-scott-pruitts-epa-tenure/2018/02/11/5bb89afc-0b7d-11e8-8b0d-891602206fb7_story.html|title=First-class travel distinguishes Scott Pruitt's EPA tenure|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=February 11, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=February 12, 2018|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/epas-scott-pruitt-got-waiver-to-fly-business-class-on-non-u-s-carrier-from-italy-to-u-s/|title=EPA's Scott Pruitt got waiver to fly business class on foreign carrier from Italy to U.S.|access-date=February 14, 2018}}</ref> The cost of Pruitt's seats on those flights are often several times higher than the seats for his accompanying staffers.<ref name=\":12\" /> Pruitt also has a vastly larger around-the-clock security detail than his predecessors.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/at-epa-guarding-the-chief-pulls-agents-from-pursuing-environmental-crimes/2017/09/19/7b7b8b6c-9ce0-11e7-8ea1-ed975285475e_story.html|title=At EPA, guarding the chief pulls agents from pursuing environmental crimes|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=September 20, 2017|work=Washington Post|access-date=September 28, 2017|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref name=\"threats\">{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2017/10/23/politics/epa-pruitt-security-costs/index.html|title=Security costs skyrocket at EPA|authors=Rene Marsh and Gregory Wallace|publisher=CNN|date=October 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, the inspector general of the EPA launched a probe into Pruitt's travel to and from Oklahoma at taxpayer expense.<ref name=\":7\" /> In September 2017, it was revealed that Pruitt had used at least $58,000 worth of noncommercial charter flights and military flights during his tenure, and when traveling on commercial airlines had opted for business or first class when those seats were available.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-epa-pruitt/epas-pruitt-took-flights-costing-taxpayers-more-than-58000-washington-post-idUSKCN1C30E7|title=EPA's Pruitt took flights costing taxpayers more than $58,000: Washington Post|date=2017|agency=Reuters|access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref> In February 2018, a ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' investigation determined that Pruitt has thus far spent hundreds of thousands of dollars on first-class airline travel, charter flights, military aircraft and luxury hotel stays, potentially contravening federal travel regulations and contrary to the practices of his predecessors, who routinely traveled in economy class. On June 5, 2017, for example, Pruitt billed the government for a $1,641.43 first-class ticket on a flight from Washington, D.C. to New York.<ref name=\"WaPoTravel\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/first-class-travel-distinguishes-scott-pruitts-epa-tenure/2018/02/11/5bb89afc-0b7d-11e8-8b0d-891602206fb7_story.html First-class travel distinguishes Scott Pruitt's EPA tenure]. ''[[The Washington Post]]'', February 11, 2018</ref>\n\nPruitt defended his unprecedented travel costs as necessary for security reasons. His spokesman told ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' that Pruitt has a \"blanket waiver\" to travel regulations which normally prohibit first-class travel by federal employees.<ref name=\"HillTravel\">[http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/373747-pruitt-has-blanket-waiver-to-first-class-travel-rules Pruitt has 'blanket waiver' to first-class travel rules]. ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', February 13, 2018</ref> Pruitt's staff later elaborated that the security reasons included other passengers being uncivil, quoting one individual yelling a vulgarism at him, referring what he was doing to the environment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/02/15/scott-pruitt-first-class-travel-epa-351669|title=Pruitt's security threat? A passenger shouting, 'You're f\u2014ing up the environment'|work=POLITICO|access-date=February 16, 2018}}</ref> Despite the purported security threats to Pruitt, he opted to travel in coach on flights home to Oklahoma when taxpayers were not paying for his travel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/382060-pruitt-flew-coach-when-taxpayers-were-not-paying-for-his-travel|title=Pruitt flew coach when taxpayers were not paying for his travel: report|last=Anapol|first=Avery|date=April 6, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref> Furthermore, according to a former top aide, Pruitt refused to stay at hotels which had been vetted by the U.S. Embassy while traveling abroad, opting instead for more expensive and less secure hotels.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/12/climate/pruitt-epa-ethics-letter-congress.html|title=Lawmakers' Letter Claims Further Spending Abuses by the E.P.A. Head, Scott Pruitt|last=Lipton|first=Eric|date=April 12, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 12, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nPruitt frequently opted to fly with Delta Airlines, despite US government contracts giving discounts on certain routes.<ref name=\":11\" /> According to one of Pruitt's former top aides, Pruitt wanted to fly Delta so that he could collect more frequent flyer miles.<ref name=\":2\" /> During one trip, Pruitt used [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]], a Dubai-based airline, requiring a waiver from the [[Fly America Act]], which normally requires federal employees to travel on American-owned airlines.<ref name=\":12\" /> Pruitt also tended to stay at high-end hotels during his trips.<ref name=\":11\" /> Pruitt was found to have spent 43 of the 92 days from March to May 2017 in Oklahoma or traveling there.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=Scott Pruitt Spent Much of Early Months at E.P.A. Traveling Home, Report Says|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/24/climate/scott-pruitt-epa-travel-expenses.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=July 24, 2017|page=A12}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the EPA spent what was thought to be $25,000 to build a [[Soundproofing|soundproof]] booth for Pruitt to use in his office. The EPA's spokesperson said that this was to protect against hacking and eavesdropping.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/26/climate/pruitt-epa.html|title=E.P.A. to Spend Nearly $25,000 on a Soundproof Booth for Pruitt|last=Friedman|first=Lisa|date=September 26, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 28, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In March 2018, it was revealed that the cost of the booth was even higher than initially reported; actually almost $43,000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/03/14/scott-pruitts-25000-soundproof-phone-booth-it-actually-cost-more-like-43000/|title=Scott Pruitt's $25,000 soundproof phone booth? It actually cost more like $43,000.|last=Dennis|first=Brady|date=March 14, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=March 14, 2018|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> [[Christine Todd Whitman]], EPA Administrator under [[George W. Bush]], noted that there was already a secure phone booth in the building.<ref>[[Margaret Talbot]], [https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2018/04/02/scott-pruitts-dirty-politics Scott Pruitt's Dirty Politics], ''The [[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]'' (April 2, 2018). Retrieved April 9, 2018.</ref> In April 2018, the [[Government Accountability Office]] concluded that Pruitt's purchase of the $43,000 soundproof booth violated federal spending laws.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/04/16/scott-pruitts-43000-soundproof-phone-booth-violated-spending-laws-federal-watchdog-finds/|title=Scott Pruitt's $43,000 soundproof phone booth violated spending laws, federal watchdog finds|last=Dennis|first=Brady|date=April 16, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 16, 2018|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nThe EPA also swept for bugs in Pruitt's office and installed biometric locks on his office doors, at a cost of approximately $9,000.<ref name=\":21\" /> In September 2017, it was reported that Pruitt's security detail had increased to 18 people who guarded him around the clock, which was without precedent in size for an EPA chief. Additional agents for Pruitt's security detail were reassigned from the EPA's Criminal Investigation Division, which more typically investigates environmental crimes.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/09/21/politics/epa-pruitt-agents/index.html|title=EPA pulls agents from investigations to guard Pruitt|author=Rene Marsh and Gregory Wallace|access-date=September 28, 2017|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref name=\":13\" /> The EPA justified the size of the detail, saying that it was because Pruitt faced greater security threats.<ref name=\"threats\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> However, an internal EPA report showed that EPA intelligence officials concluded there was no justification for the expansion of Pruitt's security detail and that there were no specific credible security threats against Pruitt; the career EPA official who approved the report was later dismissed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/04/10/internal-epa-documents-question-justification-for-pruitts-round-the-clock-security-detail/|title=Internal EPA documents question justification for Pruitt's round-the-clock security detail|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=April 10, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 10, 2018|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/10/documents-contradict-epa-claims-threats-984459|title=Exclusive: EPA removes staffer who OK'd report on Pruitt's security|work=Politico|access-date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> The Associated Press failed to find any case where someone had been charged or arrested for threatening Pruitt.<ref name=\":21\" /> In October 2017, CNN reported that Pruitt had requested a dozen more agents, which would cost the taxpayers at least $2 million per year in salaries alone.<ref name=\"threats\" /> By June 2018, the costs of Pruitt security was more than $4.6 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2018/06/20/scott-pruitt-epa-security-total-expenses-foia/|title=Scott Pruitt Has Spent a Total of $4.6 Million on Security, New Disclosures Show \u2014 Including $1,500 on \"Tactical Pants\"|last=Fang|first=Lee|last2=Surgey|first2=Nick|date=June 20, 2018|website=The Intercept|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, it was reported that Pruitt's aides had researched leasing a private jet on a monthly basis for Pruitt's travel. The estimated cost of this would have been approximately $100,000 per month.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/epa-explored-private-jet-lease-for-pruitts-travels-last-year/2018/04/02/8651deb8-3607-11e8-8fd2-49fe3c675a89_story.html|title=EPA explored private jet lease for Pruitt's travels last year|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=April 2, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 3, 2018|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> The aides evaluated such expenditures prior to the outbreak of a similar scandal regarding exorbitant travel costs by Health and Human Services Secretary [[Tom Price (American politician)|Tom Price]], which later led to Price's resignation.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\nIn April 2018, it was also reported that Pruitt had two of his aides and three security agents sent on a trip to Australia in August 2017 to set up future meetings for him; the five staff members flew business class, costing taxpayers a combined $45,000 for airfare alone.<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-pruitt-exclusive/exclusive-epa-chiefs-aides-security-agents-made-45000-trip-to-australia-idUSKBN1HQ2U7|title=Exclusive: EPA chief's aides, security agents made $45,000 trip to ...|last=Mason|first=Jeff|publisher=Reuters|access-date=April 19, 2018}}</ref> Each ticket cost $9,000 (an economy class ticket would have cost approximately $1,400).<ref name=\":25\" /> Pruitt's trip to Australia was canceled due to Hurricane Harvey.<ref name=\":25\" />\n\nResponding to allegations of ethics violations, in April 2018, thirty-nine members of the Senate and more than 130 members of the House of Representatives\ncalled for Pruitt's resignation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Record number of lawmakers sign resolution demanding Pruitt's resignation |url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/768375/record-number-lawmakers-sign-resolution-demanding-pruitts-resignation |website=The Week |accessdate=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, it was reported that Pruitt had spent approximately $1,500 on 12 customized fountain pens from a Washington jewelry store.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/06/01/epas-pruitt-spent-1560-on-12-customized-fountain-pens-from-washington-jewelry-store/|title=EPA's Pruitt spent $1,560 on 12 customized fountain pens from Washington jewelry store|last=Dennis|first=Brady|date=June 1, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=June 1, 2018|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n==== 2017 Morocco trip to encourage U.S. LNG sales ====\nIn 2018, Pruitt faced increased scrutiny concerning a December 2017 trip to Morocco. The trip was disclosed via a press release after Pruitt had returned.<ref name=\"EPAPress\">{{cite press release|title=Administrator Pruitt Promotes Environmental Cooperation with U.S. Partners in Morocco|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/administrator-pruitt-promotes-environmental-cooperation-us-partners-morocco|agency=U.S. Environmental Protection Agency|date=December 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"EilperinFourDays\">Juliet Eilperin, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/12/13/scott-pruitt-and-a-crew-of-epa-aides-just-spent-four-days-in-morocco-promoting-natural-gas/ Scott Pruitt and a crew of EPA aides just spent four days in Morocco promoting natural gas], ''Washington Post'' (December 13, 2017).</ref> During the trip, Pruitt met with Moroccan officials to discuss the [[United States-Morocco Free Trade Agreement|bilateral Morocco-U.S. agreement]] and promoted the export of [[liquified natural gas]] (LNG) to Morocco.<ref name=\"EPAPress\"/><ref name=\"EilperinFourDays\" /> Pruitt and his entourage spent four days in Morocco and some additional time in Paris, which an EPA spokesman said was due to weather delays.<ref name=\"DennisEilperinMar20\">{{cite news|last1=Dennis|first1=Brady|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|title=New documents show nearly $68,000 in recent premium flights, hotel stays for EPA's Pruitt|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/03/20/new-documents-show-nearly-68000-in-recent-premium-flights-hotel-stays-for-epas-pruitt/|accessdate=April 6, 2018|newspaper=Washington Post|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref> Pruitt's travel expenses for the trip cost $17,631; the costs for Pruitt's 10-person entourage were not disclosed.<ref name=\"DennisEilperinMar20\" />\n\nIn May 2018, it was revealed that Richard Smotkin, a former Comcast lobbyist and long-time friend of Pruitt's, arranged the trip to Morocco.<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/lobbyist-helped-broker-pruitts-100000-trip-to-morocco/2018/05/01/b2e20ee0-4d76-11e8-b725-92c89fe3ca4c_story.html |title=Lobbyist helped arrange Scott Pruitt's $100,000 trip to Morocco|last=Sullivan|first=Kevin|date=May 1, 2018|work=Washington Post|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|last3=Dennis|first3=Brady}}</ref> In April 2018, Smotkin received a $40,000-a-month contract (retroactive to January 2018) with the Moroccan government to lobby on behalf of the country.<ref name=\":26\" /> Ethics experts said that it was highly unusual for individuals outside of government to arrange trips such as these and that the trip raised questions as to whether it was intended to financially benefit Smotkin.<ref name=\":26\" />\n\nPruitt's Morocco trip was controversial, prompting criticism from Democrats and from the [[Sierra Club]], and prompting an expanded inquiry from the EPA inspector general. In a letter to Pruitt asking him to explain the trip, Senator [[Sheldon Whitehouse]] (D-RI) noted that the five-day trip consisted of one full workday, two days with a one-hour meeting for each, and a two-day, non-work layover in Paris over a weekend.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=A Trip to Morocco. A Condo Rental. Here's Why Scott Pruitt Is Under Fire.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/04/climate/scott-pruitt-condo-travel.html|accessdate=April 6, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 4, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Mosk\">{{cite news|last1=Mosk|first1=Matthew|last2=Ebbs|first2=Stephanie|last3=Turner|first3=Trish|title=More scrutiny for Pruitt's Morocco trip from Democrats, EPA inspector general|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/scrutiny-pruitts-morocco-trip-democrats-epa-inspector-general/story?id=54240618|accessdate=April 6, 2018|publisher=ABC News|date=April 4, 2018}}</ref> Critics also said that Pruitt's trip was improper because the export of liquified natural gas (LNG), a [[fossil fuel]], falls outside the EPA's mission of ensuring clean air and water, and because the Energy Department and [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]], not the EPA, oversee the export of LNG.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Biesecker|first1=Michael|title=EPA chief jets to Morocco to help promote fossil fuel use|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sns-bc-us--epa-pruitt-travel-morocco-20171213-story.html|agency=Associated Press|date=December 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Eilperin|first1=Juliet|title=Scott Pruitt and a crew of EPA aides just spent four days in Morocco promoting natural gas|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/12/13/scott-pruitt-and-a-crew-of-epa-aides-just-spent-four-days-in-morocco-promoting-natural-gas/|accessdate=April 6, 2018|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=December 13, 2017}}</ref> At the time of the trip, Pruitt's landlord's lobbying firm represented the only U.S. domestic exporter of LNG.<ref name =Cheniere /><ref name=Cheniere2 />\n\nIn December 2017, Senator [[Tom Carper]] (D-DE) wrote a letter to the EPA Inspector General, requesting that the IG expand the scope of the pending audit concerning Pruitt's travel to include the Morocco trip.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Carper|first1=Thomas|title=12/18/17 Letter to EPA Inspector General from Senator Thomas Carper|url=https://www.epw.senate.gov/public/_cache/files/a/7/a7271e2f-169d-4421-8aa1-bd2aee769bb0/357ADF0B861CF8EE2E008EE37D270633.carper-asks-inspector-general-to-expand-investigation-into-epa-administrators-travel.pdf|publisher=U.S. Senate|accessdate=April 6, 2018}}</ref> In response to Carper's letter, \"the IG said he would expand the scope of the investigation of Pruitt's travel costs through the end of 2017 and would look at whether EPA followed all policies and procedures.\"<ref name=\"Mosk\"/>\n\nIn April 2018, Pruitt released his travel itinerary for the Morocco trip in response to Freedom of Information requests, but the bulk of the itinerary had been redacted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/scott-pruitts-moroccan-calendar-draws-blanks/story?id=54556574|title=Scott Pruitt's Moroccan calendar draws blanks|date=April 19, 2018|publisher=ABC News|access-date=April 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Housing arrangements ====\nIn March 2018, it was reported that Pruitt had leased a condominium [[townhouse]] in Washington D.C. from a lobbyist couple, Vicki and Steven Hart, at a price of $50 per night, which amounted to $6,100 over a six-month period.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-30/epa-chief-s-50-a-night-rental-said-to-raise-white-house-angst|title=EPA Chief's $50-a-Night Rental Raises White House Angst|date=March 30, 2018|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Daily Beast\">{{cite web|title=EPA Administrator Scott Pruitt's Lobbyist-Owned Pad Was GOP Fundraising Hub|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/epa-administrator-scott-pruitts-lobbyist-owned-pad-was-gop-fundraising-hub|website=Daily Beast|publisher=Daily Beast|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref> The average price for [[Airbnb]] lodging in the same neighborhood is $142 per night.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/03/30/as-new-details-emerge-scott-pruitts-housing-arrangements-come-under-scrutiny/|title=As new details emerge, Scott Pruitt's housing arrangements come under scrutiny|last=Dennis|first=Brady|date=March 30, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=March 31, 2018|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Pruitt's adult daughter also stayed for months in the condo's second bedroom while a White House intern, but was not charged for her stay.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/exclusive-epa-chief-pruitt-joined-family-condo-tied/story EXCLUSIVE: EPA chief Pruitt joined by family in condo tied to lobbyist 'power couple'], [[ABC News]], John Santucci, Matthew Mosk & Stephanie Ebbs, March 30, 2018. Retrieved March 31, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe Harts' firm was registered to lobby on behalf of at least a half a dozen clients in industries regulated by the EPA,<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/02/climate/epa-pruitt-pipeline-apartment.html|title=Pruitt Had a $50-a-Day Condo Linked to Lobbyists. Their Client's Project Got Approved.|last=Lipton|first=Eric|date=April 2, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 3, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/20/pruitt-condo-lobbyist-leaving-firm-543508|title=Lobbyist whose wife rented to Pruitt lobbied EPA despite denials|work=POLITICO|access-date=April 21, 2018}}</ref> including Canadian energy company Enbridge.<ref name=\"Cheniere\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/30/climate/scott-pruitt-epa-rental.html Scott Pruitt, E.P.A. Chief, Rented Residence From Wife of Energy Lobbyist], ''[[New York Times]]'', Brad Plumer & Eric Lipton, March 30, 2018. Retrieved April 11, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"Cheniere2\">{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/exclusive-pruitts-epa-security-broke-door-lobbyist-condo/story?id=54129080|title=Pruitt's EPA security broke down door to lobbyist condo|date=March 30, 2018|publisher=ABC News|access-date=March 30, 2018}}</ref> At the same time that Pruitt was renting the condo, the EPA approved Enbridge's plan to expand a pipeline carrying oil to the United States from Canadian tar sands.<ref name=\":15\" /> Enbridge had in 2010 been given the second-largest fine in EPA history for spilling crude oil into the [[Kalamazoo River]] in Michigan.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nA Pruitt spokesperson denied any link between the condo rental and the agency approvals, but government ethics experts said that the situation raised an [[Appearance of impropriety|appearance]] of a conflict of interests that made it reasonable to question the EPA's decision.<ref name=\":15\" /> In May 2018, emails showed that Hart had asked Pruitt to get three people appointed to the EPA's Science Advisory Board.<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/01/climate/epa-kelly-perrotta-resignations.html|title=Two Top Aides to Scott Pruitt Quit the E.P.A. Unexpectedly|date=May 1, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 2, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The three people were recommended by a company that Hart lobbied on behalf of.<ref name=\":27\" />\n\nIn March 2018, EPA's Designated Agency Ethics Official and principal deputy general counsel, Kevin Minoli, wrote that Pruitt's lease, which as drafted provided Pruitt with access to a single unlocked bedroom at a rate of $50 per night for the nights used up to a maximum of 37 nights, was not a violation of federal gift rules because of the limited use provided by the lease and the availability of other temporary housing in the area for a similar price.<ref>https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/4429953-MInoli-Memo.html</ref> However, Minoli emphasized he had only evaluated the narrow terms of the lease itself, not any other activities or benefits provided outside of the lease that the document did not address. Minoli issued a second memorandum on April 4, 2018, providing additional explanation of his determination and the factual information he considered.<ref>https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/4431672-Record-Re-Review-of-Lease2018-04-04-163433.html</ref> As to allegations that Pruitt's daughter stayed in a separate bedroom, Minoli's memorandum did not opine on the implication of those or other allegations explaining that to evaluate them \"would have required factual information that was not before\" the ethics office.<ref>https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/4431672-Record-Re-Review-of-Lease2018-04-04-163433.html at page 3.</ref> Minoli's memorandum also explained that it was limited only to the question of whether the rental agreement constituted a gift and \"did not address other portions of the Federal ethics regulations such as the impartiality rule.<ref>Id.</ref> Other apartments in the building complex, located in a prime location less than a block away from the U.S. Capitol, rented for as much as $5,000 per month.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/04/05/top-epa-ethics-official-says-he-lacked-key-facts-about-pruitts-condo-rental/|title=Top EPA ethics official says he lacked key facts about Pruitt's condo rental|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=April 5, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 5, 2018|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Furthermore, when the EPA ethics official reviewed the undated lease document, the name of the husband who had EPA interests had been struck through by Vicki Hart and her own name had instead been handwritten in.<ref name=\":18\" /> The owners were issued a notice of infraction by the District of Columbia because they lacked a license to rent out rooms.<ref>[http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/dc-officials-cite-pruitt-landlord-questions-rental-linger/story Scott Pruitt's landlord in controversial deal wasn't allowed to rent out room: Officials], [[ABC News]], Matthew Mosk, Benjamin Siegel and Stephanie Ebbs, April 6, 2018. Retrieved April 9, 2018.</ref> Pruitt's landlords gave him notice that he would have to move by July 2017, and changed the locks on the doors when he departed.<ref>[[Eliana Johnson]], [https://www.politico.com/story/2018/04/06/pruitt-was-the-kato-kaelin-of-capitol-hill-505658 Lobbyist couple had to change the locks on Pruitt], ''Politico'' (April 6, 2018).</ref> On June 30, 2018, four days before Pruitt's resignation, the New York Times reported that Minoli had referred multiple allegations against Pruitt to the EPA's Inspector General, including aspects of Pruitt's use of the Hart's condo.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/30/climate/pruitt-epa-ethics.html The E.P.A.\u2019s Ethics Officer Once Defended Pruitt. Then He Urged Investigations, Lipton, Eric (June 30, 2018)</ref>\n\nThe townhouse rented by Pruitt was also used as a Republican fundraising hub while he and his adult daughter were living there.<ref name=\"Daily Beast\"/> The Harts hosted a fundraising reception for Pruitt in 2014 (at the expense of $1,616.43) and contributed $1750 to Pruitt's campaign for Oklahoma attorney general over the period 2010\u20132012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/03/30/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-white-house/index.html|title=White House frustrated with EPA's Pruitt|authors=Dan Merica, Pamela Brown, Jim Acosta & Rene Marsh|publisher=CNN|date=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, 2017, Pruitt's security detail, unable to reach him, broke down the front door to the apartment building to gain entrance. The EPA eventually reimbursed the condo association $2,460 for the necessary repairs.<ref name=\"Cheniere2\" />\n\nIn July 2018, it was reported that Pruitt had requested help from two EPA aides, both of whom were attorneys, in a dispute that he had with a separate landlord.<ref name=\":32\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/pruitt-aides-reveal-new-details-of-his-spending-and-management-at-epa/2018/07/02/71b87384-7aec-11e8-80be-6d32e182a3bc_story.html|title=Pruitt aides reveal new details of his spending and management at EPA |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=July 2, 2018 |first=Juliet |last=Eilperin |first2=Josh |last2=Dawsey |first3=Brady |last3=Dennis |archive-date=July 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703012152/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/pruitt-aides-reveal-new-details-of-his-spending-and-management-at-epa/2018/07/02/71b87384-7aec-11e8-80be-6d32e182a3bc_story.html?utm_term=.204e235cc1ec}}</ref>\n\n==== No-bid contract to Republican opposition research firm ====\n\nIn December 2017, [[Definers Public Affairs]] was paid $120,000 in a [[no-bid contract]] from the EPA for services which included searching for \"resistance figures\" opposing Pruitt's agenda.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/15/us/politics/epa-scott-pruitt-foia.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |title=Executive at Consultancy Hired by E.P.A. Scrutinized Agency Employees Critical of Trump |first=Eric |last=Lipton |first2=Lisa |last2=Friedman |date=December 15, 2017 |access-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usaspending.gov/transparency/Pages/TransactionDetails.aspx?RecordID=53D2AF0E-B566-47BB-8EB4-728DAC00CEB7&AwardID=59978626&AwardType=C \n|title=DEFINERS CORP EP18H000025 |publisher=[[Office of Management and Budget]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171216051716/https://www.usaspending.gov/transparency/Pages/TransactionDetails.aspx?RecordID=53D2AF0E-B566-47BB-8EB4-728DAC00CEB7&AwardID=59978626&AwardType=C |archive-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"MJ\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2017/12/the-epa-hired-a-major-republican-opposition-research-firm-to-track-press-activity/|title=The EPA Hired a Major Republican Opposition Research Firm to Track Press Activity |magazine=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|first=Rebecca|last=Leber |first2=Andy|last2=Kroll |first3=Russ |last3=Choma |date=December 15, 2017 |access-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref> During the bid Definers listed erroneously itself as a \"[[small business|small]] [[disadvantaged business enterprise|disadvantaged business]]\", a preferred designation corrected after Definers received the contract.<ref>Eric Lipton & Lisa Friedman, [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/19/climate/epa-definers-public-affairs-contract.html Consulting Firm Whose Staff Scoured E.P.A. Employees' Emails Loses Media Contract], ''New York Times'' (December 19, 2017).</ref> Definers cancelled the contract following a public backlash.<ref>{{cite news |quote=The Republican media monitoring firm Definers Public Affairs canceled its $120,000 contract with Environmental Protection Agency after a media backlash because of the company's links to GOP opposition research firm America Rising. |title=GOP firm ends controversial media monitoring contract with EPA |first=Emily |last=Holden |date=December 19, 2017 |work=[[Politico]] |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2017/12/19/definers-public-affairs-epa-contract-304980}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=PounderFile |number=943172637202755584 |date=December 19, 2017 |title=Below is my statement regarding the EPA contract ...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/12/19/epa-to-end-controversial-contract-with-conservative-media-monitoring-firm/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |first=Brady |last=Dennis |date=December 19, 2017 |title=EPA to end controversial contract with conservative 'media monitoring' firm |quote=But an agency spokesman confirmed Tuesday that the EPA and the company had agreed to terminate the contract. In a separate conversation, the company's president, Joe Pounder, said the decision was a mutual one. \"Definers offered EPA a better and more efficient news clipping service that would give EPA's employees real-time news at a lower cost than what previous administrations paid for more antiquated clipping services,\" Pounder said in an emailed statement. \"But it's become clear this will become a distraction.\"}}</ref>\n\n==== Oklahoma associates' hiring and salary increase ====\nIn April 2018, it became known that Pruitt had raised the salaries of two of his closest aides whom he'd brought from Oklahoma, despite rejection of the submitted increases by the White House.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/04/pruitt-epa/557123/|title=Scott Pruitt Bypassed the White House to Give Big Raises to Favorite Aides|last=Meyer|first=Elaina Plott and Robinson|work=The Atlantic|access-date=April 3, 2018}}</ref> Pruitt sought to increase the salary from $107,435 to $164,200 for one aide and from $86,460 to $114,590 for the other. The provision was intended to allow the EPA administrator to hire specialists into unique roles in especially stressed offices.<ref name=\":17\" /> Instead, Pruitt circumvented the process by using a provision of the Safe Drinking Water Act which allowed him to autonomously determine the salaries for the two aides.<ref name=\":17\" /> The compensation of the two staffers was substantially higher than the salaries of staff in similar positions in the Obama administration.<ref name=\":17\" /> The method of raising their pay also allowed both to avoid signing ethics pledges meant to deter conflicts of interest, an issue raised by Democratic Senators [[Tom Carper]] and [[Sheldon Whitehouse]] for consideration of an investigation.<ref name=\":17\" />  While Pruitt claimed in an April 4, 2018 televised interview with Fox News correspondent Ed Henry that he didn't know anything about the raises to his two close aides, the Washington Post reported on April 5, 2018 that two EPA officials and a White House official told The Post that Pruitt instructed staff to award substantial pay boosts to both women, who had worked in different roles for him in Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eilperin|first1=Juliet|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|last3=Dawsey|first3=Josh|title=Scott Pruitt's Job in jeopardy amid expanding ethics issues|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/04/05/top-epa-ethics-official-says-he-lacked-key-facts-about-pruitts-condo-rental/|accessdate=April 6, 2018|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPruitt hired former Oklahoma banker Albert Kelly to head the [[Superfund]] program, which is responsible for cleaning up the nation's most contaminated land.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2017/12/28/scott-pruitt-failed-banker-running-epa-superfund-program/|title=Banned From the Banking Industry for Life, a Scott Pruitt Friend Finds a New Home at the EPA|last=Lerner|first=Sharon|date=December 28, 2017|website=The Intercept|access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eenews.net/stories/1060059295|title=EPA: Pruitt's Superfund point man penalized by banking regulators|publisher=[[E&E News]]|access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.apnews.com/649fb04caa70402789c667792019a0f5|title=Adviser to EPA chief cited for federal banking violations|work=AP News|access-date=December 28, 2017}}</ref> Kelly completely lacked any experience with environmental issues, and had just received a lifetime ban from working in [[banking]], his career until then, due to \"unfitness to serve\".<ref name=\":10\" /> The [[Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation]] (FDIC) also fined him $125,000 and said he had made loans that harmed the bank.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.americanbanker.com/news/epa-official-banned-from-banking-rep-elijah-cummings-wants-answers|title=EPA official banned from banking; congressman wants answers|author=Rob Blackwell|date=September 21, 2017|access-date=January 21, 2017}}</ref> Kelly had a long-standing financial relationship with Pruitt as head of a [[SpiritBank Event Center#Ownership|SpiritBank]], which held extensive outstanding loans to Pruitt.<ref name=\":10\" /> In his new position, Kelly earned $172,100 a year.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n==== Reactions from ex-EPA administrators ====\nFormer EPA Administrators have been critical of Pruitt's tenure. [[William Ruckelshaus]], the first and fifth EPA Administrator under [[Richard Nixon]] and [[Ronald Reagan]] respectively, characterized Pruitt as disbelieving of \"the mission of the agency\" while believing that the EPA was \"over-regulating\". Ruckelshaus accused Pruitt of having an \"ideological approach ... that affects the large contributors in his party in Oklahoma\". Ruckelshaus also described the ideological opposition to the scientific consensus on climate change as a national \"threat\", and that \"lives will be sacrificed\" with further inaction.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kaufman|first1=Alexander|title=EPA Chief Under Nixon And Reagan: GOP's Climate Denial Is 'Killing Everything'|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/ruckelshaus-climate-gop_us_5a6b96f1e4b06e25326783fd|work=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=January 29, 2018}}</ref> Ruckelshaus has also criticized Pruitt for lacking transparency.<ref name=transparency>{{cite news|last1=Ruckelshaus|first1=William|title=Pruitt is turning his back on transparency at the EPA|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/pruitt-is-turning-his-back-on-transparency-at-the-epa/2017/11/01/cd2c1b84-bd88-11e7-8444-a0d4f04b89eb_story.html|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=January 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Carol Browner]], EPA Administrator under [[Bill Clinton]], said, \"Under Pruitt, what they're doing is conscientiously tearing the place down.\" [[Christine Todd Whitman]], EPA Administrator under [[George W. Bush]], said it was \"mindless\" that under Pruitt, policies enacted under Obama were being reversed regardless of their merits or shortcomings. [[Gina McCarthy]], EPA Administrator under Barack Obama, said that Pruitt's EPA had created a \"wealth of uncertainty\" in undoing so many regulations because businesses would not know if they should \"take rules seriously\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kaufman|first1=Alexander|title=Scott Pruitt's First Year Set The EPA Back Anywhere From A Few Years To 3 Decades|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/pruitt-one-year_us_5a610a5ce4b074ce7a06beb4|work=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=January 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe EPA's overhaul of their website under Pruitt has also drawn flak from former administrators. Whitman has argued that the website's credibility was damaged, and that \"undermining science means there is no basis on which to act based on fact, which is dangerous.\" McCarthy described the EPA's website changes as \"censoring scientific data\" and carrying out \"a dangerous assault on public health safeguards that protect all Americans.\"<ref name=TIMEwebsite/>\n\n==== Establishment of legal defense fund ====\nAt a May 16, 2018 hearing of the [[Senate Appropriations Committee]]'s Interior, Environment and Related Agencies Appropriations Subcommittee, Pruitt affirmed that he had set up a legal defense fund that will enable \"friends, allies, lobbyists and others\" to  help defray any legal costs Pruitt may face due to numerous charges of spending and ethics violations.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cama |first1=Timothy |title=Pruitt confirms he has a legal defense fund |url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/387943-pruitt-confirms-he-has-a-legal-defense-fund |website=The Hill |accessdate=July 5, 2018}}</ref> Maryland Democrat [[Chris Van Hollen]] asked Pruitt if sources of donations would be publicly disclosed. Pruitt agreed they would be and added that his attorney would be working with the [[General Accounting Office]] (GAO) to assure the fund met legal requirements. The subcommittee's ranking member, New Mexico's [[Tom Udall]] remarked, \"It's hard to know what to begin with today.  Every day, there seems to be a new scandal, and you at the center of it.\" Subcommittee Chairwoman, Alaska Senator [[Lisa Murkowski]] stated said she's \"constantly asked\" about his management of the agency, continuing, \"I think there are legitimate questions that need to be answered.\"<ref name=Senate />\n\n==== Special favors for family members ====\nIn June 2018, it was revealed that Pruitt had used his official position at the EPA to line up special favors and business opportunities for his wife and daughter.<ref name=\":28\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/scott-pruitt-enlisted-an-epa-aide-to-help-his-wife-find-a-job--at-chick-fil-a/2018/06/05/b798e4e4-5eac-11e8-9ee3-49d6d4814c4c_story.html|title=Scott Pruitt enlisted an EPA aide to help his wife find a job \u2014 with Chick-fil-A|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=June 5, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=June 5, 2018|last2=Dennis|first2=Brady|issn=0190-8286|last3=Dawsey|first3=Josh}}</ref><ref name=\":31\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/15/us/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-aides.html|title=For Pruitt Aides, the Boss's Personal Life Was Part of the Job|access-date=June 15, 2018}}</ref> Three months after being sworn in as head of the EPA, Pruitt's scheduler sent an email to [[Dan Cathy]], the chairman, president, and CEO of fast-food chain [[Chick-fil-A]], about \"a potential business opportunity\".<ref name=\":28\" /> The business interest entailed granting Pruitt's wife, Marlyn, license to set up a Chick-fil-A franchise. Pruitt also approached the CEO of Concordia, a New York nonprofit organization which sets up summits to build [[public-private partnership]]s, about hiring his wife to plan summits.<ref name=\":28\" /> Pruitt also had a top EPA aide contact major Republican donors for job opportunities for his wife.<ref name=\":30\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/epa-chief-scott-pruitt-tapped-aide-donors-to-help-wife-land-job-at-conservative-group/2018/06/13/f54c87fa-6db1-11e8-afd5-778aca903bbe_story.html|title=EPA chief Scott Pruitt tapped aide, donors to help wife land job at conservative group|last=Eilperin|first=Juliet|date=June 13, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=June 13, 2018|last2=Dawsey|first2=Josh|issn=0190-8286|last3=Dennis|first3=Brady|last4=Boburg|first4=Shawn}}</ref> When one such donor said that it would be a conflict of interest to offer a job to Pruitt's wife, Pruitt continued to solicit the donor's help in finding job opportunities.<ref name=\":30\" /> The [[Judicial Crisis Network]] ended up hiring Pruitt's wife temporarily after [[Leonard Leo]], executive vice president of the [[Federalist Society]], sent the group her resume.<ref name=\":30\" /> Federal ethics law prohibits public officials from using their public positions for private gain.<ref name=\":28\" /> Pruitt instructed one of his aides to contact the Republican Attorneys General Association about finding a job for his wife, but the aide refused as she considered it an ethics violation.<ref name=\":32\" />\n\nPruitt also instructed at least three EPA aides to help secure a White House internship for his daughter, after which she received such a post.<ref name=\":31\" /> Pruitt obtained Rose Bowl tickets via the head of a firm, Saxum, doing public affairs work for energy companies. Representative [[Elijah Cummings]] requested documents pertaining to assistance Pruitt received to obtain the prized tickets. The Oklahoma City-based firm represented Plains All American Pipeline LP, which has a pending petition at the EPA to permit discharge of hydrostatic test water from a Corpus Christi, Texas, pipeline.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-15/epa-s-pruitt-got-rose-bowl-tickets-democrats-want-to-know-how EPA's Pruitt Snagged Rose Bowl Tickets. Democrats Ask How], ''[[Bloomberg News]]'', Terrence Dopp and Jennifer A. Dlouhy, June 15, 2018. Retrieved June 25, 2018.</ref> Pruitt's security detail accompanied the family to the game.<ref>[https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/30/politics/epa-pruitt-travel-whitehouse-rose-bowl-disneyland/index.html Senator: Pruitt security included Disneyland, Rose Bowl trips], ''[[CNN]]'', Sara Ganim and Rene Marsh, April 3, 2018. Retrieved June 25, 2018.</ref>\n\n=== Resignation ===\nFollowing the assorted ethics and management scandals, Pruitt announced on July 5, 2018, he would be resigning effective July 6. Following Pruitt's resignation, EPA Deputy Administrator [[Andrew R. Wheeler]] became acting administrator.<ref name=globe2018>Brady Dennis & Juliet Eilperin, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/trump-epa-head-steps-down-after-wave-of-ethics-management-scandals/2018/07/05/39f4251a-6813-11e8-bea7-c8eb28bc52b1_story.html Scott Pruitt steps down as EPA head after ethics, management scandals], ''Washington Post'' (July 5, 2018).</ref> The EPA  Office of Inspector General continued its probes of Pruitt after the resignation,<ref>Jory Heckman, [https://federalnewsradio.com/agency-oversight/2018/07/epa-inspector-general-to-continue-pruitt-related-audits-following-resignation/ EPA inspector general to continue Pruitt-related audits following resignation], Federal News Radio (July 12, 2018).</ref><ref>Juana Summers & Sara Ganim, [https://www.cnn.com/politics/live-news/epa-scott-pruitt-resigns/h_1800b39181f455f35e5fb22025f500b4 The EPA's inspector general will continue investigating Pruitt], CNN (July 5, 2018).</ref> but in November 2018 the EPA Inspector General's Office closed two probes as inconclusive because it could not interview Pruitt after his resignation.<ref name=\"Inconclusive\">Juliet Eilperin & Brady Dennis, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/energy-environment/2018/11/29/epa-watchdog-closes-two-probes-into-scott-pruitts-conduct-citing-his-resignation/ EPA watchdog closes two probes into Scott Pruitt's conduct, citing his resignation], ''Washington Post'' (November 29, 2018).</ref> (The office lacks the ability to [[subpoena]] officials who have resigned.<ref name=\"Inconclusive\"/>)\n\n== Post-EPA career ==\nAfter resigning from the EPA, Pruitt has sought to establish an energy consulting business. He promoted overseas coal sales for coal baron [[Joe Craft|Joseph Craft III]]. ''The Washington Post'' reported that Pruitt had meetings with officials from the same industries that he regulated while EPA head. Pruitt's lawyer said that Pruitt had not and would not violate the five-year ban on lobbying the EPA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2018/national/scott-pruitt-epa-expenses/|title=Scott Pruitt: After the High Life, a Job Hunt|author=Juliet Eilperin, Brady Dennis & Josh Dawsey|date=December 28, 2018|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> On April 18, 2019 Pruitt registered as a compensated lobbyist with the Indiana Lobby Registration Commission specifying that he anticipates his lobbying efforts would relate to energy and natural resources. His sole client listed is connected to Sunrise Coal, which operates four coal mines in the state at the time of the filing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Biesecker |first1=Michael |title=Ex-EPA chief Pruitt registers as energy lobbyist in Indiana |url=https://www.apnews.com/a1318acdfba24a0cb02f045254cd2419 |accessdate=20 April 2019 |agency=The Associated Press |date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Pruitt's environmental views ==\n{{See also|Environmental policy of the Donald Trump administration}}\n[[File:Re (32295962460).jpg|thumb|Resist Trump Rally, NYC, 2017]]\n\n=== Rejection of scientific consensus on climate change ===\nPruitt rejects the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus on climate change]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/washington/la-na-essential-washington-updates-1489078393-htmlstory.html|title=House committee advances Obamacare repeal plan but GOP opposition remains|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=March 9, 2017|issn=0458-3035}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/09/us/politics/epa-scott-pruitt-global-warming.html|title=E.P.A. Chief Doubts Consensus View of Climate Change|last=Davenport|first=Coral|date=March 9, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 9, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt2\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/07/us/politics/scott-pruitt-epa-trump.html | title=Trump Picks Scott Pruitt, Climate Change Denialist, to Lead E.P.A. | date=December 7, 2016 |access-date=April 30, 2017| work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2017/mar/10/scott-pruitt/epa-head-scott-pruitt-says-carbon-dioxide-not-prim/|title=EPA head Pruitt: CO2 is not a main cause of global warming|work=@politifact|access-date=June 2, 2017}}</ref>  During his January 18, 2017, confirmation hearing to be EPA Administrator, he said that \"the climate is changing, and human activity contributes to that in some manner\".<ref name=\"theclimate\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/01/18/bernie-sanders-to-scott-pruitt-why-is-the-climate-changing/?|title=Bernie Sanders to Scott Pruitt: Why is the climate changing?|date=January 18, 2017|work=[[The Washington Post]]|last2=Erickson|first2=Andee|last1=Mooney|first1=Chris|accessdate=January 20, 2017}}</ref> In March 2017, Pruitt said that he does not believe that human activities, specifically carbon dioxide emissions, are a primary contributor to climate change, a view which is in contradiction with the scientific consensus.<ref name=\"cnbc\"/><ref name=\":4\">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4696658/scott-pruitt-epa-carbon-climate-change/|title=EPA Chief Says Carbon Isn't a 'Primary Contributor' to Climate Change|website=Time|access-date=April 30, 2017 |date=March 9, 2017 |first=Justin |last=Worland}}</ref> On June 2, 2017, Pruitt acknowledged that global warming is occurring, and that \"human activity contributes to it in some manner.\" However he added \"Measuring with precision, from my perspective, the degree of human contribution is very challenging.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=David Smith in Washington |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/jun/02/us-paris-climate-deal-epa-chief-scott-pruitt |title=US has nothing to apologize for on climate change, says defiant EPA chief &#124; Environment |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=July 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Pruitt and [[Luther Strange]] authored an [[op-ed]] in the ''[[National Review]]'' criticizing a group of Democratic attorneys general for investigating [[ExxonMobil]] in connection with the [[ExxonMobil climate change controversy]]. In part, Pruitt and Strange wrote:\n\n<blockquote>[The global warming] debate is far from settled. [[Scientific opinion on climate change|Scientists continue to disagree]] about the degree and extent of [[global warming]] and its connection to the actions of mankind. That debate should be encouraged \u2014 in classrooms, public forums, and the halls of Congress. It should not be silenced with threats of prosecution. Dissent is not a crime.<ref name=Strange>{{cite news| url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/435470/climate-change-attorneys-general | title=The Climate-Change Gang | newspaper=[[National Review]] | accessdate=December 8, 2016}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAdditionally, Pruitt joined 12 other Republican attorneys general in writing a letter that stated that \"If it is possible to minimize the risks of climate change, then the same goes for exaggeration. If minimization is fraud, exaggeration is fraud.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/jun/16/gop-ags-dems-climate-alarmists-can-be-prosecuted/?platform=hootsuite|title=GOP AGs warn Dems that if climate skeptics can be prosecuted for 'fraud,' so can alarmists|last=Richardson|first=Valerie|newspaper=The Washington Times|access-date=February 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAccording to one person, Pruitt suggested debates to President Trump, stating to him, \"We can show that most scientists don't even believe in global warming.\" Trump was said to have liked the idea, but the concept was rejected by White House Chief of Staff [[John F. Kelly]], according to several officials involved in the discussions.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/for-pruitt-gaining-trumps-favor--and-keeping-it--came-through-fierce-allegiance/2018/06/16/84025ccc-6fe2-11e8-bd50-b80389a4e569_story.html For Pruitt, gaining Trump's favor \u2014 and keeping it \u2014 came through fierce allegiance], ''[[Washington Post]]'', Josh Dawsey, Juliet Eilperin and Brady Dennis, June 16, 2018. Retrieved June 18, 2018.</ref>\n\nA May 2017 study in ''[[Scientific Reports]]'' examined Pruitt's claim that \"over the past two decades satellite data indicates there has been a leveling off of warming.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Santer|first=Benjamin D.|last2=Solomon|first2=Susan|last3=Wentz|first3=Frank J.|last4=Fu|first4=Qiang|last5=Po-Chedley|first5=Stephen|last6=Mears|first6=Carl|last7=Painter|first7=Jeffrey F.|last8=Bonfils|first8=C\u00e9line|date=May 24, 2017|title=Tropospheric Warming Over The Past Two Decades|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=7|issue=1|pages=2336|doi=10.1038/s41598-017-02520-7|pmid=28539644|issn=2045-2322|pmc=5443760}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/epa-scott-pruitt-climate-change-denial-scientific-paper-nature-scientific-reports-a7754871.html|title=Scientists publish entire study taking down Trump environment chief's climate change views|date=May 25, 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=May 25, 2017}}</ref> The study found that the claim was false: \"[[Satellite temperature measurements]] do not support the claim of a \"leveling off of warming\" over the past two decades\".<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIn an interview with Las Vegas television station [[KSNV]], Pruitt, in contradiction to the EPA's own scientific position, argued that an increase in global temperate might not be \"a bad thing\" and that it is \"arrogant\" to say what \"the ideal surface temperature should be in the year 2100.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/02/07/scott-pruitt-asks-if-global-warming-necessarily-is-a-bad-thing/|title=EPA's Scott Pruitt asks whether global warming 'necessarily is a bad thing'|first1=Dino|last1=Grandoni|first2=Brady|last2=Dennis|first3=Chris|last3=Mooney|date=February 8, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=June 6, 2018|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref>\n\nPruitt opposes the [[Paris Agreement]].<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|author=Glenn Kessler|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2017/04/14/epa-administrator-scott-pruitts-claim-that-china-and-india-have-no-obligations-until-2030-under-the-paris-accord/|title=Fact Checker: EPA Administrator Scott Pruitt's claim that China and India have 'no obligations' until 2030 under the Paris Accord|website=Washington Post|date=April 4, 2017}}</ref> He has incorrectly asserted that [[China]] and [[India]] have \"no obligations\" until 2030 under the Paris Agreement.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite news|author=Vanessa Schipani|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2017/03/pruitt-paris-accord/|title=Pruitt on the Paris Accord|work=[[FactCheck.org]]|publisher=Annenberg Public Policy Center|date=March 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Lawsuits against the Environmental Protection Agency===\nPruitt has described himself as \"a leading advocate against the EPA's activist agenda.\"<ref name=\"WashPo8Dec\"/> Upon taking office as Oklahoma Attorney General, Pruitt established a \"federalism unit\" to fight \"unwarranted regulation and systematic overreach\" by the federal government, a first-of-its-kind.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/epa-nominee-has-long-sought-to-scale-back-the-federal-government/2017/01/17/d81c3034-d6b0-11e6-9f9f-5cdb4b7f8dd7_story.html|title=EPA nominee has long sought to scale back the federal government|website=Washington Post|access-date=February 28, 2017}}</ref> [[Andrew P. Miller|Andrew Miller]], a former Democratic attorney general of Virginia who later represented energy companies, recalled a meeting in 2013 with Pruitt and other attorneys general: \"[t]he issue of the day was discussed in a way that allowed Attorney General Pruitt, to his credit, to emerge as one of the leaders, if not the leader with respect to energy issues among the attorneys general.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eenews.net/stories/1060048547|title=EPA: How Scott Pruitt rode a wave of federalism to power|website=www.eenews.net|access-date=February 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs Oklahoma Attorney General, Pruitt sued the EPA at least 14 times. Regulated industry companies or trade associations who were financial donors to Pruitt's political causes were co-parties in 13 of these 14 cases. These cases included suing to block the anti-climate change [[Clean Power Plan]] four times, challenging [[mercury pollution]] limits twice, [[ozone]] pollution limits once, fighting the [[Cross-State Air Pollution Rule]] and the [[Clean Water Rule]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Pruitt v. EPA: 14 Challenges of EPA Rules by the Oklahoma Attorney General|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/01/14/us/politics/document-Pruitt-v-EPA-a-Compilation-of-Oklahoma-14.html?_r=0|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 5, 2017}}</ref> as well as fighting regulations on [[methane emissions]].<ref name=\"WashPo8Dec\" /> Pruitt stated at his Senate confirmation hearing in January 2017 that the EPA has an \"obligation\" to regulate carbon dioxide in accordance with a 2007 Supreme Court case and 2009 EPA decision establishing carbon emissions as a threat to public health.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/314970-five-takeaways-from-pruitts-epa-hearing|title=Five takeaways from Pruitt's EPA hearing|last=Swanson|first=Ian|date=January 18, 2017|work=TheHill|access-date=February 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nUnder Pruitt, Oklahoma sued the EPA and lost on challenges to the EPA's [[regulatory authority]] over mercury and other [[toxin]]s, as well as pollutants responsible for creating regional atmospheric [[haze]]. It challenged the manner in which EPA sued unrelated entities and for what Pruitt termed the agency's \"sue and settle\" practices. Oklahoma further sued and lost after the EPA declined to provide extensive records in a FOIA lawsuit, a request the federal judge hearing the case found to be overly broad and economically burdensome.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.readfrontier.org/stories/pruitt-failed-to-follow-law-on-reporting-outside-attorney-contracts |title=Frontier exclusive: Pruitt failed to follow law on reporting outside attorney contracts |work=[[The Frontier (website)|The Frontier]] |first1=Ziva |last1=Branstetter |first2=Kassie |last2=McClung |date=January 11, 2017 |accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Rulemaking===\nOn March 28, 2017, President Trump signed an [[executive order]] directing Pruitt to rescind the [[Clean Power Plan]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|last2=Rubin|first2=Alissa J.|title=TRUMP SIGNS RULE TO BLOCK EFFORTS ON AIDING CLIMATE \u2013 Executive Order Is Intended to Dismantle Obama Plan on Curbing Carbon|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/28/climate/trump-executive-order-climate-change.html|accessdate=May 8, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 29, 2017|page=A1}}</ref> Pruitt has refused to rescind EPA's endangerment finding which determined that [[carbon dioxide]] emissions threaten [[public health]], prompting criticism from some Trump supporters.  Pruitt has stated that a move to rescind would almost certainly be overturned by the courts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=Scott Pruitt Faces Anger From Right Over E.P.A. Finding He Won't Fight|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/12/climate/scott-pruitt-epa-endangerment-finding.html|accessdate=May 9, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 13, 2017|page=A15}}</ref>  On October 10, 2017, Pruitt issued a [[notice of proposed rulemaking]] to repeal the Clean Power Plan.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|last2=Plumer|first2=Brad|title=E.P.A. Announces Repeal of Major Obama-Era Carbon Emissions Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/09/climate/clean-power-plan.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=October 10, 2017|page=A1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=EPA Takes Another Step To Advance President Trump's America First Strategy, Proposes Repeal Of \"Clean Power Plan\"|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-takes-another-step-advance-president-trumps-america-first-strategy-proposes-repeal|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=October 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn June 27, 2017, Pruitt released a proposal to rescind the [[Clean Water Rule]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=E.P.A. Moves to Rescind Contested Water Pollution Regulation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/27/climate/epa-rescind-water-pollution-regulation.html|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 4, 2017|page=D2}}</ref>  On January 31, 2018, Pruitt finalized repeal of the Clean Water Rule.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=E.P.A. Blocks Obama-Era Clean Water Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/31/climate/trump-water-wotus.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=February 1, 2018|page=A16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=EPA and Army Finalize \"Waters of the United States\" Applicability Date {{!}} US EPA|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-and-army-finalize-waters-united-states-applicability-date|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=January 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 1, 2018, Pruitt issued a proposed rule to relax regulation of [[coal ash]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dennis|first1=Brady|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|title=EPA moves to overhaul Obama-era safeguards on coal ash waste|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2018/03/01/epa-moves-to-overhaul-obama-era-safeguards-on-coal-ash-waste/|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The Washington Post|date=March 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=EPA Proposes First of Two Rules to Amend Coal Ash Disposal Regulations, Saving Up To $100M Per Year in Compliance Costs|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-proposes-first-two-rules-amend-coal-ash-disposal-regulations-saving-100m-year|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=March 1, 2018}}</ref>  Pruitt has finalized a rule postponing new [[effluent guidelines]] on power plants.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Buford|first1=Talia|title=What It's Like Inside the Trump Administration's Regulatory Rollback at the EPA|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/inside-trump-regulatory-rollback-epa|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=[[ProPublica]]|date=December 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=EPA Finalizes Rule to Postpone Steam Electric Power Plant Effluent Guidelines Rule|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-finalizes-rule-postpone-steam-electric-power-plant-effluent-guidelines-rule|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=September 13, 2017}}</ref>  Pruitt has rejected a proposed rule to require [[underground mining (hard rock)|hard rock miners]] to guarantee they can pay [[mine reclamation]] costs.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Preston|first1=Benjamin|title=Trump EPA rule change exploits taxpayers for mine cleanup, critics say|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/dec/17/donald-trump-epa-mining-pollution-rules|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=EPA Determines Risks from Hardrock Mining Industry Minimal and No Need for Additional Federal Requirements|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-determines-risks-hardrock-mining-industry-minimal-and-no-need-additional-federal|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=December 1, 2017}}</ref>  Pruitt has agreed to allow permitting to proceed for the [[Pebble Mine]] on [[Bristol Bay]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schlossberg|first1=Tatiana|title=In Reversal, E.P.A. Eases Path for a Mine Near Alaska's Bristol Bay|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/12/climate/in-reversal-epa-eases-path-for-a-mine-near-alaskas-bristol-bay.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=May 13, 2017|page=A17}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Pruitt announced that he would delay designating which areas met new [[National Ambient Air Quality Standards]] for [[ozone]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=EPA to Extend Deadline for 2015 Ozone NAAQS Area Designations|url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-extend-deadline-2015-ozone-naaqs-area-designations|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA Press Office|date=June 6, 2017}}</ref>  In August 2017, Pruitt said he would reverse that decision after being sued by 16 state Attorneys General.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=E.P.A. Reverses Course on Ozone Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/03/climate/epa-reverses-course-on-ozone-rule.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=August 4, 2017|page=A11}}</ref>  In March 2018, Pruitt was finally ordered to do so by U.S. District Judge [[Haywood Stirling Gilliam Jr.]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cama|first1=Timothy|title=Court: EPA broke law with smog rule delay|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/377977-court-epa-broke-law-with-smog-rule-delay|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=March 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Press Release|title=Attorney General Becerra Secures Ruling Requiring EPA to Implement Life-Saving Clean Air Protections|url=https://oag.ca.gov/news/press-releases/attorney-general-becerra-secures-ruling-requiring-epa-implement-life-saving|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=California Office of the Attorney General|date=March 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Pruitt began reconsidering new [[United States emission standards|car emissions standards]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grandoni|first1=Dino|title=Trump officials begin review of Obama emissions standards for cars|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/08/10/trump-officials-begin-review-of-obama-emissions-standards-for-cars/|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=Washington Post|date=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Midterm Evaluation of Light-Duty Vehicle Greenhouse Gas Emissions Standards for Model Years 2022\u20132025|url=https://www.epa.gov/regulations-emissions-vehicles-and-engines/midterm-evaluation-light-duty-vehicle-greenhouse-gas|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA}}</ref>  Pruitt has been planning to reduce federally mandated [[corporate average fuel economy]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|last2=Tabuchi|first2=Hiroko|title=E.P.A. Prepares to Roll Back Rules Requiring Cars to Be Cleaner and More Efficient|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/29/climate/epa-cafe-auto-pollution-rollback.html|accessdate=March 30, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=March 30, 2018|page=A1}}</ref>  Pruitt has proposed to repeal heightened emissions standards on \"glider trucks\", which are [[semi-trailer truck]]s that have new bodies but old engines.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipton|first1=Eric|title=How $225,000 Can Help Secure a Pollution Loophole at Trump's E.P.A.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/15/us/politics/epa-pollution-loophole-glider-trucks.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=February 15, 2018|page=A1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Regulations for Greenhouse Gas Emissions from Commercial Trucks & Buses|url=https://www.epa.gov/regulations-emissions-vehicles-and-engines/regulations-greenhouse-gas-emissions-commercial-trucks|accessdate=March 28, 2018|agency=EPA}}</ref>  Pruitt had requested [[public comment]] on reductions to the [[Renewable Fuel Standard (United States)|Renewable Fuel Standard]] after being encouraged to do so by [[Carl Icahn]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tabuchi|first1=Hiroko|title=Score One for Corn: In Battle Over Biofuel, a Rare Setback for Big Oil|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/30/climate/trump-ethanol-biofuel.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=December 1, 2017|page=B3}}</ref>  Pruitt has since traveled to Iowa twice to promote the repeal of the Clean Water Rule and to promise support of [[corn ethanol]] production.<ref name=nyt18march18/>\n\nPruitt has indefinitely postponed regulations of [[methylene chloride]], [[N-methylpyrrolidone]], and [[trichloroethylene]] that had been called for by the [[Frank R. Lautenberg Chemical Safety for the 21st Century Act]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kaplan|first1=Sheila|title=E.P.A. Delays Bans on Uses of Hazardous Chemicals|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/19/health/epa-toxic-chemicals.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=December 20, 2017|page=A16}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the EPA, [[lead poisoning]] is the number one environmental health threat in the U.S. for children ages 6 and younger.  No new standards have been set since 2001, though it is agreed that the old standards need to be updated.  In December 2017, after Pruitt requested six more years to regulate lead levels, a divided federal appeals court issued a writ of [[mandamus]] ordering Pruitt to regulate lead within the next 90 days.  The Court called the lead paint risks for children \"severe\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=E.P.A. Wanted Years to Study Lead Paint Rule. It Got 90 Days.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/27/us/epa-lead-paint.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=December 28, 2017|page=A10}}</ref>\n\n====Chlorpyrifos ban====\n\n[[Chlorpyrifos]] is a pesticide that is used to kill a number of pests on crops, animals, and in buildings.  In a 2016 report, EPA scientists were not able to find any level of exposure to chlorpyrifos that was safe.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rabin|first1=Roni Caryn|title=A Strong Case Against a Pesticide Does Not Faze E.P.A. Under Trump|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/15/health/pesticides-epa-chlorpyrifos-scott-pruitt.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=May 16, 2017|page=D1}}</ref> The EPA 2016 report states in part \"...this assessment indicates that dietary risks from food alone are of concern ...\"  The report also states that previous published risk assessments for \"chlorpyrifos may not provide a [sufficient] ... human health risk assessment given the potential for neurodevelopmental outcomes.\"<ref name=\"EPA-HQ-OPP-2015-0653\">{{cite web|last1=Drew|first1=Danette|title=Chlorpyrifos Revised Human Health Risk Assessment (2016)|url=https://www.regulations.gov/contentStreamer?documentId=EPA-HQ-OPP-2015-0653-0454&contentType=pdf|website=Regulations.gov|publisher=EPA|accessdate=April 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, 2017, Pruitt denied an administrative petition by the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] and the [[Pesticide Action Network North America]] to ban [[chlorpyrifos]], explaining \"we are returning to using sound science in decision-making \u2013 rather than predetermined results\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=[[Eric Lipton]]|title=E.P.A. Chief, Rejecting Agency's Science, Chooses Not to Ban Insecticide|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/29/us/politics/epa-insecticide-chlorpyrifos.html|accessdate=May 8, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 30, 2017|page=A21}}</ref> On April 5, 2017, [[Earthjustice]] sued the EPA, again demanding that the pesticide be banned.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rabin|first1=Roni Caryn|title=Advocacy Groups Ask for Ban on Common Pesticide|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/05/well/advocacy-groups-ask-for-ban-on-common-pesticide.html|accessdate=May 8, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 6, 2017|page=A14}}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Academy of Pediatrics]] responded to the administration's decision, saying they were \"deeply alarmed\" by Pruitt's decision to allow the [[pesticide]]'s continued use.<ref name=AP30june17>{{cite news|title=EPA chief met with Dow Chemical CEO before deciding not to ban toxic pesticide|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-epa-pesticide-dow-20170627-story.html|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=June 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAsked in April whether he had met with [[Dow Chemical Company]] (who manufactures chlorpyrifos) executives or lobbyists before his decision, an EPA spokesman replied: \"We have had no meetings with Dow on this topic.\" In June, after several [[Freedom of Information Act]] requests, the EPA released a copy of Pruitt's March meeting schedule which showed that a meeting had been scheduled with Dow CEO [[Andrew Liveris]] at a hotel in [[Houston, Texas]], on March 9, 2017.<ref name=AP30june17/>  Internal documents show Pruitt worked closely with the [[American Farm Bureau Federation]] to permit continuation of the pesticide's use.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipton|first1=Eric|last2=Rabin|first2=Roni Caryn|title=E.P.A. Promised 'a New Day' for the Agriculture Industry, Documents Reveal|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/18/us/politics/epa-agriculture-industry.html|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|date=August 19, 2017|page=A13}}</ref>\n\n====Methane rule====\nOn March 22, 2017, Pruitt had dinner at the Washington [[Old Post Office Pavilion|Trump International Hotel]] with 45 board members of the [[American Petroleum Institute]], where they asked for relief from a new regulation of [[methane]] leaks from their wells, which the industry estimates could cost it over $170 million.<ref name=NYT2july17>{{cite news|last1=Davenport|first1=Coral|title=E.P.A. CHIEF VOIDS OBAMA-ERA RULES IN BLAZING START \u2014 COUNSELED BY INDUSTRY \u2014 Pruitt's Decision-Making Keeps Staff's Experts Largely Sidelined|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/01/us/politics/trump-epa-chief-pruitt-regulations-climate-change.html|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 2, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>  On June 13, Pruitt ordered the rule delayed for two years.<ref name=NYT2july17/>  On July 3, Judges [[David S. Tatel]] and [[Robert L. Wilkins]] of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] vacated that delay, finding Pruitt's order was \"arbitrary\" and \"capricious\" and in violation of the [[Clean Air Act (United States)|Clean Air Act]], over the dissent of Judge [[Janice Rogers Brown]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Lisa|title=Court Blocks E.P.A. Effort to Suspend Obama-Era Methane Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/03/climate/court-blocks-epa-effort-to-suspend-obama-era-methane-rule.html|accessdate=July 5, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 4, 2017|page=A1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=''Clean Air Council v. Pruitt'', No. 17-1145 (D.C. Cir. 2017)|url=http://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/cadc/17-1145/17-1145-2017-07-03.html|website=Justia Law|accessdate=July 5, 2017}}</ref>  In October 2017, a federal magistrate judge ordered the administration to reimpose regulations it had repealed on methane [[gas flare]]s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lipton|first1=Eric|title=Courts Thwart Administration's Effort to Rescind Obama-Era Environmental Regulations|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/06/climate/trump-administration-environmental-regulations.html|work=The New York Times|date=October 7, 2017|page=A1}}</ref>\n\n===PFOS and PFOA study publication withheld===\nJanuary 2018 emails between the EPA, the White House, and the [[Department of Health and Human Services]] (DHHS) made public following a [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] request showed that the White House and EPA under Pruitt decided to halt the publication of a study done by the DHHS [[Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry]] (ATSDR). The study, an assessment of the chemical pollutants [[PFOS]] and [[PFOA]], showed that the substances present dangers to human health at far lower levels than the EPA previously deemed safe. An email from a White House official said that the administration feared a \"potential public relations nightmare.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Snider|first1=Annie|title=White House, EPA headed off chemical pollution study|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/14/emails-white-house-interfered-with-science-study-536950|website=Politico|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe withholding of the study prompted widespread criticism from congressional Democrats, as well as at least three congressional Republicans. These critics called upon the EPA to provide answers to questions about suppression of scientific assessments on chemical pollution of water.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|last1=Snider|first1=Annie|title=EPA move on chemical study may trip up Pruitt|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/16/pruitt-chemical-study-epa-590947|website=Politico|accessdate=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPruitt conceded that his agency should take \"concrete action\" related to chemicals like PFAS, but testified that he was unaware of any delay in the release of the study.<ref name=Senate>[https://www.eenews.net/greenwire/2018/05/16/stories/1060081889 Legal defense fund in place \u2014 Pruitt], ''[[E&E News]]'', Kevin Bogardus, May 16, 2018. Retrieved May 17, 2018.</ref> At a May 2018 \"leadership summit\" on PFOA, PFOS and related chemicals attended by Pruitt,<ref name=\"auto\"/> some reporters were barred from attending, including those from  ''[[Politico]]'' (which first reported on the release of the emails), [[CNN]], and [[E&E News]] (which writes on environmental issues). An [[Associated Press]] correspondent, Ellen Knickmeyer, was physically ejected from the meeting room, and U.S. Representative [[Dan Kildee]] of Michigan, who represents a district dealing with the [[Flint water crisis]], said that a member of his staff was barred from the meeting. Kildee wrote to the EPA's inspector general to ask whether any open meetings laws were violated.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|last1=Ebbs|first1=Stephanie|title=EPA continues to face questions about blocking public from chemicals summit|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/epa-criticized-blocking-reporters-chemicals-summit/story?id=55362966|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=May 24, 2018}}</ref> An EPA spokesman asserted that the summit was not subject to the [[Federal Advisory Committee Act]].<ref>[https://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/for-second-day-reporters-barred-from-epa-event-on-toxic-chemicals For Second Day, Reporters Barred From EPA Event On Toxic Chemicals], ''[[Talking Points Memo]]'', Matt Shuham, May 23, 2018. Retrieved May 24, 2018.</ref> Senator [[Tom Udall]], in response, wrote a letter to Pruitt stating, \"This intimidation of journalists seeking to cover a federal official presiding over important policy-making is un-American and unacceptable. ... Clean drinking water is a public health issue that does not belong behind closed doors.\"<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nPruitt married Marlyn Lloyd in 1990, at [[Southeast Christian Church (Louisville, Kentucky)|Southeast Christian Church]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"LHL\"/> They have two children: daughter McKenna and son Cade.<ref name=everything>{{cite news | title=Everything You Need to Know About Donald Trump's Pick to Head EPA, Scott Pruitt | url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/donald-trumps-pick-head-epa-scott-pruitt/story?id=44046481 | publisher=[[ABC News]] | first1=Veronica |last1=Stracqualursi | date=December 8, 2016 |accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nPruitt is [[Southern Baptist Convention|Southern Baptist]]. According to the Oklahoma Office of Attorney General, the Pruitts are members of the First Baptist Church of [[Broken Arrow, Oklahoma|Broken Arrow]], where Pruitt served as a [[deacon]]. Pruitt was a trustee at the [[Southern Baptist Theological Seminary]]. He expressed his views regularly on the radio in Tulsa, including advocating for passage of constitutional amendments to ban abortion and gay marriage, and objecting to what he feels is the suppression of majority religious beliefs.<ref name=Baptist>[https://baptistnews.com/article/trump-picks-a-southern-baptist-to-run-the-epa/#.WYsrx-mQzIV Trump picks climate-change denier, Southern Baptist to run the EPA], ''[[Baptist News Global]]'', Bob Allen, December 28, 2016. Retrieved March 19, 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.politico.com/story/2018/03/02/scott-pruitt-epa-evolution-theory-abortion-gay-marriage-433284 Pruitt tapes revealed: Evolution's a 'theory,' 'majority' religions under attack], ''[[Politico]]'', Emily Holden & Alex Guillen, March 2, 2018. Retrieved April 11, 2018.</ref>   In 2005, Pruitt told a radio interviewer that there are not \"sufficient scientific facts to [[creation-evolution controversy|establish]] the theory of [[evolution]].\"<ref name=newyorker2april18/>\n\n==Electoral history==\n'''''November 4, 2014, general election results for Attorney General'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Candidates\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|'''Scott Pruitt'''\n|Republican Party\n|n/a\n|100.00%\n|}\n\n'''''November 2, 2010, general election results for Attorney General'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Candidates\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|'''Scott Pruitt'''\n|Republican Party\n|666,407\n|65.11%\n|-\n|Jim Priest\n|Democratic Party\n|357,162\n|34.89%\n|}\n\n'''''July 27, 2010, Republican primary election results for Attorney General'''''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Candidates\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|'''Scott Pruitt'''\n|Republican Party\n|134,335\n|56.05%\n|-\n|Ryan Leonard\n|Republican Party\n|105,343\n|43.95%\n|}\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:95%; text-align:right;\"\n|+''August 22, 2006 Republican primary election results for Lt. Governor''\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Candidates\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|Party\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|Votes\n!  style=\"background:#e9e9e9; text-align:center;\"|%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|'''Todd Hiett'''\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|'''66,220'''\n|'''50.92%'''\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n|align=left|Scott Pruitt\n|align=center|[[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]\n|63,817\n|49.08%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" colspan=\"6\"|Source:<ref>{{cite web | title=Lieutenant Governor Republican Runoff Primary Election